eBattlefieldProfiles/Hartsville%20to%20Johnsonville.pdf CWSAC report update]\n;Attribution\n* {{CWR}}\n\n{{Indiana Military Units in the Civil War}}\n{{Indiana in the Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1862]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1865]]\n[[Category:Indiana Civil War regiments]]\n[[Category:1862 establishments in Indiana]]\n", "name_user": "Hhfjbaker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/72nd_Indiana_Infantry_Regiment"}
{"title_page": "Timeline of the 21st century", "text_new": "{{about||other timelines of modern history|Timelines of modern history|future timelines|Timelines of the future}}\n\n{{Centurybox|21}}\nThis is a '''timeline of the [[21st century]]'''.\n\n== [[2000s (decade)|2000s]] ==\n<!--The 21st century began in 2001, not 2000 -->\n=== [[2001]] ===\n*[[September 11 attacks]]: [[Al-Qaeda]] terrorists crash planes into the twin towers of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] in [[New York City]], and [[the Pentagon]] in [[Washington, DC]]. A fourth plane is downed on the outskirts of [[Stonycreek Township, Somerset County, Pennsylvania|Stonycreek Township, PA.]] 2,996 people die in the attacks.\n*An [[2001 Gujarat earthquake|earthquake]] strikes [[Gujarat]], [[India]] on [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]], resulting in more than 20,000 deaths.\n*The [[War on Terror]] is declared by [[George W. Bush|President Bush]], in response to [[September 11 attacks|9/11]].\n*The [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|United States invades Afghanistan]] and topples the [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan|Taliban regime]]. The result is a [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|long-term war.]]\n*The [[African Union]] is founded in [[Addis Ababa]], [[Ethiopia]].\n*During an [[Argentine economic crisis (1999\u20132002)|economic crisis in Argentina,]] the government effectively [[Corralito|freezes all bank accounts]] for twelve months which [[December 2001 riots in Argentina|leads to riots]] and President [[Fernando de la R\u00faa|de la R\u00faa]]'s resignation from office. There are five \"presidents\" in less than a month.\n*President [[Joseph Estrada]] of the [[Philippines]] is [[Second EDSA Revolution|ousted]].\n*[[China and the World Trade Organization|China becomes]] a member of the [[World Trade Organization]].\n*[[Wikipedia]] is launched.\n*Eleven members of the royal family of [[Nepal]], including the king and queen, are killed in the [[Nepalese royal massacre]]. The perpetrator, Crown Prince [[Dipendra of Nepal|Dipendra]], wounds himself and dies three days later.\n*[[Dos Palmas kidnappings]]: Twenty tourists are abducted by the [[Abu Sayyaf]] Group terrorists from a popular island resort in the Philippines.\n*Deaths of [[Aaliyah]], [[George Harrison]], [[Death of Dale Earnhardt|Dale Earnhardt]], [[Jack Lemmon]], [[Carroll O'Connor]], [[Anthony Quinn]] and [[John Lee Hooker]].\n\n=== [[2002]] ===\n*[[2002 Bali bombings]].\n*The [[Euro]] first enters circulation.\n*[[2002 Gujarat riots|Riots and mass killings]] in the Indian state of [[Gujarat]] leave 1,044 dead.\n*Israel starts [[Operation Defensive Shield]] in the West Bank in response to a wave of [[List of Palestinian suicide attacks #2000s|Palestinian suicide attacks]].\n*Construction of the [[Israeli West Bank barrier]] begins.\n*Chechen rebels [[Moscow theater hostage crisis|seize theater]] in Moscow.\n*Establishment of the [[International Criminal Court]].\n*America demands [[Iraq disarmament crisis|Iraq allow unfettered access to weapons inspectors]].\n*[[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] is established.\n*[[Algerian Civil War]] ends.\n*[[Beltway sniper attacks]].\n*Independence of [[East Timor]].\n*[[First Ivorian Civil War]] begins.\n*[[Brazil]] wins the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].\n*[[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Golden Jubilee]] of [[Elizabeth II]].\n*Deaths of [[Lisa Lopes]], [[Waylon Jennings]], [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|The Queen Mother]], [[Ted Williams]], [[Chuck Jones]], [[Dudley Moore]], [[Milton Berle]], [[Dave Thomas (businessman)|Dave Thomas]], [[Eppie Lederer|Ann Landers]], [[Johnny Unitas]] and [[Bill Blass]].\n\n=== [[2003]] ===\n*The United States [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invades Iraq]] and topples [[Saddam Hussein]], triggering [[Protests against the Iraq War|worldwide protests]] and an [[Iraq War|8 year war]].\n*[[War in Darfur]] begins.\n*The [[Human Genome Project]] is completed.\n*[[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] becomes [[President of Brazil]]\n*[[Second Congo War]] ends with more than 5 million dead.\n*[[Second Liberian Civil War]] ends.\n*[[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']] is [[Space Shuttle Columbia disaster|destroyed on re-entry]].\n*[[Rose Revolution]] in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].\n*The last [[Volkswagen Beetle]] is made in Mexico, after 65 years in production.\n*[[2003 Marriott Hotel bombing]].\n*The first [[six-party talks]], involving [[South Korea|South]] and [[North Korea]], the [[United States]], [[China]], [[Japan]] and [[Russia]].\n*Deaths of [[Johnny Cash]], [[June Carter Cash]], [[Fred Rogers]], [[John Ritter]], [[Katharine Hepburn]], [[Bob Hope]], [[Barry White]], [[Maurice Gibb]], [[Gregory Peck]], [[Charles Bronson]], [[Althea Gibson]] and [[David Brinkley]].\n\n=== [[2004]] ===\n*[[Enlargement of NATO|NATO]] and [[2004 enlargement of the European Union|the European Union]] incorporates most of the former Eastern Bloc.\n*[[Facebook]] formed by [[Mark Zuckerberg]].\n*[[Union of South American Nations]] formed.\n*[[Madrid train bombings]].\n*The [[Second Battle of Fallujah]] is the deadliest American battle since Vietnam, killing 95 troops.\n*[[Orange Revolution]] in [[Ukraine]].\n*[[Beslan school hostage crisis]].\n*[[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|Boxing Day Tsunami]] occurs in [[Indian Ocean]], leading to the deaths of 230,000.\n*First surface images of [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]].\n*[[2004 SuperFerry 14 bombing]].\n*Deaths of [[Death and State Funeral of Ronald Reagan|Ronald Reagan]], [[Ray Charles]], [[Marlon Brando]], [[Julia Child]], [[Rick James]], [[Christopher Reeve]], [[Rodney Dangerfield]], [[Estee Lauder (businesswoman)|Estee Lauder]], [[Richard Avedon]], [[Pat Tillman]], [[Jerry Orbach]], [[Janet Leigh]] and [[Yasser Arafat]].\n\n=== [[2005]] ===\n*[[Irish Republican Army]] end military campaign in Northern Ireland.\n*[[7/7 attacks]] on [[London Underground]].\n*[[Angela Merkel]] becomes Germany's first female [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor]].\n*[[Tulip Revolution]] in [[Kyrgyzstan]].\n*[[Second Intifada]] ends.\n*[[Israeli disengagement from Gaza|Israel withdraws from Gaza]].\n*[[Cedar Revolution]] in [[Lebanon]] triggered by the [[assassination of Rafic Hariri]].\n*[[Second Sudanese Civil War]] ends.\n*[[Hurricane Katrina]] kills 1,836 people in the [[Gulf of Mexico]] (particularly in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]).\n*80,000 are killed in [[2005 Kashmir earthquake|an earthquake]] in [[Kashmir]].\n*The [[Kyoto Protocol]] comes into effect.\n*[[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] becomes [[President of Iran]].\n*[[Pope Benedict XVI|Benedict XVI]] becomes Pope.\n*[[Michael E. Brown]] discovers [[Eris (dwarf planet)|Eris]].\n*[[YouTube]] formed by [[Jawed Karim]], [[Chad Hurley]] and [[Steve Chen]].\n*[[2005 Valentine's Day bombings]].\n*[[2005 World Summit]].\n*Deaths of [[Funeral of Pope John Paul II|Pope John Paul II]], [[Rosa Parks]], [[Richard Pryor]], [[Johnny Carson]], [[Luther Vandross]], [[Pat Morita]], [[Arthur Miller]], [[Anne Bancroft]], [[Johnnie Cochran]], [[Peter Jennings]], [[Don Adams]] and [[William Rehnquist]].\n*[[Reddit]] is founded by [[Steve Huffman]], [[Aaron Swartz]] and [[Alexis Ohanian]]\n\n=== [[2006]] ===\n*[[2006 Montenegrin independence referendum|Independence of Montenegro]].\n*[[2006 Lebanon War]].\n*[[2006 Mumbai train bombings|Mumbai bombings]].\n*[[Comprehensive Peace Accord]] ends the [[Nepalese Civil War]].\n*[[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]] becomes President of [[Liberia]], and thus Africa's first elected female head of state.\n*The [[International Astronomical Union]] creates [[IAU definition of planet|the first formal definition of a planet]], and excludes [[Pluto]] from the list.\n*[[Execution of Saddam Hussein]].\n*The [[Baiji]], the Yangtze [[river dolphin]], becomes [[functionally extinct]].\n*[[Twitter]] is launched.\n*Former Russian security agent [[Poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko|Alexander Litvinenko dies from poisoning]] in the UK.\n*[[Nintendo]] launches the [[Wii]].\n*[[2006 Southern Leyte mudslide]].\n*Deaths of [[Steve Irwin]], [[James Brown]], [[Don Knotts]], [[Death and state funeral of Gerald Ford|Gerald Ford]], [[Coretta Scott King]], [[Peter Boyle]], [[Lou Rawls]], [[Betty Friedan]], [[Kirby Puckett]], [[Aaron Spelling]], [[Robert Altman]], [[Gordon Parks]] and [[Ed Bradley]].\n*[[Italy national football team|Italy]] wins [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 Fifa World Cup]]\n\n=== [[2007]] ===\n*[[Saffron Revolution|Anti-government protests]] in [[Myanmar]] suppressed by ruling [[Military junta|junta]].\n*[[2007\u20132008 world food price crisis|Spike in food prices]] and [[subprime crisis]] help trigger [[Late-2000s recession|global recession]].\n*[[Assassination of Benazir Bhutto]].\n*[[Gordon Brown]] becomes [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]].\n*[[Hrant Dink]], assassinated in Istanbul on January 19, 2007 by Og\u00fcn Samast, a 17-year-old Turkish nationalist. Dink was shot three times in the head and died instantly. Photographs of the assassin flanked by smiling Turkish police and [[gendarmerie]], posing with the killer side by side in front of the Turkish flag, surfaced. The photos sparked a scandal in Turkey, prompting a spate of investigations and the removal from office of those involved. This case is one of the most hideous act of both anti-Christian and anti-Armenian sentiment in Turkey.  \n*[[First Ivorian Civil War]] ends.\n*[[Virginia Tech shooting]].\n*Deaths of [[Anna Nicole Smith]], [[Luciano Pavarotti]], [[Ike Turner]], [[Evel Knievel]], [[Lady Bird Johnson]], [[Death and state funeral of Boris Yeltsin|Boris Yeltsin]], [[Merv Griffin]], [[Kurt Vonnegut]], [[Tammy Faye Messner]], [[Phil Rizzuto]], [[Jerry Falwell]], [[Liz Claiborne]] and [[Norman Mailer]].\n\n=== [[2008]] ===\n*Stock markets [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|plunge]] around the world, signalling the start of the [[Great Recession]].\n*End of Monarchy in [[Nepal]].\n*[[Barack Obama]] is elected as [[President of the United States]].\n*[[Cyclone Nargis]] kills 133,000 in [[Myanmar]].\n*[[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]] begins.\n*[[2008 South Ossetia war]].\n*[[Kosovo]] [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|declares independence]], to mixed reaction.\n*Iraqi forces [[Battle of Basra (2008)|crack down]] on [[Muqtada al Sadr]]'s Mahdi forces in Basra and Sadr City.\n*[[2008 Mumbai attacks]].\n*The [[Large Hadron Collider]] is completed as the world's largest and most powerful [[particle collider]].\n*[[MV Princess of the Stars|Sinking of MV Princess of the Stars]].\n*Deaths of [[Heath Ledger]], [[Bernie Mac]], [[Paul Newman]], [[Estelle Getty]], [[Yves Saint Laurent (designer)|Yves Saint Laurent]], [[Sir Edmund Hillary]], [[George Carlin]], [[Charlton Heston]], [[Roy Scheider]], [[Isaac Hayes]], [[Bettie Page]], [[Bo Diddley]], [[Michael Crichton]], [[Tim Russert]], [[Sydney Pollack]], [[Mark Felt]] and [[William F. Buckley]].\n\n=== [[2009]] ===\n*[[Bitcoin]] is launched.\n*[[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]] ends while [[Gaza blockade]] continues.\n*[[Sri Lankan Civil War]] ends.\n*[[2009\u20132010 Iranian election protests|Election protests]] begin in Iran.\n*[[Second Chechen War]] ends.\n*[[Boko Haram]] rebellion begins in Nigeria.\n*Construction of the world's tallest skyscraper [[Burj Khalifa]] is completed in [[Dubai]].\n*Formation of [[BRICS]] economic bloc.\n*[[Treaty of Lisbon]] ratified.\n*[[2009 flu pandemic]].\n*Former [[President of the Philippines|Philippine president]] [[Corazon Aquino]] [[Death and funeral of Corazon Aquino|dies]] of [[colorectal cancer|colon cancer]].\n*[[Typhoon Ketsana]] causes widespread damages in the Philippines.\n*[[Maguindanao massacre|58 people are abducted and killed]] in the province of [[Maguindanao]].\n*Deaths of [[Death of Michael Jackson|Michael Jackson]], [[Patrick Swayze]], [[Brittany Murphy]], [[Billy Mays]], [[Farrah Fawcett]], [[Bea Arthur]], [[Natasha Richardson]], [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]], [[Les Paul]], [[Ted Kennedy]], [[Walter Cronkite]], [[Dom DeLuise]], [[David Carradine]], [[Ed McMahon]], [[John Updike]], [[Mary Travers]], [[Paul Harvey]], [[Oral Roberts]] and [[Frank McCourt]].\n\n== [[2010s]] ==\n\n=== [[2010]] ===\n*After the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]], [[David Cameron]] becomes [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]].\n*[[Benigno Aquino III]] is elected as the [[List of Presidents of the Philippines|15th]] [[President of the Philippines]].\n*A [[2010 Haiti earthquake|7.0 magnitude earthquake]] in [[Haiti]] kills 230,000.\n*The threat of [[Greece]] [[Greek government-debt crisis|defaulting on its debts]] triggers the [[2010 European sovereign debt crisis|European sovereign debt crisis]] and [[Republic of Ireland]]'s [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|financial crisis]].\n*The [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill|largest oil spill in US history]] occurs in the [[Gulf of Mexico]].\n*[[North Korea]] [[Bombardment of Yeonpyeong|shells]] the island of [[Yeonpyeong]].\n*Burmese political prisoner [[Aung San Suu Kyi]] is released from house arrest.\n*The FIFA world cup is [[2010 FIFA World Cup|held]] in Africa for the first time.\n*[[2010 Moscow Metro bombings]].\n*[[Arab Spring]] starts.\n*[[Kyrgyz Revolution of 2010]].\n*[[2010 Nigerien coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n*The President of Poland, [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]], is among 96 killed when their airplane [[2010 Polish Air Force Tu-154 crash|crashes]] in Smolensk on April 10.\n*The [[Burj Khalifa]] located in [[Dubai]] opened to the public and stood as the [[tallest structure in the world]], standing at 829.8 m (2,722&nbsp;ft).\n*[[Dilma Rousseff]] is elected as the first female president of [[Brazil]].\n*[[Instagram]] is launched.\n*[[Manila hostage crisis]].\n*[[2010 Colombia\u2013Venezuela diplomatic crisis]].\n*[[2010 Copiap\u00f3 mining accident]].\n*[[2010 eruptions of Eyjafjallaj\u00f6kull]].\n*[[Julia Gillard]] is elected [[Prime Minister of Australia]].\n*Deaths of [[Paul Gray]], [[Corey Haim]], [[Gary Coleman]], [[Rue McClanahan]], [[Alexander McQueen]], [[Lena Horne]], [[Leslie Nielsen]], [[Tony Curtis]], [[George Steinbrenner]], [[Dennis Hopper]], [[J.D. Salinger]] and [[Tom Bosley]].\n\n=== [[2011]] ===\n*Independence of [[South Sudan]].\n*Snapchat launched.\n*February [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|Christchurch earthquake]] kills 185 and injures 2,000.\n*[[Arab Spring]]: [[Tunisian revolution|revolutions in Tunisia]], [[2011 Egyptian revolution|Egypt]] [[2011 Libyan civil war|and Libya]] follow, as well as [[2011 Yemeni uprising|uprisings in Yemen]] [[2011 Bahraini uprising|and Bahrain]], and protests in several other Arab countries.\n*[[Syrian civil war]] begins.\n*[[Second Ivorian Civil War]].\n*[[Occupy movement]] inspires worldwide protests.\n*[[News International phone hacking scandal]].\n*A [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|9.0 earthquake]] in [[Japan]] triggers a tsunami and the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|meltdown of the Fukushima Nuclear Power Plant]].\n*The [[Danyang\u2013Kunshan Grand Bridge]], the world's longest, opens in China.\n*[[Second Ivorian Civil War]] ends with the arrest of former president [[Laurent Gbagbo]].\n*[[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq|Iraq War ends]].\n*[[2011 England riots|Riots flare across England]].\n*Bombings occur [[2011 Domodedovo International Airport bombing|In Russia]] [[2011 Mogadishu bombing|and Somalia]].\n*[[World population]] reaches [[Day of 7 Billion|7 Billion]].\n*[[2011 Sindh floods|Floods in Pakistan]], [[2011 Thailand floods|Thailand]] [[Tropical Storm Washi (2011)|and the Philippines]] kill roughly 2,500 people.\n*[[Death of Osama bin Laden|Osama bin Laden is shot dead]] by [[United States Navy SEALs]] in Pakistan.\n*[[2011 Norway attacks]].\n*[[Death of Muammar Gaddafi|Muammar Gaddafi is captured and killed]] during the [[Battle of Sirte (2011)|Battle of Sirte]].\n*[[Wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton]].\n*[[Space Shuttle program]] is officially ended.\n*[[Amazon rainforest|Amazon Rainforest]] and [[Amazon River|River]], [[H\u1ea1 Long Bay]], [[Jeju Island]], [[Iguaz\u00fa Falls]], [[Puerto Princesa Subterranean River National Park|Puerto Princesa Underground River]], [[Komodo Island]] and [[Table Mountain]] were named as the world's [[New7Wonders of Nature]].\n*Deaths of [[Steve Jobs]], [[Death and state funeral of Kim Jong-il|Kim Jong-il]], [[Amy Winehouse]], [[Elizabeth Taylor]], [[Peter Falk]], [[Betty Ford]], [[Randy Savage]] and [[Andy Rooney]].\n\n=== [[2012]] ===\n*[[2012 Northern Mali conflict|Northern Mali conflict]], the [[National Movement for the Liberation of Azawad|MNLA]] declares [[Azawad]] an independent state.\n*[[Yemen]]i President [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]] steps down.\n*[[2012 Benghazi attack]] leads to the death of US ambassador [[J. Christopher Stevens]].\n*[[Shenouda III]], [[Pope of the Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria]], departs; [[Pope Tawadros II of Alexandria|Tawadros II]] succeeds him.\n*The [[Higgs boson]] is discovered.\n*Vladimir Putin is elected president of Russia for the third time.\n*[[Hurricane Sandy]] kills 209 people in North America, while [[Typhoon Bopha]] kills over 1,600 in the [[Philippines]].\n*Skydiver [[Felix Baumgartner]] becomes the first person to [[Sound barrier#Breaking the sound barrier as a human projectile|break the sound barrier without a vehicle]].\n*[[Central African Republic conflict (2012\u201313)|Conflict begins]] in the [[Central African Republic]].\n*[[2012 United Nations Climate Change Conference|UN Climate Change Conference]] agrees to extend the [[Kyoto Protocol]] until 2020.\n*[[Israel]] launches [[Operation Pillar of Defense]] against the [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]]-governed [[Gaza Strip]].\n*[[2012 Guinea-Bissau coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n*The US rover, [[Curiosity (rover)|Curiosity]], takes a selfie on Mars.\n*[[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]].\n*[[2012 Aurora shooting]].\n*[[Costa Concordia disaster]].\n*[[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]].\n*[[Impeachment of Renato Corona]].\n*Pakistani Taliban attempt to assassinate outspoken schoolgirl [[Malala Yousafzai]].\n*Deaths of [[Whitney Houston]], [[Neil Armstrong]], [[Andy Griffith]], [[Dick Clark]], [[Donna Summer]], [[Etta James]], [[Robin Gibb]], [[Sally Ride]], [[Michael Clarke Duncan]], [[Sherman Hemsley]], [[Ernest Borgnine]], [[Larry Hagman]], [[Davy Jones (musician)|Davy Jones]], [[Jack Klugman]], [[Phyllis Diller]], [[Ray Bradbury]], [[Gore Vidal]], [[Maurice Sendak]], [[Mike Wallace]], [[Adam Yauch]], [[Dave Brubeck]], [[Dolphy]], [[Yitzhak Shamir]], [[Jesse Robredo]] and [[Don Cornelius]].\n\n=== [[2013]] ===\n*The French military intervenes in the [[Northern Mali conflict]].\n*[[Chelyabinsk meteor]].\n*[[Resignation of Pope Benedict XVI|Pope Benedict XVI resigns]] and [[Pope Francis]] becomes Pope.\n*[[Boston Marathon bombings|Terrorist attacks occur]] in [[Boston]] [[Westgate shopping mall attack|and Nairobi]].\n*The [[2013 Savar building collapse|Rana Plaza collapses]] in [[Bangladesh]].\n*[[Edward Snowden]] releases classified documents concerning [[Global surveillance disclosure|mass surveillance by the NSA]].\n*[[President of Egypt]] [[Mohamed Morsi]] [[2013 Egyptian coup d'\u00e9tat|is deposed by the military in a coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n*[[Croatia]] becomes a member of the [[European Union]].\n*The [[Euromaidan]] protest begins in [[Ukraine]].\n*[[Ghouta chemical attack|A chemical attack in Ghouta, Syria]] is blamed on President [[Bashar al-Assad]].\n*A [[2013 Bohol earthquake|7.2 magnitude earthquake]] in [[Bohol]], kills 222.\n*[[Typhoon Haiyan]] kills nearly 6,150 people in the [[Philippines]] and [[Vietnam]].\n*[[South Sudanese conflict (2013\u2013present)|Conflict begins in South Sudan]].\n*[[Uruguay]] becomes [[Legality of cannabis by country|the first country to fully legalize cannabis]].\n*End of [[2012\u20132013 Cypriot financial crisis]].\n*[[Zamboanga City crisis]].\n*[[Kiss nightclub fire]].\n*[[2013 Alberta floods]].\n*Deaths of [[Death of Nelson Mandela|Nelson Mandela]], [[Death and funeral of Margaret Thatcher|Margaret Thatcher]], [[Death of Hugo Ch\u00e1vez|Hugo Chavez]], [[Paul Walker]], [[Cory Monteith]], [[James Gandolfini]], [[Annette Funicello]], [[Peter O'Toole]], [[Roger Ebert]], [[Tom Clancy]], [[Jean Stapleton]], [[Lou Reed]] and [[George Jones]].\n\n=== [[2014]] ===\n*[[Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa|The worst Ebola epidemic in recorded history]] occurs in West Africa, infecting nearly 30,000 people and resulting in the deaths of 11,000+.\n*[[Euromaidan]] protest in Ukraine sparks a [[2014 Ukrainian Revolution|revolution]] and the overthrow of [[Viktor Yanukovych]], leading to Russia's [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation of Crimea]] and the [[War in Donbass]].\n*[[Malaysia Airlines Flight 370]] disappears from radar while en route to Beijing from Kuala Lumpur on March 8. There were 239 people on board.\n*A [[2014 Thai coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]] in Thailand overthrows the caretaker government.\n*King [[Juan Carlos I]] of Spain abdicates; his son becomes [[King Felipe VI]].\n*[[Indonesia AirAsia Flight 8501]] crashes into the Java Sea, while [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 17]] is shot down over Ukraine and [[Air Alg\u00e9rie Flight 5017]] is downed in [[Mali]].\n*[[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan]] [[2014 Peshawar school massacre|kill]] over 130 students in [[Pakistan]].\n*[[Israel]] launches [[Operation Protective Edge|an assault]] on the [[Gaza Strip]] in response to [[2014 kidnapping and murder of Israeli teenagers|tit-for-tat]] [[Kidnapping and murder of Mohammed Abu Khdeir|murder-kidnappings]], leading to the deaths of 71 Israelis and 2,100 Palestinians.\n*[[Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] begins [[Northern Iraq offensive (June 2014)|its offensive in northern Iraq]], leading to [[2014 American-led intervention in Iraq|intervention in Iraq]] [[American-led intervention in Syria|and Syria]] by a US-led coalition.\n*[[Second Libyan Civil War]] begins.\n*The [[Rosetta (spacecraft)|''Rosetta'' spacecraft]]'s ''[[Philae (spacecraft)|Philae]]'' probe becomes the first to successfully land on [[67P/Churyumov-Gerasimenko|a comet]].\n*The [[shooting of Michael Brown|shooting]] of African-American teenager Michael Brown by police leads to [[Ferguson unrest|violent unrest]] in [[Ferguson, Missouri]].\n*[[Joko Widodo]] is [[2014 Indonesian presidential election|elected]] [[President of Indonesia]].\n*[[Sinking of MV Sewol]].\n*[[Doha]], [[Durban]], [[Havana]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[La Paz]] and [[Vigan]] were chosen as the world's [[New7Wonders Cities]].\n*Deaths of [[Robin Williams]], [[Maya Angelou]], [[Shirley Temple]], [[Joan Rivers]], [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]], [[Mickey Rooney]], [[James Garner]], [[Casey Kasem]], [[Lauren Bacall]], [[Richard Attenborough]], [[Harold Ramis]], [[Pete Seeger]], [[Joe Cocker]], [[Oscar de la Renta]], [[Ariel Sharon]], and [[Mike Nichols]].\n\n=== [[2015]] ===\n*Five [[former Soviet Union]] countries form the [[Eurasian Economic Union]].\n*A [[November 2015 Paris attacks|series of terrorist attacks]] [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|occur in Paris]].\n*[[Boko Haram]] perpetrates [[2015 Baga massacre|a massacre of over 2,000 people]] in [[Baga, Nigeria]], and allies itself with [[Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]].\n*[[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] perpetrates a [[Garissa University College attack|a mass shooting]] in [[Kenya]], killing 148.\n*[[Houthis]] [[Houthi takeover in Yemen|overthrow the government in Yemen]], triggering [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|a military response]] by [[Saudi Arabia]].\n*[[April 2015 Nepal earthquake|A series]] [[May 2015 Nepal earthquake|of earthquakes]] [[October 2015 Hindu Kush earthquake|in the Himalayas]] kills over 10,000 people.\n*[[ISIL]] claims responsibility for the [[Koban\u00ee massacre]] in [[Syria]], the [[2015 Sousse attacks|Sousse attacks in Tunisia]], [[2015 Kuwait mosque bombing|a mosque bombing in Kuwait]], the [[2015 Suru\u00e7 bombing|Suru\u00e7 bombing]] in [[Turkey]], multiple bombings in [[2015 Beirut bombings|Beirut]] and a massacre in [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris]], as well as [[Metrojet Flight 9268|the bombing of a Russian Airliner]] over Egypt. They also inspire a [[2015 San Bernardino attack|mass shooting in San Bernardino, California]].\n*[[Turkish involvement in the Syrian Civil War|Turkey and]] [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War|Russia intervene]] in the [[Syrian Civil War]].\n*The heads of [[China]] and [[Taiwan]] [[2015 Ma\u2013Xi meeting|meet for the first time]], while the [[United States]] and [[Cuba]] resume diplomatic relations.\n*[[2015 United Nations Climate Change Conference|195 nations agree]] to lower [[carbon emissions]].\n*[[Water on Mars|Liquid water]] is found on [[Mars]].\n*First close-up images of [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] and [[Pluto]].\n*[[Charleston church shooting]].\n*[[Pope Francis's visit to the Philippines]].\n*[[100th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide]] was commemorated worldwide. The event occurred in light of continued Armenian Genocide denial by Turkey.\n*[[Mamasapano clash]].\n*[[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Manny Pacquiao]].\n*[[Kentex slipper factory fire]].\n*[[Pia Wurtzbach|Pia Alonzo Wurtzbach]] of the [[Philippines]] is crowned [[Miss Universe 2015]].\n*The opposition-led [[Democratic Unity Roundtable]] wins the most seats in the [[2015 Venezuelan parliamentary election]], defeating the [[United Socialist Party of Venezuela]] for the first time since the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] was established in 1999.\n*Deaths of [[Leonard Nimoy]], [[B.B. King]], [[Christopher Lee]], [[Yogi Berra]], [[Bob Simon]], [[Frank Gifford]], [[John Forbes Nash Jr.]], [[Wes Craven]], [[Ben E. King]], [[Jackie Collins]], [[Natalie Cole]], [[Lesley Gore]], [[Sam Simon]], [[Scott Weiland]], [[Omar Sharif]], [[Dick Van Patten]], [[Death and state funeral of Lee Kuan Yew|Lee Kuan Yew]], [[Lemmy Kilmister]] and [[James Horner]].\n\n=== [[2016]] ===\n*[[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic|An outbreak of the Zika virus]] is linked to a cluster of cases of [[microcephaly]].\n*The [[United Nations]] lifts sanctions on [[Iran]] in recognition of its dismantling of its [[Iran and weapons of mass destruction|nuclear program]].\n*[[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] claims responsibility for [[2016 Brussels bombings|a series of bombings in Brussels]], [[2016 Atat\u00fcrk Airport attack|a massacre]] at [[Istanbul]]'s [[Ataturk Airport]] and car ramming attacks in [[2016 Nice attack|Nice]] and [[2016 Berlin attack|Berlin]].\n*The [[Gotthard Base Tunnel]], the world's longest [[railway tunnel]], is completed.\n*The people of the [[United Kingdom]] vote narrowly to [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|leave the European Union]]; [[Theresa May]] becomes [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]].\n*[[Donald Trump]] is [[2016 United States presidential election|elected]] [[President of the United States]].\n*The [[Colombia]]n government signs a [[Colombian peace process|peace deal]] with [[FARC]] despite losing [[2016 Colombian peace agreement referendum|a referendum]].\n*[[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan|United States troops withdraw from Afghanistan]] after 15 years.\n*The [[President of Brazil]], [[Dilma Rousseff]], is impeached.\n*The government of Turkey begins a [[2016 Turkish purges|series of purges]] in reaction to a [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|failed coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]].\n*[[Rodrigo Duterte]] becomes [[President of the Philippines]], and initiates [[Philippine Drug War|a controversial drug war]].\n*[[Philippines]] wins the [[Philippines v. China|arbitration case against China]].\n*[[Andrei Karlov]], the Russian Ambassador to Turkey, [[Assassination of Andrei Karlov|is assassinated]] at an art exhibition in Ankara.\n*Detection of [[gravitational wave]]s by [[LIGO]] confirmed.\n*[[July 2016 Dhaka attack|Dhaka attack]] kills 29 people.\n*A shooter [[Orlando nightclub shooting|kills 49 people]] at a gay nightclub in [[Orlando, Florida]].\n*[[2016 Southern Taiwan earthquake]].\n*[[Tsai Ing-wen]] is [[2016 Taiwanese presidential election|elected]] [[President of the Republic of China|President of Taiwan]].\n*[[2016 attack on the Saudi diplomatic missions in Iran]].\n*[[2016 Russian Defence Ministry Tupolev Tu-154 crash]].\n*[[Burial of Ferdinand Marcos]].\n*Deaths of [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Muhammad Ali]], [[David Bowie]], [[Carrie Fisher]], [[Alan Rickman]], [[George Michael]], [[Debbie Reynolds]], [[Gene Wilder]], [[Death and state funeral of Fidel Castro|Fidel Castro]], [[Nancy Reagan]], [[Harper Lee]], [[Anton Yelchin]], [[Alan Thicke]], [[Arnold Palmer]], [[John Glenn]], [[Florence Henderson]], [[Doris Roberts]], [[Elie Wiesel]], [[Merle Haggard]], [[Leonard Cohen]], [[Garry Marshall]], [[Glenn Frey]], [[Garry Shandling]], [[Gwen Ifill]], [[Morley Safer]], [[Christina Grimmie]], [[German Moreno]], [[Miriam Defensor Santiago]], [[Death and funeral of Bhumibol Adulyadej|Bhumibol Adulyadej]], [[Shimon Peres]], and [[Antonin Scalia]].\n\n=== [[2017]] ===\n*Tensions between [[North Korea]] and the [[UN]] escalate as the country [[2017 North Korean nuclear test|tests a hydrogen bomb]] and conducts [[2017 North Korean missile tests|a series of ballistic missile tests]]. The UN responds with a wave of export sanctions.\n*A [[Manchester Arena bombing|terrorist bombing attack]] at an [[Ariana Grande]] concert in [[Manchester, England]] kills 22 people and injures over 500.\n*[[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) launch [[2017 Tehran attacks|simultaneous attacks]] in [[Tehran]], destroy the [[Great Mosque of al-Nuri (Mosul)|Great Mosque of al-Nuri]] in [[Mosul]] [[Iraq]], and [[2017 Sinai mosque attack|kill 311 in Egypt]], but are declared defeated in Iraq by the end of the year.\n*A [[Rohingya persecution in Myanmar (2016\u2013present)|military operation]] targeting [[Rohingya people|Rohingya Muslims]] in [[Myanmar]] is declared [[ethnic cleansing]] by the [[UNHCR]].\n*A [[14 October 2017 Mogadishu bombings|bombing in Mogadishu, Somalia]] on October 14, kills 587 people and injures 316. It is one of the deadliest terrorist attacks in modern history.\n*[[Hurricane Harvey]] kills 107 and becomes the costliest hurricane in US history, while [[Hurricane Irma]] kills 134, and [[Hurricane Maria]] kills 3,059.\n*Two earthquakes strike Mexico on [[2017 Chiapas earthquake|7 September]] and [[2017 Central Mexico earthquake|19 September]], killing more than 350.\n*[[2017 Iraqi Kurdistan independence referendum|Kurdistan and]] [[2017 Catalan independence referendum|Catalonia declare independence]] from Iraq and [[Spain]], respectively. Catalonia is not recognised, and [[2017 Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict|Iraq engages the Kurds in conflict]].\n*[[Robert Mugabe]] is ousted in a [[2017 Zimbabwean coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]], while [[Ratko Mladi\u0107]] is declared guilty of genocide.\n*The city of [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]] is [[Unite the Right rally|the site of a far-right rally]] protesting the removal of [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] statues throughout the US. During the event, a white supremacist rams his car into a crowd of counter-protesters, injuring 19 and killing one.\n*[[2017 Las Vegas shooting|58 people are killed in a mass shooting in Las Vegas]].\n*[[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse allegations|Allegations of sexual abuse]] against [[film producer]] [[Harvey Weinstein]] lead to a [[Weinstein effect|wave of similar accusations]] from within [[Hollywood]] and other areas of primarily the English-speaking world.\n*[[Grenfell Tower fire]] in London kills 72 and injures 70.\n*[['Oumuamua]], the first known [[interstellar object]], is identified.\n*[[Proclamation No. 216|Martial law]] declared in Mindanao following [[Marawi crisis|clashes between government forces and the Maute group in Marawi]].\n*[[2017 Resorts World Manila attack|36 people are killed in an attack in Resorts World Manila]].\n*The [[President of South Korea]], [[Park Geun-hye]], is impeached.\n*A [[2017 Venezuelan constitutional crisis|constitutional crisis]] occurs in Venezuela after [[2017 Venezuelan Constituent Assembly election|Constituent Assembly elections]] which replaced the legislative powers held by the opposition-led [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]].\n*Deaths of [[Chester Bennington]], [[Chuck Berry]], [[Chris Cornell]], [[Tom Petty]], [[Mary Tyler Moore]], [[Glen Campbell]], [[John Hurt]], [[Roger Moore]], [[Erin Moran]], [[Jerry Lewis]], [[Bill Paxton]], [[Don Rickles]], [[Fats Domino]], [[Sam Shepard]], [[Adam West]], [[Hugh Hefner]], [[Dick Gregory]], [[Monty Hall]], [[David Cassidy]], [[Della Reese]], [[Manuel Noriega]], [[Kim Jong-hyun (singer)|Kim Jong-hyun]], [[Ricardo Vidal]], [[Lil Peep]], [[Isabel Granada]] and [[Jake LaMotta]].\n\n=== [[2018]] ===\n*[[Turkey]] [[Operation Olive Branch|invades northern Syria]], while 70 die in [[Douma chemical attack|a chemical attack]], triggering a [[2018 missile strikes against Syria|missile strike]] against [[Bashar al-Assad]].\n*The first monkeys are [[Cloning|cloned]], and first genetically modified humans reported, in China.\n*[[Jacob Zuma]] resigns as [[President of South Africa]]; [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] becomes President. [[Scott Morrison]] becomes [[Prime Minister of Australia]].\n*Four people are poisoned, one to death, in [[Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal|Salisbury]] and [[2018 Amesbury poisonings|Amesbury]], England in a suspected Russian assassination attempt. The British government responds by leading the international expulsion of 153 Russian diplomats.\n*[[March for Our Lives]] occurs in 900 locations worldwide in response to the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting|Parkland shooting]].\n*The [[northern white rhinoceros]] becomes [[functionally extinct]].\n*[[Pakatan Harapan]] becomes the first opposition party to assume power in [[Malaysia]] since independence.\n*The first summit between [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States summit|the USA and North Korea]] and the first ever crossing of the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone]] by a North Korean leader occur.\n*Twenty-year [[Eritrean\u2013Ethiopian border conflict]] formally ends.\n*[[Yellow vests movement]] becomes [[France]]'s largest sustained period of civil unrest since 1968.\n*[[2018 Sunda Strait tsunami|Sunda strait tsunami]] kills 426 and injures 14,000.\n*[[2018 Sulawesi earthquake and tsunami]] kills 4,340 and injures 10,700.\n* Exiled ''[[Washington Post]]'' journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]] is [[Assassination of Jamal Khashoggi|assassinated]] inside the Saudi consulate in Istanbul, triggering a [[Reactions to the assassination of Jamal Khashoggi|diplomatic crisis]] for Saudi Arabia.\n*[[Kerch Strait incident]] triggers martial law in [[Ukraine]].\n*[[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] and [[Greece]] reach a historic agreement in the [[Macedonia naming dispute]], in which the former is renamed in 2019 to the 'Republic of North Macedonia'.\n*China's [[National People's Congress]] votes to abolish presidential [[term limits]], allowing [[Xi Jinping]] to [[President for life|rule for life]]. Xi is also the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], the [[Paramount leader|highest position]] without term limits.\n*[[Wedding of Prince Harry and Meghan Markle]].\n*[[2018 Armenian revolution]] happens in Armenia and improves country's democratic indexes. The revolution is known to be very peaceful due to its high civic sense.\n*[[2018 Iraqi parliamentary election|First post-ISIS election in Iraq]].\n*Twelve boys and their football coach are successfully [[Tham Luang cave rescue|rescued]] from the flooded [[Tham Luang Nang Non]] cave in [[Thailand]].\n*[[France]] wins the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.\n*[[2018 Boracay closure and redevelopment]].\n*[[Quo warranto petition against Maria Lourdes Sereno]].\n*[[Balangiga bells#Repatriation|Return of the Balangiga bells]].\n*[[Catriona Gray]] of the Philippines is crowned [[Miss Universe 2018]].\n*[[Bill Cosby]] is [[Bill Cosby sexual assault cases|found guilty of sexual assault and sentenced to three to ten years in prison]].\n*Deaths of [[Stephen Hawking]], [[Stan Lee]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Burt Reynolds]], [[Avicii]], [[Kate Spade]], [[Verne Troyer]], [[Anthony Bourdain]], [[Barbara Bush]], [[John McCain]], [[Death and state funeral of George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]], [[XXXTentacion]], [[Mac Miller]], [[Dolores O\u2019Riordan]], [[Penny Marshall]], [[Stephen Hillenburg]], [[Billy Graham]], [[Mark Salling]], [[Paul Allen]], [[Philip Roth]], [[Linda Carol Brown|Linda Brown]], [[Nancy Wilson (jazz singer)|Nancy Wilson]], [[Charles Aznavour]], [[Kofi Annan]], [[Winnie Mandela]], [[Rico J. Puno]], [[Roilo Golez]] and [[Neil Simon]].\n\n=== [[2019]] ===\n*[[Jair Bolsonaro]] becomes [[President of Brazil]].\n*[[New Horizons]] takes the first close up image of a [[486958 Arrokoth|classical kuiper belt object]].\n*[[Chang'e 4]] becomes the first object to land on the [[far side of the Moon]].\n*[[2019\u201420 Bolivian protests|Protests erupt in Bolivia]] [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis|and Venezuela]] over [[2018 Venezuelan presidential election|disputed]] [[2019 Bolivian general election|elections]].\n*[[Nursultan Nazarbayev]] resigns as [[President of Kazakhstan]]. [[Kassym-Jomart Tokayev]] assumes power. [[Astana]] is renamed [[Nur-Sultan]] in his honor.\n*[[Christchurch mosque shootings]] kill 51 people, while a [[2019 Khash\u2013Zahedan suicide bombing|suicide bombing in Iran]] kills 41, and a [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings|series of bomb attacks]] in [[Sri Lanka]] kills 250.\n*The [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] loses the last of its territory.\n*The EU [[Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market]] is passed over intense opposition.\n*[[Abdelaziz Bouteflika]] resigns as [[President of Algeria]], while [[Omar al-Bashir]] is deposed as [[President of Sudan]] in [[2019 Sudanese coup d'\u00e9tat|a coup d'\u00e9tat]] amid [[2019 Algerian protests|widespread protests]] [[2018\u201319 Sudanese protests|in both countries]].\n*The [[Event Horizon Telescope]] takes the first ever image of a [[black hole]], at the core of galaxy [[Messier 87]].\n*[[Volodymyr Zelensky]] becomes [[President of Ukraine]].\n*[[Victor Vescovo]] breaks the human depth record, reaching 10,928&nbsp;m in the [[Challenger Deep]].\n*[[Akihito]] [[2019 Japanese imperial transition|abdicates]] as [[Emperor of Japan]]; [[Naruhito]] becomes Emperor.\n*[[Bashar al Assad]] launches [[Northwestern Syria offensive (April\u2013August 2019)|multiple offensives]] [[Northwestern Syria offensive (November 2019\u2013present)|in Northwestern Syria]]; [[Turkey]] launches [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|an offensive into northeastern Syria]].\n*[[Khartoum massacre|More than a hundred people are killed]] after police and [[Janjaweed]] attack protesters in Sudan.\n*The United States blames [[June 2019 Gulf of Oman incident|attacks on ships in the Gulf of Oman]] on Iran, escalating [[2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis|tensions in the Persian Gulf]].\n*[[Kyriakos Mitsotakis]] becomes [[Prime Minister of Greece]].\n*[[Boris Johnson]] becomes [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], and attempts a [[2019 British prorogation controversy|prorogation of Parliament]] that is [[R (Miller) v The Prime Minister and Cherry v Advocate General for Scotland|ultimately declared unlawful]].\n*[[2019-2020 Hong Kong protests|Protests begin]] in [[Hong Kong]] over an extradition bill.\n*[[India]] [[Revocation of the special status of Jammu and Kashmir|revokes the special status of Jammu and Kashmir]].\n*[[Barisha raid]] ends in the [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi|death of Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]].\n*[[2019 Albania earthquake|A 6.4 magnitude earthquake]] in [[Albania]], kills 51 people.\n*[[Citizenship Amendment Act protests|Protests erupt in India]] over the passing of the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019|Citizenship Amendment Act]].\n*[[2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires|Wildfires spike]] in [[Brazil]], while [[Australia]] endures the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|most widespread brush fires in its history]].\n*A major [[Notre-Dame de Paris fire|fire]] engulfs [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame Cathedral]] in Paris, resulting in the roof and main spire collapsing.\n*A [[2019 Jolo Cathedral bombings|series of suicide bombings]] [[2019 Indanan bombings|occurred in Sulu]].\n*The [[Murders of Eileen Sarmenta and Allan Gomez|June 1993 rape and murder case of Eileen Sarmenta and Allan Gomez]] is reopened due to the impending release of former [[Calauan, Laguna|Calauan]] mayor [[Antonio Sanchez (politician)|Antonio Sanchez]].\n*An [[2019\u20132020 Philippines polio outbreak|outbreak of polio]] is declared in the Philippines, 19 years following its eradication in the country.\n*The [[President of the United States]], [[Donald Trump]], is [[Impeachment of Donald Trump|impeached]].\n*[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] begins in [[Wuhan]], China.\n*Deaths of [[Jacques Chirac]], [[Robert Mugabe]], [[Mohamed Morsi]], [[Zine El Abidine Ben Ali]], [[Yasuhiro Nakasone]], [[Beji Caid Essebsi]], [[Luke Perry]], [[Doris Day]], [[Karl Lagerfeld]], [[Cameron Boyce]], [[Tim Conway]], [[Gloria Vanderbilt]], [[Toni Morrison]], [[John Singleton]], [[John Witherspoon (actor)|John Witherspoon,]] [[Ross Perot]], [[Valerie Harper]], [[Diahann Carroll]], [[Peter Mayhew]], [[Caroll Spinney]], [[Ric Ocasek]], [[Danny Aiello]], [[Peter Fonda]], [[Cokie Roberts]], [[Henry Sy]], [[Eddie Garcia]], [[Goo Hara]], [[Aquilino Pimentel Jr.]], [[Gina Lopez]], [[Elijah Cummings]] and [[Juice Wrld]].\n\n== [[2020s]] ==\n<!-- do not add anything from the current year until after it is complete -->\n{{for|the current year|{{CURRENTYEAR}}|{{CURRENTYEAR}} in politics and government}}<!-- do not add new material until the current year is ended. -->\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Timeline of the 20th century]]\n* [[21st century in fiction]]\n* [[Timelines of the future]]\n\n{{21st century}}\n\n[[Category:21st century|*]]\n[[Category:Contemporary history timelines|*]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia timelines|*]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||other timelines of modern history|Timelines of modern history|future timelines|Timelines of the future}}\n\n{{Centurybox|21}}\nThis is a '''timeline of the [[21st century]]'''.\n\n== [[2000s (decade)|2000s]] ==\n<!--The 21st century began in 2001, not 2000 -->\n=== [[2001]] ===\n*[[September 11 attacks]]: [[Al-Qaeda]] terrorists crash planes into the twin towers of the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] in [[New York City]], and [[the Pentagon]] in [[Washington, DC]]. A fourth plane is downed on the outskirts of [[Stonycreek Township, Somerset County, Pennsylvania|Stonycreek Township, PA.]] 2,996 people die in the attacks.\n*An [[2001 Gujarat earthquake|earthquake]] strikes [[Gujarat]], [[India]] on [[Republic Day (India)|Republic Day]], resulting in more than 20,000 deaths.\n*The [[War on Terror]] is declared by [[George W. Bush|President Bush]], in response to [[September 11 attacks|9/11]].\n*The [[United States invasion of Afghanistan|United States invades Afghanistan]] and topples the [[Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan|Taliban regime]]. The result is a [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|long-term war.]]\n*The [[African Union]] is founded in [[Addis Ababa]], [[Ethiopia]].\n*During an [[Argentine economic crisis (1999\u20132002)|economic crisis in Argentina,]] the government effectively [[Corralito|freezes all bank accounts]] for twelve months which [[December 2001 riots in Argentina|leads to riots]] and President [[Fernando de la R\u00faa|de la R\u00faa]]'s resignation from office. There are five \"presidents\" in less than a month.\n*President [[Joseph Estrada]] of the [[Philippines]] is [[Second EDSA Revolution|ousted]].\n*[[China and the World Trade Organization|China becomes]] a member of the [[World Trade Organization]].\n*[[Wikipedia]] is launched.\n*Eleven members of the royal family of [[Nepal]], including the king and queen, are killed in the [[Nepalese royal massacre]]. The perpetrator, Crown Prince [[Dipendra of Nepal|Dipendra]], wounds himself and dies three days later.\n*[[Dos Palmas kidnappings]]: Twenty tourists are abducted by the [[Abu Sayyaf]] Group terrorists from a popular island resort in the Philippines.\n*Deaths of [[Aaliyah]], [[George Harrison]], [[Death of Dale Earnhardt|Dale Earnhardt]], [[Jack Lemmon]], [[Carroll O'Connor]], [[Anthony Quinn]] and [[John Lee Hooker]].\n\n=== [[2002]] ===\n*[[2002 Bali bombings]].\n*The [[Euro]] first enters circulation.\n*[[2002 Gujarat riots|Riots and mass killings]] in the Indian state of [[Gujarat]] leave 1,044 dead.\n*Israel starts [[Operation Defensive Shield]] in the West Bank in response to a wave of [[List of Palestinian suicide attacks #2000s|Palestinian suicide attacks]].\n*Construction of the [[Israeli West Bank barrier]] begins.\n*Chechen rebels [[Moscow theater hostage crisis|seize theater]] in Moscow.\n*Establishment of the [[International Criminal Court]].\n*America demands [[Iraq disarmament crisis|Iraq allow unfettered access to weapons inspectors]].\n*[[Guantanamo Bay detention camp]] is established.\n*[[Algerian Civil War]] ends.\n*[[Beltway sniper attacks]].\n*Independence of [[East Timor]].\n*[[First Ivorian Civil War]] begins.\n*[[Brazil]] wins the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]].\n*[[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Golden Jubilee]] of [[Elizabeth II]].\n*Deaths of [[Lisa Lopes]], [[Waylon Jennings]], [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|The Queen Mother]], [[Ted Williams]], [[Chuck Jones]], [[Dudley Moore]], [[Milton Berle]], [[Dave Thomas (businessman)|Dave Thomas]], [[Eppie Lederer|Ann Landers]], [[Johnny Unitas]] and [[Bill Blass]].\n\n=== [[2003]] ===\n*The United States [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invades Iraq]] and topples [[Saddam Hussein]], triggering [[Protests against the Iraq War|worldwide protests]] and an [[Iraq War|8 year war]].\n*[[War in Darfur]] begins.\n*The [[Human Genome Project]] is completed.\n*[[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]] becomes [[President of Brazil]]\n*[[Second Congo War]] ends with more than 5 million dead.\n*[[Second Liberian Civil War]] ends.\n*[[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']] is [[Space Shuttle Columbia disaster|destroyed on re-entry]].\n*[[Rose Revolution]] in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]].\n*The last [[Volkswagen Beetle]] is made in Mexico, after 65 years in production.\n*[[2003 Marriott Hotel bombing]].\n*The first [[six-party talks]], involving [[South Korea|South]] and [[North Korea]], the [[United States]], [[China]], [[Japan]] and [[Russia]].\n*Deaths of [[Johnny Cash]], [[June Carter Cash]], [[Fred Rogers]], [[John Ritter]], [[Katharine Hepburn]], [[Bob Hope]], [[Barry White]], [[Maurice Gibb]], [[Gregory Peck]], [[Charles Bronson]], [[Althea Gibson]] and [[David Brinkley]].\n\n=== [[2004]] ===\n*[[Enlargement of NATO|NATO]] and [[2004 enlargement of the European Union|the European Union]] incorporates most of the former Eastern Bloc.\n*[[Facebook]] formed by [[Mark Zuckerberg]].\n*[[Union of South American Nations]] formed.\n*[[Madrid train bombings]].\n*The [[Second Battle of Fallujah]] is the deadliest American battle since Vietnam, killing 95 troops.\n*[[Orange Revolution]] in [[Ukraine]].\n*[[Beslan school hostage crisis]].\n*[[2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami|Boxing Day Tsunami]] occurs in [[Indian Ocean]], leading to the deaths of 230,000.\n*First surface images of [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Titan (moon)|Titan]].\n*[[2004 SuperFerry 14 bombing]].\n*Deaths of [[Death and State Funeral of Ronald Reagan|Ronald Reagan]], [[Ray Charles]], [[Marlon Brando]], [[Julia Child]], [[Rick James]], [[Christopher Reeve]], [[Rodney Dangerfield]], [[Estee Lauder (businesswoman)|Estee Lauder]], [[Richard Avedon]], [[Pat Tillman]], [[Jerry Orbach]], [[Janet Leigh]] and [[Yasser Arafat]].\n\n=== [[2005]] ===\n*[[Irish Republican Army]] end military campaign in Northern Ireland.\n*[[7/7 attacks]] on [[London Underground]].\n*[[Angela Merkel]] becomes Germany's first female [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor]].\n*[[Tulip Revolution]] in [[Kyrgyzstan]].\n*[[Second Intifada]] ends.\n*[[Israeli disengagement from Gaza|Israel withdraws from Gaza]].\n*[[Cedar Revolution]] in [[Lebanon]] triggered by the [[assassination of Rafic Hariri]].\n*[[Second Sudanese Civil War]] ends.\n*[[Hurricane Katrina]] kills 1,836 people in the [[Gulf of Mexico]] (particularly in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]]).\n*80,000 are killed in [[2005 Kashmir earthquake|an earthquake]] in [[Kashmir]].\n*The [[Kyoto Protocol]] comes into effect.\n*[[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]] becomes [[President of Iran]].\n*[[Pope Benedict XVI|Benedict XVI]] becomes Pope.\n*[[Michael E. Brown]] discovers [[Eris (dwarf planet)|Eris]].\n*[[YouTube]] formed by [[Jawed Karim]], [[Chad Hurley]] and [[Steve Chen]].\n*[[2005 Valentine's Day bombings]].\n*[[2005 World Summit]].\n*Deaths of [[Funeral of Pope John Paul II|Pope John Paul II]], [[Rosa Parks]], [[Richard Pryor]], [[Johnny Carson]], [[Luther Vandross]], [[Pat Morita]], [[Arthur Miller]], [[Anne Bancroft]], [[Johnnie Cochran]], [[Peter Jennings]], [[Don Adams]] and [[William Rehnquist]].\n*[[Reddit]] is founded by [[Steve Huffman]], [[Aaron Swartz]] and [[Alexis Ohanian]]\n\n=== [[2006]] ===\n*[[2006 Montenegrin independence referendum|Independence of Montenegro]].\n*[[2006 Lebanon War]].\n*[[2006 Mumbai train bombings|Mumbai bombings]].\n*[[Comprehensive Peace Accord]] ends the [[Nepalese Civil War]].\n*[[Ellen Johnson Sirleaf]] becomes President of [[Liberia]], and thus Africa's first elected female head of state.\n*The [[International Astronomical Union]] creates [[IAU definition of planet|the first formal definition of a planet]], and excludes [[Pluto]] from the list.\n*[[Execution of Saddam Hussein]].\n*The [[Baiji]], the Yangtze [[river dolphin]], becomes [[functionally extinct]].\n*[[Twitter]] is launched.\n*Former Russian security agent [[Poisoning of Alexander Litvinenko|Alexander Litvinenko dies from poisoning]] in the UK.\n*[[Nintendo]] launches the [[Wii]].\n*[[2006 Southern Leyte mudslide]].\n*Deaths of [[Steve Irwin]], [[James Brown]], [[Don Knotts]], [[Death and state funeral of Gerald Ford|Gerald Ford]], [[Coretta Scott King]], [[Peter Boyle]], [[Lou Rawls]], [[Betty Friedan]], [[Kirby Puckett]], [[Aaron Spelling]], [[Robert Altman]], [[Gordon Parks]] and [[Ed Bradley]].\n*[[Italy national football team|Italy]] wins [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 Fifa World Cup]]\n\n=== [[2007]] ===\n*[[Saffron Revolution|Anti-government protests]] in [[Myanmar]] suppressed by ruling [[Military junta|junta]].\n*[[2007\u20132008 world food price crisis|Spike in food prices]] and [[subprime crisis]] help trigger [[Late-2000s recession|global recession]].\n*[[Assassination of Benazir Bhutto]].\n*[[Gordon Brown]] becomes [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]].\n*[[First Ivorian Civil War]] ends.\n*[[Virginia Tech shooting]].\n*Deaths of [[Anna Nicole Smith]], [[Luciano Pavarotti]], [[Ike Turner]], [[Evel Knievel]], [[Lady Bird Johnson]], [[Death and state funeral of Boris Yeltsin|Boris Yeltsin]], [[Merv Griffin]], [[Kurt Vonnegut]], [[Tammy Faye Messner]], [[Phil Rizzuto]], [[Jerry Falwell]], [[Liz Claiborne]] and [[Norman Mailer]].\n\n=== [[2008]] ===\n*Stock markets [[Financial crisis of 2007\u20132008|plunge]] around the world, signalling the start of the [[Great Recession]].\n*End of Monarchy in [[Nepal]].\n*[[Barack Obama]] is elected as [[President of the United States]].\n*[[Cyclone Nargis]] kills 133,000 in [[Myanmar]].\n*[[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]] begins.\n*[[2008 South Ossetia war]].\n*[[Kosovo]] [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|declares independence]], to mixed reaction.\n*Iraqi forces [[Battle of Basra (2008)|crack down]] on [[Muqtada al Sadr]]'s Mahdi forces in Basra and Sadr City.\n*[[2008 Mumbai attacks]].\n*The [[Large Hadron Collider]] is completed as the world's largest and most powerful [[particle collider]].\n*[[MV Princess of the Stars|Sinking of MV Princess of the Stars]].\n*Deaths of [[Heath Ledger]], [[Bernie Mac]], [[Paul Newman]], [[Estelle Getty]], [[Yves Saint Laurent (designer)|Yves Saint Laurent]], [[Sir Edmund Hillary]], [[George Carlin]], [[Charlton Heston]], [[Roy Scheider]], [[Isaac Hayes]], [[Bettie Page]], [[Bo Diddley]], [[Michael Crichton]], [[Tim Russert]], [[Sydney Pollack]], [[Mark Felt]] and [[William F. Buckley]].\n\n=== [[2009]] ===\n*[[Bitcoin]] is launched.\n*[[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]] ends while [[Gaza blockade]] continues.\n*[[Sri Lankan Civil War]] ends.\n*[[2009\u20132010 Iranian election protests|Election protests]] begin in Iran.\n*[[Second Chechen War]] ends.\n*[[Boko Haram]] rebellion begins in Nigeria.\n*Construction of the world's tallest skyscraper [[Burj Khalifa]] is completed in [[Dubai]].\n*Formation of [[BRICS]] economic bloc.\n*[[Treaty of Lisbon]] ratified.\n*[[2009 flu pandemic]].\n*Former [[President of the Philippines|Philippine president]] [[Corazon Aquino]] [[Death and funeral of Corazon Aquino|dies]] of [[colorectal cancer|colon cancer]].\n*[[Typhoon Ketsana]] causes widespread damages in the Philippines.\n*[[Maguindanao massacre|58 people are abducted and killed]] in the province of [[Maguindanao]].\n*Deaths of [[Death of Michael Jackson|Michael Jackson]], [[Patrick Swayze]], [[Brittany Murphy]], [[Billy Mays]], [[Farrah Fawcett]], [[Bea Arthur]], [[Natasha Richardson]], [[John Hughes (filmmaker)|John Hughes]], [[Les Paul]], [[Ted Kennedy]], [[Walter Cronkite]], [[Dom DeLuise]], [[David Carradine]], [[Ed McMahon]], [[John Updike]], [[Mary Travers]], [[Paul Harvey]], [[Oral Roberts]] and [[Frank McCourt]].\n\n== [[2010s]] ==\n\n=== [[2010]] ===\n*After the [[2010 United Kingdom general election]], [[David Cameron]] becomes [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]].\n*[[Benigno Aquino III]] is elected as the [[List of Presidents of the Philippines|15th]] [[President of the Philippines]].\n*A [[2010 Haiti earthquake|7.0 magnitude earthquake]] in [[Haiti]] kills 230,000.\n*The threat of [[Greece]] [[Greek government-debt crisis|defaulting on its debts]] triggers the [[2010 European sovereign debt crisis|European sovereign debt crisis]] and [[Republic of Ireland]]'s [[Post-2008 Irish economic downturn|financial crisis]].\n*The [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill|largest oil spill in US history]] occurs in the [[Gulf of Mexico]].\n*[[North Korea]] [[Bombardment of Yeonpyeong|shells]] the island of [[Yeonpyeong]].\n*Burmese political prisoner [[Aung San Suu Kyi]] is released from house arrest.\n*The FIFA world cup is [[2010 FIFA World Cup|held]] in Africa for the first time.\n*[[2010 Moscow Metro bombings]].\n*[[Arab Spring]] starts.\n*[[Kyrgyz Revolution of 2010]].\n*[[2010 Nigerien coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n*The President of Poland, [[Lech Kaczy\u0144ski]], is among 96 killed when their airplane [[2010 Polish Air Force Tu-154 crash|crashes]] in Smolensk on April 10.\n*The [[Burj Khalifa]] located in [[Dubai]] opened to the public and stood as the [[tallest structure in the world]], standing at 829.8 m (2,722&nbsp;ft).\n*[[Dilma Rousseff]] is elected as the first female president of [[Brazil]].\n*[[Instagram]] is launched.\n*[[Manila hostage crisis]].\n*[[2010 Colombia\u2013Venezuela diplomatic crisis]].\n*[[2010 Copiap\u00f3 mining accident]].\n*[[2010 eruptions of Eyjafjallaj\u00f6kull]].\n*[[Julia Gillard]] is elected [[Prime Minister of Australia]].\n*Deaths of [[Paul Gray]], [[Corey Haim]], [[Gary Coleman]], [[Rue McClanahan]], [[Alexander McQueen]], [[Lena Horne]], [[Leslie Nielsen]], [[Tony Curtis]], [[George Steinbrenner]], [[Dennis Hopper]], [[J.D. Salinger]] and [[Tom Bosley]].\n\n=== [[2011]] ===\n*Independence of [[South Sudan]].\n*Snapchat launched.\n*February [[2011 Christchurch earthquake|Christchurch earthquake]] kills 185 and injures 2,000.\n*[[Arab Spring]]: [[Tunisian revolution|revolutions in Tunisia]], [[2011 Egyptian revolution|Egypt]] [[2011 Libyan civil war|and Libya]] follow, as well as [[2011 Yemeni uprising|uprisings in Yemen]] [[2011 Bahraini uprising|and Bahrain]], and protests in several other Arab countries.\n*[[Syrian civil war]] begins.\n*[[Second Ivorian Civil War]].\n*[[Occupy movement]] inspires worldwide protests.\n*[[News International phone hacking scandal]].\n*A [[2011 T\u014dhoku earthquake and tsunami|9.0 earthquake]] in [[Japan]] triggers a tsunami and the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|meltdown of the Fukushima Nuclear Power Plant]].\n*The [[Danyang\u2013Kunshan Grand Bridge]], the world's longest, opens in China.\n*[[Second Ivorian Civil War]] ends with the arrest of former president [[Laurent Gbagbo]].\n*[[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq|Iraq War ends]].\n*[[2011 England riots|Riots flare across England]].\n*Bombings occur [[2011 Domodedovo International Airport bombing|In Russia]] [[2011 Mogadishu bombing|and Somalia]].\n*[[World population]] reaches [[Day of 7 Billion|7 Billion]].\n*[[2011 Sindh floods|Floods in Pakistan]], [[2011 Thailand floods|Thailand]] [[Tropical Storm Washi (2011)|and the Philippines]] kill roughly 2,500 people.\n*[[Death of Osama bin Laden|Osama bin Laden is shot dead]] by [[United States Navy SEALs]] in Pakistan.\n*[[2011 Norway attacks]].\n*[[Death of Muammar Gaddafi|Muammar Gaddafi is captured and killed]] during the [[Battle of Sirte (2011)|Battle of Sirte]].\n*[[Wedding of Prince William and Catherine Middleton]].\n*[[Space Shuttle program]] is officially ended.\n*[[Amazon rainforest|Amazon Rainforest]] and [[Amazon River|River]], [[H\u1ea1 Long Bay]], [[Jeju Island]], [[Iguaz\u00fa Falls]], [[Puerto Princesa Subterranean River National Park|Puerto Princesa Underground River]], [[Komodo Island]] and [[Table Mountain]] were named as the world's [[New7Wonders of Nature]].\n*Deaths of [[Steve Jobs]], [[Death and state funeral of Kim Jong-il|Kim Jong-il]], [[Amy Winehouse]], [[Elizabeth Taylor]], [[Peter Falk]], [[Betty Ford]], [[Randy Savage]] and [[Andy Rooney]].\n\n=== [[2012]] ===\n*[[2012 Northern Mali conflict|Northern Mali conflict]], the [[National Movement for the Liberation of Azawad|MNLA]] declares [[Azawad]] an independent state.\n*[[Yemen]]i President [[Ali Abdullah Saleh]] steps down.\n*[[2012 Benghazi attack]] leads to the death of US ambassador [[J. Christopher Stevens]].\n*[[Shenouda III]], [[Pope of the Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria]], departs; [[Pope Tawadros II of Alexandria|Tawadros II]] succeeds him.\n*The [[Higgs boson]] is discovered.\n*Vladimir Putin is elected president of Russia for the third time.\n*[[Hurricane Sandy]] kills 209 people in North America, while [[Typhoon Bopha]] kills over 1,600 in the [[Philippines]].\n*Skydiver [[Felix Baumgartner]] becomes the first person to [[Sound barrier#Breaking the sound barrier as a human projectile|break the sound barrier without a vehicle]].\n*[[Central African Republic conflict (2012\u201313)|Conflict begins]] in the [[Central African Republic]].\n*[[2012 United Nations Climate Change Conference|UN Climate Change Conference]] agrees to extend the [[Kyoto Protocol]] until 2020.\n*[[Israel]] launches [[Operation Pillar of Defense]] against the [[Palestinian people|Palestinian]]-governed [[Gaza Strip]].\n*[[2012 Guinea-Bissau coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n*The US rover, [[Curiosity (rover)|Curiosity]], takes a selfie on Mars.\n*[[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]].\n*[[2012 Aurora shooting]].\n*[[Costa Concordia disaster]].\n*[[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II]].\n*[[Impeachment of Renato Corona]].\n*Pakistani Taliban attempt to assassinate outspoken schoolgirl [[Malala Yousafzai]].\n*Deaths of [[Whitney Houston]], [[Neil Armstrong]], [[Andy Griffith]], [[Dick Clark]], [[Donna Summer]], [[Etta James]], [[Robin Gibb]], [[Sally Ride]], [[Michael Clarke Duncan]], [[Sherman Hemsley]], [[Ernest Borgnine]], [[Larry Hagman]], [[Davy Jones (musician)|Davy Jones]], [[Jack Klugman]], [[Phyllis Diller]], [[Ray Bradbury]], [[Gore Vidal]], [[Maurice Sendak]], [[Mike Wallace]], [[Adam Yauch]], [[Dave Brubeck]], [[Dolphy]], [[Yitzhak Shamir]], [[Jesse Robredo]] and [[Don Cornelius]].\n\n=== [[2013]] ===\n*The French military intervenes in the [[Northern Mali conflict]].\n*[[Chelyabinsk meteor]].\n*[[Resignation of Pope Benedict XVI|Pope Benedict XVI resigns]] and [[Pope Francis]] becomes Pope.\n*[[Boston Marathon bombings|Terrorist attacks occur]] in [[Boston]] [[Westgate shopping mall attack|and Nairobi]].\n*The [[2013 Savar building collapse|Rana Plaza collapses]] in [[Bangladesh]].\n*[[Edward Snowden]] releases classified documents concerning [[Global surveillance disclosure|mass surveillance by the NSA]].\n*[[President of Egypt]] [[Mohamed Morsi]] [[2013 Egyptian coup d'\u00e9tat|is deposed by the military in a coup d'\u00e9tat]].\n*[[Croatia]] becomes a member of the [[European Union]].\n*The [[Euromaidan]] protest begins in [[Ukraine]].\n*[[Ghouta chemical attack|A chemical attack in Ghouta, Syria]] is blamed on President [[Bashar al-Assad]].\n*A [[2013 Bohol earthquake|7.2 magnitude earthquake]] in [[Bohol]], kills 222.\n*[[Typhoon Haiyan]] kills nearly 6,150 people in the [[Philippines]] and [[Vietnam]].\n*[[South Sudanese conflict (2013\u2013present)|Conflict begins in South Sudan]].\n*[[Uruguay]] becomes [[Legality of cannabis by country|the first country to fully legalize cannabis]].\n*End of [[2012\u20132013 Cypriot financial crisis]].\n*[[Zamboanga City crisis]].\n*[[Kiss nightclub fire]].\n*[[2013 Alberta floods]].\n*Deaths of [[Death of Nelson Mandela|Nelson Mandela]], [[Death and funeral of Margaret Thatcher|Margaret Thatcher]], [[Death of Hugo Ch\u00e1vez|Hugo Chavez]], [[Paul Walker]], [[Cory Monteith]], [[James Gandolfini]], [[Annette Funicello]], [[Peter O'Toole]], [[Roger Ebert]], [[Tom Clancy]], [[Jean Stapleton]], [[Lou Reed]] and [[George Jones]].\n\n=== [[2014]] ===\n*[[Ebola virus epidemic in West Africa|The worst Ebola epidemic in recorded history]] occurs in West Africa, infecting nearly 30,000 people and resulting in the deaths of 11,000+.\n*[[Euromaidan]] protest in Ukraine sparks a [[2014 Ukrainian Revolution|revolution]] and the overthrow of [[Viktor Yanukovych]], leading to Russia's [[Annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation|annexation of Crimea]] and the [[War in Donbass]].\n*[[Malaysia Airlines Flight 370]] disappears from radar while en route to Beijing from Kuala Lumpur on March 8. There were 239 people on board.\n*A [[2014 Thai coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]] in Thailand overthrows the caretaker government.\n*King [[Juan Carlos I]] of Spain abdicates; his son becomes [[King Felipe VI]].\n*[[Indonesia AirAsia Flight 8501]] crashes into the Java Sea, while [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 17]] is shot down over Ukraine and [[Air Alg\u00e9rie Flight 5017]] is downed in [[Mali]].\n*[[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan]] [[2014 Peshawar school massacre|kill]] over 130 students in [[Pakistan]].\n*[[Israel]] launches [[Operation Protective Edge|an assault]] on the [[Gaza Strip]] in response to [[2014 kidnapping and murder of Israeli teenagers|tit-for-tat]] [[Kidnapping and murder of Mohammed Abu Khdeir|murder-kidnappings]], leading to the deaths of 71 Israelis and 2,100 Palestinians.\n*[[Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] begins [[Northern Iraq offensive (June 2014)|its offensive in northern Iraq]], leading to [[2014 American-led intervention in Iraq|intervention in Iraq]] [[American-led intervention in Syria|and Syria]] by a US-led coalition.\n*[[Second Libyan Civil War]] begins.\n*The [[Rosetta (spacecraft)|''Rosetta'' spacecraft]]'s ''[[Philae (spacecraft)|Philae]]'' probe becomes the first to successfully land on [[67P/Churyumov-Gerasimenko|a comet]].\n*The [[shooting of Michael Brown|shooting]] of African-American teenager Michael Brown by police leads to [[Ferguson unrest|violent unrest]] in [[Ferguson, Missouri]].\n*[[Joko Widodo]] is [[2014 Indonesian presidential election|elected]] [[President of Indonesia]].\n*[[Sinking of MV Sewol]].\n*[[Doha]], [[Durban]], [[Havana]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[La Paz]] and [[Vigan]] were chosen as the world's [[New7Wonders Cities]].\n*Deaths of [[Robin Williams]], [[Maya Angelou]], [[Shirley Temple]], [[Joan Rivers]], [[Philip Seymour Hoffman]], [[Mickey Rooney]], [[James Garner]], [[Casey Kasem]], [[Lauren Bacall]], [[Richard Attenborough]], [[Harold Ramis]], [[Pete Seeger]], [[Joe Cocker]], [[Oscar de la Renta]], [[Ariel Sharon]], and [[Mike Nichols]].\n\n=== [[2015]] ===\n*Five [[former Soviet Union]] countries form the [[Eurasian Economic Union]].\n*A [[November 2015 Paris attacks|series of terrorist attacks]] [[Charlie Hebdo shooting|occur in Paris]].\n*[[Boko Haram]] perpetrates [[2015 Baga massacre|a massacre of over 2,000 people]] in [[Baga, Nigeria]], and allies itself with [[Islamic State in Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]].\n*[[Al-Shabaab (militant group)|Al-Shabaab]] perpetrates a [[Garissa University College attack|a mass shooting]] in [[Kenya]], killing 148.\n*[[Houthis]] [[Houthi takeover in Yemen|overthrow the government in Yemen]], triggering [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen|a military response]] by [[Saudi Arabia]].\n*[[April 2015 Nepal earthquake|A series]] [[May 2015 Nepal earthquake|of earthquakes]] [[October 2015 Hindu Kush earthquake|in the Himalayas]] kills over 10,000 people.\n*[[ISIL]] claims responsibility for the [[Koban\u00ee massacre]] in [[Syria]], the [[2015 Sousse attacks|Sousse attacks in Tunisia]], [[2015 Kuwait mosque bombing|a mosque bombing in Kuwait]], the [[2015 Suru\u00e7 bombing|Suru\u00e7 bombing]] in [[Turkey]], multiple bombings in [[2015 Beirut bombings|Beirut]] and a massacre in [[November 2015 Paris attacks|Paris]], as well as [[Metrojet Flight 9268|the bombing of a Russian Airliner]] over Egypt. They also inspire a [[2015 San Bernardino attack|mass shooting in San Bernardino, California]].\n*[[Turkish involvement in the Syrian Civil War|Turkey and]] [[Russian military intervention in the Syrian Civil War|Russia intervene]] in the [[Syrian Civil War]].\n*The heads of [[China]] and [[Taiwan]] [[2015 Ma\u2013Xi meeting|meet for the first time]], while the [[United States]] and [[Cuba]] resume diplomatic relations.\n*[[2015 United Nations Climate Change Conference|195 nations agree]] to lower [[carbon emissions]].\n*[[Water on Mars|Liquid water]] is found on [[Mars]].\n*First close-up images of [[Ceres (dwarf planet)|Ceres]] and [[Pluto]].\n*[[Charleston church shooting]].\n*[[Pope Francis's visit to the Philippines]].\n*[[100th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide]] was commemorated worldwide. The event occurred in light of continued Armenian Genocide denial by Turkey.\n*[[Mamasapano clash]].\n*[[Floyd Mayweather Jr. vs. Manny Pacquiao]].\n*[[Kentex slipper factory fire]].\n*[[Pia Wurtzbach|Pia Alonzo Wurtzbach]] of the [[Philippines]] is crowned [[Miss Universe 2015]].\n*The opposition-led [[Democratic Unity Roundtable]] wins the most seats in the [[2015 Venezuelan parliamentary election]], defeating the [[United Socialist Party of Venezuela]] for the first time since the [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]] was established in 1999.\n*Deaths of [[Leonard Nimoy]], [[B.B. King]], [[Christopher Lee]], [[Yogi Berra]], [[Bob Simon]], [[Frank Gifford]], [[John Forbes Nash Jr.]], [[Wes Craven]], [[Ben E. King]], [[Jackie Collins]], [[Natalie Cole]], [[Lesley Gore]], [[Sam Simon]], [[Scott Weiland]], [[Omar Sharif]], [[Dick Van Patten]], [[Death and state funeral of Lee Kuan Yew|Lee Kuan Yew]], [[Lemmy Kilmister]] and [[James Horner]].\n\n=== [[2016]] ===\n*[[2015\u201316 Zika virus epidemic|An outbreak of the Zika virus]] is linked to a cluster of cases of [[microcephaly]].\n*The [[United Nations]] lifts sanctions on [[Iran]] in recognition of its dismantling of its [[Iran and weapons of mass destruction|nuclear program]].\n*[[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL]] claims responsibility for [[2016 Brussels bombings|a series of bombings in Brussels]], [[2016 Atat\u00fcrk Airport attack|a massacre]] at [[Istanbul]]'s [[Ataturk Airport]] and car ramming attacks in [[2016 Nice attack|Nice]] and [[2016 Berlin attack|Berlin]].\n*The [[Gotthard Base Tunnel]], the world's longest [[railway tunnel]], is completed.\n*The people of the [[United Kingdom]] vote narrowly to [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|leave the European Union]]; [[Theresa May]] becomes [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]].\n*[[Donald Trump]] is [[2016 United States presidential election|elected]] [[President of the United States]].\n*The [[Colombia]]n government signs a [[Colombian peace process|peace deal]] with [[FARC]] despite losing [[2016 Colombian peace agreement referendum|a referendum]].\n*[[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan|United States troops withdraw from Afghanistan]] after 15 years.\n*The [[President of Brazil]], [[Dilma Rousseff]], is impeached.\n*The government of Turkey begins a [[2016 Turkish purges|series of purges]] in reaction to a [[2016 Turkish coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|failed coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]].\n*[[Rodrigo Duterte]] becomes [[President of the Philippines]], and initiates [[Philippine Drug War|a controversial drug war]].\n*[[Philippines]] wins the [[Philippines v. China|arbitration case against China]].\n*[[Andrei Karlov]], the Russian Ambassador to Turkey, [[Assassination of Andrei Karlov|is assassinated]] at an art exhibition in Ankara.\n*Detection of [[gravitational wave]]s by [[LIGO]] confirmed.\n*[[July 2016 Dhaka attack|Dhaka attack]] kills 29 people.\n*A shooter [[Orlando nightclub shooting|kills 49 people]] at a gay nightclub in [[Orlando, Florida]].\n*[[2016 Southern Taiwan earthquake]].\n*[[Tsai Ing-wen]] is [[2016 Taiwanese presidential election|elected]] [[President of the Republic of China|President of Taiwan]].\n*[[2016 attack on the Saudi diplomatic missions in Iran]].\n*[[2016 Russian Defence Ministry Tupolev Tu-154 crash]].\n*[[Burial of Ferdinand Marcos]].\n*Deaths of [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Muhammad Ali]], [[David Bowie]], [[Carrie Fisher]], [[Alan Rickman]], [[George Michael]], [[Debbie Reynolds]], [[Gene Wilder]], [[Death and state funeral of Fidel Castro|Fidel Castro]], [[Nancy Reagan]], [[Harper Lee]], [[Anton Yelchin]], [[Alan Thicke]], [[Arnold Palmer]], [[John Glenn]], [[Florence Henderson]], [[Doris Roberts]], [[Elie Wiesel]], [[Merle Haggard]], [[Leonard Cohen]], [[Garry Marshall]], [[Glenn Frey]], [[Garry Shandling]], [[Gwen Ifill]], [[Morley Safer]], [[Christina Grimmie]], [[German Moreno]], [[Miriam Defensor Santiago]], [[Death and funeral of Bhumibol Adulyadej|Bhumibol Adulyadej]], [[Shimon Peres]], and [[Antonin Scalia]].\n\n=== [[2017]] ===\n*Tensions between [[North Korea]] and the [[UN]] escalate as the country [[2017 North Korean nuclear test|tests a hydrogen bomb]] and conducts [[2017 North Korean missile tests|a series of ballistic missile tests]]. The UN responds with a wave of export sanctions.\n*A [[Manchester Arena bombing|terrorist bombing attack]] at an [[Ariana Grande]] concert in [[Manchester, England]] kills 22 people and injures over 500.\n*[[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIL) launch [[2017 Tehran attacks|simultaneous attacks]] in [[Tehran]], destroy the [[Great Mosque of al-Nuri (Mosul)|Great Mosque of al-Nuri]] in [[Mosul]] [[Iraq]], and [[2017 Sinai mosque attack|kill 311 in Egypt]], but are declared defeated in Iraq by the end of the year.\n*A [[Rohingya persecution in Myanmar (2016\u2013present)|military operation]] targeting [[Rohingya people|Rohingya Muslims]] in [[Myanmar]] is declared [[ethnic cleansing]] by the [[UNHCR]].\n*A [[14 October 2017 Mogadishu bombings|bombing in Mogadishu, Somalia]] on October 14, kills 587 people and injures 316. It is one of the deadliest terrorist attacks in modern history.\n*[[Hurricane Harvey]] kills 107 and becomes the costliest hurricane in US history, while [[Hurricane Irma]] kills 134, and [[Hurricane Maria]] kills 3,059.\n*Two earthquakes strike Mexico on [[2017 Chiapas earthquake|7 September]] and [[2017 Central Mexico earthquake|19 September]], killing more than 350.\n*[[2017 Iraqi Kurdistan independence referendum|Kurdistan and]] [[2017 Catalan independence referendum|Catalonia declare independence]] from Iraq and [[Spain]], respectively. Catalonia is not recognised, and [[2017 Iraqi\u2013Kurdish conflict|Iraq engages the Kurds in conflict]].\n*[[Robert Mugabe]] is ousted in a [[2017 Zimbabwean coup d'\u00e9tat|coup d'\u00e9tat]], while [[Ratko Mladi\u0107]] is declared guilty of genocide.\n*The city of [[Charlottesville, Virginia|Charlottesville]] is [[Unite the Right rally|the site of a far-right rally]] protesting the removal of [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] statues throughout the US. During the event, a white supremacist rams his car into a crowd of counter-protesters, injuring 19 and killing one.\n*[[2017 Las Vegas shooting|58 people are killed in a mass shooting in Las Vegas]].\n*[[Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse allegations|Allegations of sexual abuse]] against [[film producer]] [[Harvey Weinstein]] lead to a [[Weinstein effect|wave of similar accusations]] from within [[Hollywood]] and other areas of primarily the English-speaking world.\n*[[Grenfell Tower fire]] in London kills 72 and injures 70.\n*[['Oumuamua]], the first known [[interstellar object]], is identified.\n*[[Proclamation No. 216|Martial law]] declared in Mindanao following [[Marawi crisis|clashes between government forces and the Maute group in Marawi]].\n*[[2017 Resorts World Manila attack|36 people are killed in an attack in Resorts World Manila]].\n*The [[President of South Korea]], [[Park Geun-hye]], is impeached.\n*A [[2017 Venezuelan constitutional crisis|constitutional crisis]] occurs in Venezuela after [[2017 Venezuelan Constituent Assembly election|Constituent Assembly elections]] which replaced the legislative powers held by the opposition-led [[National Assembly (Venezuela)|National Assembly]].\n*Deaths of [[Chester Bennington]], [[Chuck Berry]], [[Chris Cornell]], [[Tom Petty]], [[Mary Tyler Moore]], [[Glen Campbell]], [[John Hurt]], [[Roger Moore]], [[Erin Moran]], [[Jerry Lewis]], [[Bill Paxton]], [[Don Rickles]], [[Fats Domino]], [[Sam Shepard]], [[Adam West]], [[Hugh Hefner]], [[Dick Gregory]], [[Monty Hall]], [[David Cassidy]], [[Della Reese]], [[Manuel Noriega]], [[Kim Jong-hyun (singer)|Kim Jong-hyun]], [[Ricardo Vidal]], [[Lil Peep]], [[Isabel Granada]] and [[Jake LaMotta]].\n\n=== [[2018]] ===\n*[[Turkey]] [[Operation Olive Branch|invades northern Syria]], while 70 die in [[Douma chemical attack|a chemical attack]], triggering a [[2018 missile strikes against Syria|missile strike]] against [[Bashar al-Assad]].\n*The first monkeys are [[Cloning|cloned]], and first genetically modified humans reported, in China.\n*[[Jacob Zuma]] resigns as [[President of South Africa]]; [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] becomes President. [[Scott Morrison]] becomes [[Prime Minister of Australia]].\n*Four people are poisoned, one to death, in [[Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal|Salisbury]] and [[2018 Amesbury poisonings|Amesbury]], England in a suspected Russian assassination attempt. The British government responds by leading the international expulsion of 153 Russian diplomats.\n*[[March for Our Lives]] occurs in 900 locations worldwide in response to the [[Stoneman Douglas High School shooting|Parkland shooting]].\n*The [[northern white rhinoceros]] becomes [[functionally extinct]].\n*[[Pakatan Harapan]] becomes the first opposition party to assume power in [[Malaysia]] since independence.\n*The first summit between [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States summit|the USA and North Korea]] and the first ever crossing of the [[Korean Demilitarized Zone]] by a North Korean leader occur.\n*Twenty-year [[Eritrean\u2013Ethiopian border conflict]] formally ends.\n*[[Yellow vests movement]] becomes [[France]]'s largest sustained period of civil unrest since 1968.\n*[[2018 Sunda Strait tsunami|Sunda strait tsunami]] kills 426 and injures 14,000.\n*[[2018 Sulawesi earthquake and tsunami]] kills 4,340 and injures 10,700.\n* Exiled ''[[Washington Post]]'' journalist [[Jamal Khashoggi]] is [[Assassination of Jamal Khashoggi|assassinated]] inside the Saudi consulate in Istanbul, triggering a [[Reactions to the assassination of Jamal Khashoggi|diplomatic crisis]] for Saudi Arabia.\n*[[Kerch Strait incident]] triggers martial law in [[Ukraine]].\n*[[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]] and [[Greece]] reach a historic agreement in the [[Macedonia naming dispute]], in which the former is renamed in 2019 to the 'Republic of North Macedonia'.\n*China's [[National People's Congress]] votes to abolish presidential [[term limits]], allowing [[Xi Jinping]] to [[President for life|rule for life]]. Xi is also the [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], the [[Paramount leader|highest position]] without term limits.\n*[[Wedding of Prince Harry and Meghan Markle]].\n*[[2018 Armenian revolution]] happens in Armenia and improves country's democratic indexes. The revolution is known to be very peaceful due to its high civic sense.\n*[[2018 Iraqi parliamentary election|First post-ISIS election in Iraq]].\n*Twelve boys and their football coach are successfully [[Tham Luang cave rescue|rescued]] from the flooded [[Tham Luang Nang Non]] cave in [[Thailand]].\n*[[France]] wins the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.\n*[[2018 Boracay closure and redevelopment]].\n*[[Quo warranto petition against Maria Lourdes Sereno]].\n*[[Balangiga bells#Repatriation|Return of the Balangiga bells]].\n*[[Catriona Gray]] of the Philippines is crowned [[Miss Universe 2018]].\n*[[Bill Cosby]] is [[Bill Cosby sexual assault cases|found guilty of sexual assault and sentenced to three to ten years in prison]].\n*Deaths of [[Stephen Hawking]], [[Stan Lee]], [[Aretha Franklin]], [[Burt Reynolds]], [[Avicii]], [[Kate Spade]], [[Verne Troyer]], [[Anthony Bourdain]], [[Barbara Bush]], [[John McCain]], [[Death and state funeral of George H. W. Bush|George H.W. Bush]], [[XXXTentacion]], [[Mac Miller]], [[Dolores O\u2019Riordan]], [[Penny Marshall]], [[Stephen Hillenburg]], [[Billy Graham]], [[Mark Salling]], [[Paul Allen]], [[Philip Roth]], [[Linda Carol Brown|Linda Brown]], [[Nancy Wilson (jazz singer)|Nancy Wilson]], [[Charles Aznavour]], [[Kofi Annan]], [[Winnie Mandela]], [[Rico J. Puno]], [[Roilo Golez]] and [[Neil Simon]].\n\n=== [[2019]] ===\n*[[Jair Bolsonaro]] becomes [[President of Brazil]].\n*[[New Horizons]] takes the first close up image of a [[486958 Arrokoth|classical kuiper belt object]].\n*[[Chang'e 4]] becomes the first object to land on the [[far side of the Moon]].\n*[[2019\u201420 Bolivian protests|Protests erupt in Bolivia]] [[2019 Venezuelan presidential crisis|and Venezuela]] over [[2018 Venezuelan presidential election|disputed]] [[2019 Bolivian general election|elections]].\n*[[Nursultan Nazarbayev]] resigns as [[President of Kazakhstan]]. [[Kassym-Jomart Tokayev]] assumes power. [[Astana]] is renamed [[Nur-Sultan]] in his honor.\n*[[Christchurch mosque shootings]] kill 51 people, while a [[2019 Khash\u2013Zahedan suicide bombing|suicide bombing in Iran]] kills 41, and a [[2019 Sri Lanka Easter bombings|series of bomb attacks]] in [[Sri Lanka]] kills 250.\n*The [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] loses the last of its territory.\n*The EU [[Directive on Copyright in the Digital Single Market]] is passed over intense opposition.\n*[[Abdelaziz Bouteflika]] resigns as [[President of Algeria]], while [[Omar al-Bashir]] is deposed as [[President of Sudan]] in [[2019 Sudanese coup d'\u00e9tat|a coup d'\u00e9tat]] amid [[2019 Algerian protests|widespread protests]] [[2018\u201319 Sudanese protests|in both countries]].\n*The [[Event Horizon Telescope]] takes the first ever image of a [[black hole]], at the core of galaxy [[Messier 87]].\n*[[Volodymyr Zelensky]] becomes [[President of Ukraine]].\n*[[Victor Vescovo]] breaks the human depth record, reaching 10,928&nbsp;m in the [[Challenger Deep]].\n*[[Akihito]] [[2019 Japanese imperial transition|abdicates]] as [[Emperor of Japan]]; [[Naruhito]] becomes Emperor.\n*[[Bashar al Assad]] launches [[Northwestern Syria offensive (April\u2013August 2019)|multiple offensives]] [[Northwestern Syria offensive (November 2019\u2013present)|in Northwestern Syria]]; [[Turkey]] launches [[2019 Turkish offensive into north-eastern Syria|an offensive into northeastern Syria]].\n*[[Khartoum massacre|More than a hundred people are killed]] after police and [[Janjaweed]] attack protesters in Sudan.\n*The United States blames [[June 2019 Gulf of Oman incident|attacks on ships in the Gulf of Oman]] on Iran, escalating [[2019\u201320 Persian Gulf crisis|tensions in the Persian Gulf]].\n*[[Kyriakos Mitsotakis]] becomes [[Prime Minister of Greece]].\n*[[Boris Johnson]] becomes [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]], and attempts a [[2019 British prorogation controversy|prorogation of Parliament]] that is [[R (Miller) v The Prime Minister and Cherry v Advocate General for Scotland|ultimately declared unlawful]].\n*[[2019-2020 Hong Kong protests|Protests begin]] in [[Hong Kong]] over an extradition bill.\n*[[India]] [[Revocation of the special status of Jammu and Kashmir|revokes the special status of Jammu and Kashmir]].\n*[[Barisha raid]] ends in the [[Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi|death of Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi]].\n*[[2019 Albania earthquake|A 6.4 magnitude earthquake]] in [[Albania]], kills 51 people.\n*[[Citizenship Amendment Act protests|Protests erupt in India]] over the passing of the [[Citizenship (Amendment) Act, 2019|Citizenship Amendment Act]].\n*[[2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires|Wildfires spike]] in [[Brazil]], while [[Australia]] endures the [[2019\u201320 Australian bushfire season|most widespread brush fires in its history]].\n*A major [[Notre-Dame de Paris fire|fire]] engulfs [[Notre-Dame de Paris|Notre-Dame Cathedral]] in Paris, resulting in the roof and main spire collapsing.\n*A [[2019 Jolo Cathedral bombings|series of suicide bombings]] [[2019 Indanan bombings|occurred in Sulu]].\n*The [[Murders of Eileen Sarmenta and Allan Gomez|June 1993 rape and murder case of Eileen Sarmenta and Allan Gomez]] is reopened due to the impending release of former [[Calauan, Laguna|Calauan]] mayor [[Antonio Sanchez (politician)|Antonio Sanchez]].\n*An [[2019\u20132020 Philippines polio outbreak|outbreak of polio]] is declared in the Philippines, 19 years following its eradication in the country.\n*The [[President of the United States]], [[Donald Trump]], is [[Impeachment of Donald Trump|impeached]].\n*[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] begins in [[Wuhan]], China.\n*Deaths of [[Jacques Chirac]], [[Robert Mugabe]], [[Mohamed Morsi]], [[Zine El Abidine Ben Ali]], [[Yasuhiro Nakasone]], [[Beji Caid Essebsi]], [[Luke Perry]], [[Doris Day]], [[Karl Lagerfeld]], [[Cameron Boyce]], [[Tim Conway]], [[Gloria Vanderbilt]], [[Toni Morrison]], [[John Singleton]], [[John Witherspoon (actor)|John Witherspoon,]] [[Ross Perot]], [[Valerie Harper]], [[Diahann Carroll]], [[Peter Mayhew]], [[Caroll Spinney]], [[Ric Ocasek]], [[Danny Aiello]], [[Peter Fonda]], [[Cokie Roberts]], [[Henry Sy]], [[Eddie Garcia]], [[Goo Hara]], [[Aquilino Pimentel Jr.]], [[Gina Lopez]], [[Elijah Cummings]] and [[Juice Wrld]].\n\n== [[2020s]] ==\n<!-- do not add anything from the current year until after it is complete -->\n{{for|the current year|{{CURRENTYEAR}}|{{CURRENTYEAR}} in politics and government}}<!-- do not add new material until the current year is ended. -->\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Timeline of the 20th century]]\n* [[21st century in fiction]]\n* [[Timelines of the future]]\n\n{{21st century}}\n\n[[Category:21st century|*]]\n[[Category:Contemporary history timelines|*]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia timelines|*]]\n", "name_user": "2605:b100:713:180a:1156:41c1:9e5d:6d9c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200e2019)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_the_21st_century"}
{"title_page": "Laura Ingalls Wilder", "text_new": "{{short description|American writer, teacher, and journalist}}\n{{Redirect2|Laura Ingalls|Laura Wilder|other persons|Laura Ingalls (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Laura Ingalls Wilder\n| image       = Laura Ingalls Wilder cropped sepia2.jpg\n| caption     = Laura Ingalls Wilder, circa 1885\n| birth_name  = Laura Elizabeth Ingalls\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1867|02|07}}\n| birth_place = [[Pepin County, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1957|02|10|1867|02|07}}\n| death_place = [[Mansfield, Missouri]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Writer, teacher, journalist, family farmer\n| nationality = American\n| period      = 1911\u20131957 (as a writer)\n| genre       = Diaries, essays, [[family saga]] ([[Children's literature|children's]] [[historical novels]])\n| subject<!-- designed for nonfiction -->     = [[Midwestern United States|Midwestern]] and [[Western United States|Western]]\n| movement    =\n| notableworks = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Little House on the Prairie (novel)|Little House on the Prairie]]''\n* [[List of Little House on the Prairie books|Little House series]]\n}}\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Almanzo Wilder]] |1885|1949|end=d.}}\n| children    = {{Plainlist|\n* 2, [[Rose Wilder Lane]] and Unnamed Male Infant}}\n| relatives   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Charles Ingalls|Charles Phillip Ingalls]] <small>(father)</small>\n* [[Caroline Ingalls|Caroline Lake Quiner]] <small>(mother)</small>\n* [[Mary Ingalls|Mary Amelia Ingalls]] <small>(sister)</small>\n* [[Carrie Ingalls|Caroline Celestia \"Carrie\" Ingalls Swansey]] <small>(sister)</small>\n* [[Caroline Ingalls#Freddie Ingalls|Charles Frederick \"Freddie\" Ingalls]] <small>(brother)</small>\n* [[Grace Ingalls|Grace Pearl Ingalls Dow]] <small>(sister)</small>}}\n| awards      = {{Awards | [[Laura Ingalls Wilder Medal]] |est. 1954}}\n| signature   = Laura Ingalls Wilder signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Laura Elizabeth Ingalls Wilder''' (February 7, 1867 \u2013 February 10, 1957) was an American writer known for the ''[[Little House on the Prairie]]'' series of children's books, published between 1932 and 1943, which were based on her childhood in a [[settler]] and [[American pioneer|pioneer]] family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Laura-Ingalls-Wilder|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder {{!}} Biography, Books, & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1970s and early 1980s, the television series ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' was loosely based on the Little House books, and starred [[Melissa Gilbert]] as Laura and [[Michael Landon]] as her father, [[Charles Ingalls]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Little House on the Prairie|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0071007/|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\n==Birth and ancestry==\n[[File:Caroline and Charles Ingalls sepia cropped.jpg|thumb|Caroline and Charles Ingalls]]\nLaura Elizabeth Ingalls was born to [[Charles Ingalls|Charles Phillip]] and [[Caroline Ingalls|Caroline Lake (n\u00e9e Quiner) Ingalls]] on February 7, 1867.  At the time of Ingalls' birth, the family lived seven miles north of the village of [[Pepin, Wisconsin]] in the [[Big Woods]] region of [[Wisconsin]]. Ingalls' home in Pepin became the setting for her first book, ''[[Little House in the Big Woods]]''.<ref name=\"pepin\">{{cite web |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder |url=http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/topics/wilder/index.asp |publisher=Wisconsin Historical Society |website=wisconsinhistory.org |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210135806/http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/topics/wilder/index.asp|archive-date=February 10, 2007}}</ref>  She was the second of five children, following older sister, [[Mary Ingalls|Mary Amelia]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Benge |first=Janet and Geoff |url=https://books.google.com/?id=hbdPbFVxE7oC |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder: A Storybook Life |page=180 |publisher=YWAM Publishing |year=2005 |isbn=1-932096-32-9}}</ref><ref>[http://www.aap.org/en-us/about-the-aap/aap-press-room/Pages/What-Really-Caused-Mary-Ingalls-to-Go-Blind.aspx \"What Really Caused Mary Ingalls to Go Blind?\"]. February 4, 2013. [[American Academy of Pediatrics]]. Press release announcing Allexan, et al.:<br /> \u2022 {{cite journal|author1=Allexan, Sarah S. |author2=Byington, Carrie L. |author3=Finkelstein, Jerome I. |author4=Tarini, Beth A. | title = Blindness in Walnut Grove: How Did Mary Ingalls Lose Her Sight? | journal = Pediatrics | volume = 131 |issue=3 |date=March 1, 2013 |pages=404\u201306 |doi=10.1542/peds.2012-1438|pmid=23382439 |pmc=4074664 }}</ref><ref name=NYT>{{cite news |first= KJ |last= Dell'Antonia |title= Scarlet Fever Probably Didn't Blind Mary Ingalls |url= http://parenting.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/04/scarlet-fever-probably-didnt-blind-mary-ingalls/ |newspaper=The New York Times |date= February 4, 2013 |accessdate= February 4, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=USNews>{{cite news |first= Gordon |last= Serena |title= Mistaken Infection 'On The Prairie'? |url= http://health.usnews.com/health-news/news/articles/2013/02/04/mistaken-infection-on-the-prairie |publisher=HealthDay; [[U.S. News & World Report]] (usnews.com/health-news) |date= February 4, 2013 |accessdate= February 4, 2013 }}</ref> Three more children would follow, [[Carrie Ingalls|Caroline Celestia (Carrie)]], [[Caroline Ingalls#Freddie Ingalls|Charles Frederick]], who died in infancy, and [[Grace Ingalls|Grace Pearl]]. Ingalls Wilder's birth site is commemorated by a replica [[log cabin]] at the [[Little House Wayside]] in Pepin.<ref name=\"VisitPepinCounty\">{{cite web |url=http://visitpepincounty.com/Laura.pdf |title=Laura.pdf |publisher=Little House Wayside; Pepin, Wisconsin (visitpepincounty.com) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref> Her life in Pepin formed the basis for her first book, ''Little House in the Big Woods'' (1932).<ref name=pepin/>\n\nIngalls was a descendant of the [[Delano family]], the ancestral family of [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Franklin Delano Roosevelt]].<ref name=\"genealogymagazine\">{{cite web |author1=Gormley, Myra Vanderpool |author2=Rhonda R. McClure |url=http://www.genealogymagazine.com/ingalls.html|title=A Genealogical Look at Laura Ingalls Wilder |publisher=GenealogyMagazine.com |accessdate=October 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmund-rice.org/era5gens/p34.htm#i1065|title=Eunice Sleeman |publisher= Edmund Rice (1638) Association (edmund-rice.org) |date=2002 |quote=Eunice Sleeman was the mother of Eunice Blood (1782\u20131862), the wife of Nathan Colby (born 1778), who were the parents of [[Charles Phillip Ingalls|Laura Louise Colby Ingalls (1810\u20131883)]], Ingalls' paternal grandmother |accessdate=April 20, 2010}}</ref> One paternal ancestor, Edmund Ingalls, from [[Skirbeck]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]],  emigrated to [[Thirteen Colonies|America]], settling in [[Lynn, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\"genealogymagazine\" />\n\nShe was a third cousin, once removed, of President [[Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mayflowerhistory.com/famous-descendants/|title=Famous Descendants|website=MayflowerHistory.com}}</ref>\n\n===Early life===\nWhen she was two years old, Ingalls Wilder moved with her family from Wisconsin in 1869. After stopping in [[Rothville, Missouri]], they settled in the [[Indian country]] of [[Kansas]], near modern day [[Independence, Kansas#History|Independence, Kansas]]. Her younger sister, [[Carrie Ingalls|Carrie]], was born in Independence in August 1870, not long before they moved again. According to Ingalls Wilder, her father Charles Ingalls had been told that the location would be open to white settlers, but when they arrived this was not the case. The Ingalls family had no legal right to occupy their homestead because it was on the [[Osage Nation|Osage Indian]] reservation. They had just begun to farm when they heard rumors that settlers would be evicted, so they left in the spring of 1871. Although in her novel, ''[[Little House on the Prairie (novel)|Little House on the Prairie]],'' and ''Pioneer Girl'' memoir, Ingalls Wilder portrayed their departure as being prompted by rumors of eviction, she also noted that her parents needed to recover their Wisconsin land because the buyer had not paid the mortgage.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Kaye |first=Frances W. |title=Little Squatter on the Osage Diminished Reserve: Reading Laura Ingalls Wilder's Kansas Indians |journal=Great Plains Quarterly |volume=20 |issue=2 |year=2000 |pages=123\u2013140 |doi= |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1022&context=greatplainsquarterly }}</ref>\n\nThe Ingalls family went back to Wisconsin where they lived for the next three years. Those experiences formed the basis for Wilder's novels ''Little House in the Big Woods'' (1932) and ''[[Little House on the Prairie (novel)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' (1935).\n\n''[[On the Banks of Plum Creek]]'' (1937), the third volume of her fictionalized history which takes place around 1874, the Ingalls family moves from Kansas to an area near [[Walnut Grove, Minnesota]], settling in a [[Dugout (shelter)|dugout]] on the banks of [[Plum Creek (Cottonwood River)|Plum Creek]].<ref name=\"archives\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Timeline |work=Laura Ingalls Wilder |publisher=The Herbert Hoover Presidential Library and Museum; National Archives and Records Administration (hoover.archives.gov) |accessdate=October 25, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025222424/http://www.hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html |archive-date=October 25, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They moved there from Wisconsin when Ingalls was about seven years old, after briefly living with the family of her uncle, Peter Ingalls, first in Wisconsin and then on rented land near [[Lake City, Minnesota]]. In Walnut Grove, the family first lived in a dugout sod house on a [[Preemption (land)|preemption]] claim; after wintering in it, they moved into a new house built on the same land. Two summers of ruined crops led them to move to [[Iowa]]. On the way, they stayed again with Charles Ingalls' brother, Peter Ingalls, this time on his farm near [[South Troy, Minnesota]]. Her brother, Charles Frederick Ingalls (\"Freddie\"), was born there on November 1, 1875, dying nine months later in August 1876. In [[Burr Oak, Iowa]], the family helped run a hotel. The youngest of the Ingalls children, [[Grace Ingalls|Grace]], was born there on May 23, 1877.\n\nThe family moved from Burr Oak back to Walnut Grove where Charles Ingalls served as the town butcher and [[justice of the peace]]. He accepted a railroad job in the spring of 1879, which took him to eastern [[Dakota Territory]], where they joined him that fall. Ingalls Wilder omitted the period in 1876\u20131877 when they lived near Burr Oak, skipping to Dakota Territory, portrayed in ''[[By the Shores of Silver Lake]]'' (1939).\n\n===De Smet===\n[[File:Laura ingalls wilder museum surveyor's house desmet sd.jpg|thumb|right|Surveyor's House, the first home in Dakota Territory of the Charles Ingalls family - De Smet, South Dakota]]\nWilder's father filed for a [[Homestead Act|formal homestead]] over the winter of 1879\u20131880.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archives.gov/research/land/ingalls|title=Land Records: Ingalls Homestead File|date=August 15, 2016|website=National Archives|access-date=13 June 2019}}</ref> [[De Smet, South Dakota]], became her parents' and sister Mary's home for the remainder of their lives. After spending the mild winter of 1879\u20131880 in the surveyor's house, they watched the town of De Smet rise up from the prairie in 1880. The following winter, 1880\u20131881, one of the most severe on record in the Dakotas, was later described by Ingalls Wilder in her novel, ''[[The Long Winter (novel)|The Long Winter]]'' (1940). Once the family was settled in De Smet, Ingalls attended school, worked several part-time jobs, and made friends. Among them was bachelor homesteader [[Almanzo Wilder]]. This time in her life is documented in the books ''[[Little Town on the Prairie]]'' (1941) and ''[[These Happy Golden Years]]'' (1943).\n\n===Young teacher===\nOn December 10, 1882, two months before her 16th birthday, Ingalls accepted her first teaching position.<ref>{{cite web|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Timeline|url=https://hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html|website=Herbert Hoover Presidential Library & Museum|publisher=Herbert Hoover Presidential Library & Museum|accessdate=January 27, 2017}}</ref> She taught three terms in [[one-room school]]s when she was not attending school in De Smet. (In ''Little Town on the Prairie'' she receives her first teaching certificate on December 24, 1882, but that was an enhancement for dramatic effect.{{Citation needed|date=November 2011|reason=How was it an enhancement?}}) Her original \"Third Grade\" teaching certificate can be seen on page 25 of William Anderson's book ''Laura's Album'' (1998).<ref>{{cite book|author=Anderson, William|title=Laura's Album|date=1998|publisher=Harper Collins}}</ref> She later admitted she did not particularly enjoy it, but felt a responsibility from a young age to help her family financially, and wage-earning opportunities for women were limited. Between 1883 and 1885, she taught three terms of school, worked for the local dressmaker, and attended high school, although she did not graduate.\n\n===Early marriage years===\n[[File:Rose wilder lane birthplace roadside marker.jpg|thumb|right|Rose Wilder Lane birthplace roadside marker - DeSmet]]\n[[File:Laura and Almanzo Wilder 1885 retouched sepia.jpg|thumb|left|upright=.6|Laura and Almanzo Wilder, circa 1885]]\n[[File:Rose wilder lane birthplace desmet sd 2b.jpg|thumb|right|Location of Wilder homestead where both of Wilder's children were born - DeSmet]]\nIngalls' teaching career and studies ended when the 18-year-old Laura married 28-year-old Almanzo Wilder on August 25, 1885, tbe ceremony officiated by a Rev Edward Brown, a first cousin of the celebrated John Brown.<ref name=\"WfH\" /> From the beginning of their relationship, the pair had nicknames for each other: she called him \"Manly\" and he, because he had a sister named Laura, called her \"Bessie\", from her middle name, Elizabeth.<ref name=\"WfH\">{{cite book | first1=Laura Ingalls | last1=Wilder | title=West from Home: Letters of Laura Ingalls Wilder, San Francisco, 1915 | publisher=HarperCollins | date=1974 | last2=Wilder | first2=Almanzo | page=xvii}}</ref> Almanzo had achieved a degree of prosperity on his homestead claim;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-mteBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT99&dq=Almanzo+Wilder+prosperous#v=onepage&q=Almanzo%20Wilder%20prosperous&f=false|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder: American Writer on the Prairie|last=Ketcham|first=Sallie|date=September 16, 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136725739|language=en}}</ref> the newly married couple started their life together in a new home, north of De Smet.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/08/10/wilder-women|title=Wilder Women|last=Thurman|first=Judith|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 1886, Wilder gave birth to her daughter, [[Rose Wilder Lane|Rose]].  In 1889, she gave birth to a son who died at 12 days of age before being named. He was buried at De Smet, Kingsbury County, South Dakota.<ref name=\"Laura Ingalls Wilder Timeline\">{{cite web |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Timeline |website=hoover.archives.gov |url=https://www.hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html |publisher=The Herbert Hoover Presidential Library and Museum |location=West Branch, IA, US |accessdate=June 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525034756/http://www.hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html |archive-date=May 25, 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"De Smet Info\">{{cite web |title=De Smet Info |website=ingallshomestead.com |url=http://www.ingallshomestead.com/de-smet-info/ |accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> On the grave marker, he is remembered as \"Baby Son of A. J. Wilder\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=JGjYAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Baby+Son+of+A.+J.+Wilder%22&dq=%22Baby+Son+of+A.+J.+Wilder%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJpuyO64vmAhWwna0KHf4jCRcQ6AEIMDAB|title=Christian Living: A Magazine for Home and Community|date=March 3, 1963|publisher=Mennonite Publishing House|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nTheir first few years of marriage were difficult. Complications from a life-threatening bout of [[diphtheria]] left Almanzo partially [[paralysis|paralyzed]]. Although he eventually regained nearly full use of his legs, he needed a cane to walk for the remainder of his life. This setback, among many others, began a series of unfortunate events that included the death of their newborn son, the destruction of their barn along with its hay and grain by a mysterious fire,<ref>Miller 1998, p. 80.</ref> the total loss of their home from a fire accidentally set by Rose,<ref>Miller 1998, p. 84.</ref> and several years of severe [[drought]] that left them in debt, physically ill, and unable to earn a living from their 320 acres (129.5 hectares) of prairie land. These trials were documented in Wilder's book ''[[The First Four Years (novel)|The First Four Years]]'' (published in 1971). Around 1890, they left De Smet and spent about a year resting at the home of Almanzo's parents on their [[Spring Valley, Minnesota]], farm before moving briefly to [[Westville, Florida]], in search of a climate to improve Almanzo's health. They found, however, that the dry plains they were used to were very different from the humidity they encountered in Westville. The weather, along with feeling out of place among the locals, encouraged their return to De Smet in 1892, where they purchased a small home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.minnpost.com/mnopedia/2014/08/story-behind-stories-laura-ingalls-wilders-life-minnesota-and-beyond/|title=The story behind the stories: Laura Ingalls Wilder\u2019s life in Minnesota and beyond|date=2014-08-19|website=MinnPost|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2018/04/19/laura-ingalls-wilder-and-wilder/|title=Wilder and Wilder|last=Messud|first=Claire|date=2018-04-19|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en|issn=0028-7504}}</ref>\n\n==Move to Mansfield, Missouri==\n[[File:LauraIngallsWilder-RockyRidgeFarm-MansfieldMO adjusted.jpg|thumb|right|Rocky Ridge Farm, Mansfield, Missouri]]\n\nIn 1894, the Wilders moved to [[Mansfield, Missouri]], and used their savings to make the [[down payment]] on an undeveloped property just outside town. They named the place [[Laura Ingalls Wilder House|Rocky Ridge Farm]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Laura's Life on Rocky Ridge Farm | website=Laura Ingalls Wilder Historic Home & Museum | date=November 5, 2012 | url=http://www.lauraingallswilderhome.com/?page_id=452 | ref={{sfnref | Laura Ingalls Wilder Historic Home & Museum | 2012}} | accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref> and moved into a ramshackle log cabin. At first, they earned income only from wagon loads of fire wood they would sell in town for 50 cents.  Financial security came slowly. Apple trees they planted did not bear fruit for seven years. Almanzo's parents visited around that time and gave them the deed to the house they had been renting in Mansfield, which was the economic boost Wilder's family needed. They then added to the property outside town, and eventually accrued nearly 200 acres (80.9 hectares). Around 1910, they sold the house in town, moved back to the farm, and completed the farmhouse with the proceeds. What began as about 40 acres (16.2 hectares) of thickly wooded, stone-covered hillside with a windowless log cabin became in 20 years a relatively prosperous poultry, dairy, and fruit farm, and a 10-room farmhouse.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=kWsrAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA69&ots=VWlFJOd3i1&dq=laura%20ingalls%20wilder%20missouri%2010%20room%20farmhouse&pg=PA69#v=onepage&q=laura%20ingalls%20wilder%20missouri%2010%20room%20farmhouse&f=false|title=Famous Americans: A Directory of Museums, Historic Sites, and Memorials|last=Danilov|first=Victor J.|date=2013-09-26|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-9186-9|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Wilders had learned from cultivating wheat as their sole crop in De Smet. They diversified Rocky Ridge Farm with poultry, a dairy farm, and a large apple orchard. Wilder became active in various clubs and was an advocate for several regional farm associations. She was recognized as an authority in poultry farming and rural living, which led to invitations to speak to groups around the region.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder, farm journalist : writings from the Ozarks|last=Wilder |first=Laura Ingalls |date=2007 |publisher=University of Missouri Press |editor-last=Hines |editor-first=Stephen W. |isbn=978-0826266156 |location=Columbia |oclc=427509646}}</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\nAn invitation to submit an article to the ''Missouri Ruralist'' in 1911 led to Wilder's permanent position as a columnist and editor with that publication, which she held until the mid-1920s. She also took a paid position with the local [[Federal Farm Loan Act|Farm Loan Association]], dispensing small loans to local farmers.\n\nWilder's column in the ''Ruralist'', \"As a Farm Woman Thinks\", introduced her to a loyal audience of rural [[Ozarks|Ozarkians]], who enjoyed her regular columns. Her topics ranged from home and family, including her 1915 trip to [[San Francisco, California]], to visit Rose Lane and the Pan-Pacific exhibition, to [[World War I]] and other world events, and to the fascinating world travels of Lane as well as her own thoughts on the increasing options offered to women during this era. While the couple were never wealthy until the \"Little House\" books began to achieve popularity, the farming operation and Wilder's income from writing and the Farm Loan Association provided them with a stable living.\n\n\"[By] 1924\", according to the Professor John E. Miller, \"[a]fter more than a decade of writing for farm papers, Wilder had become a disciplined writer, able to produce thoughtful, readable prose for a general audience.\" At this time, her now-married daughter, Rose Wilder Lane, helped her publish two articles describing the interior of the farmhouse, in ''Country Gentleman'' magazine.<ref>Miller 1998, p. 161.</ref>\n\nIt was also around this time that Lane began intensively encouraging Wilder to improve her writing skills with a view toward greater success as a writer than Lane had already achieved.<ref>Miller 1998, p. 162.</ref>  The Wilders, according to Miller, had come to \"[depend] on annual income subsidies from their increasingly famous and successful daughter.\" They both had concluded that the solution for improving their retirement income was for Wilder to become a successful writer herself. However, the \"project never proceeded very far.\"<ref>Miller 2008, p. 24.</ref>\n\nIn 1928, Lane hired out the construction of an English-style stone cottage for her parents on property adjacent to the farmhouse they had personally built and still inhabited. She remodeled and took it over.<ref name=Miller1998-177>Miller 1998, p. 177.</ref>\n\n===''Little House'' books===\n{{main|List of Little House on the Prairie books}}\n\nThe [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|Stock Market Crash of 1929]] wiped the Wilders out; Lane's investments were devastated as well. They still owned the 200-acre (81-hectare) farm, but they had invested most of their savings with Lane's broker. In 1930, Wilder requested Lane's opinion about an autobiographical manuscript she had written about her pioneering childhood. The [[Great Depression]], coupled with the deaths of Wilder's mother in 1924 and her older sister in 1928, seem to have prompted her to preserve her memories in a life story called ''Pioneer Girl''. She also hoped that her writing would generate some additional income. The original title of the first of the books was ''When Grandma Was a Little Girl''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Students visiting Wilder's prairie|last=Hines-Dochterman|first=Meredith|date=30 September 2005|work=St. Joseph News-Press|access-date=}}</ref> On the advice of Lane's publisher, she greatly expanded the story. As a result of Lane's publishing connections as a successful writer and after editing by her, [[Harper (publisher)#Harper & Brothers (1833\u20131962)|Harper & Brothers]] published Wilder's book in 1932 as ''Little House in the Big Woods''. After its success, she continued writing. The close and often rocky collaboration between her and Lane continued, in person until 1935, when Lane permanently left Rocky Ridge Farm, and afterward by correspondence.\n\nThe collaboration worked both ways: two of Lane's most successful novels, ''Let the Hurricane Roar'' (1932) and ''Free Land'' (1938), were written at the same time as the \"Little House\" series and basically retold Ingalls and Wilder family tales in an adult format.<ref name=Miller2008-40>Miller 2008, p. 40.</ref>\n\n====Authorship controversy====\nSome, including Lane's biographer, William Holtz, have alleged that Wilder's daughter was her ghostwriter.<ref>Holtz 1993.{{full citation needed|date=October 2015}}<!-- page needed --></ref>  Existing evidence includes ongoing correspondence between the women about the books' development, Lane's extensive diaries, and Wilder's handwritten manuscripts with edit notations shows an ongoing collaboration between the two women.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nMiller, using this record, describes varying levels of involvement by Lane. ''[[Little House in the Big Woods]]'' (1932) and ''[[These Happy Golden Years]]'' (1943), he notes, received the least editing. \"The first pages&nbsp;... and other large sections of [''Big Woods'']\", he observes, \"stand largely intact, indicating&nbsp;... from the start&nbsp;...[Laura's] talent for narrative description.\"<ref>Miller 1998, pp. 6, 190.</ref>  Some volumes saw heavier participation by Lane,<ref>Miller 2008, pp. 37 et seq.</ref> while [[The First Four Years (novel)|''The First Four Years'']] (1971) appears to be exclusively a Wilder work.<ref name=thurman2009>{{cite web |author=Thurman, Judith |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/atlarge/2009/08/10/090810crat_atlarge_thurman?currentPage=paragraph-29 |title=Wilder Women: The mother and daughter behind the Little House stories |date=August 10, 2009 |work=The New Yorker |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\nConcludes Miller, \"In the end, the lasting literary legacy remains that of the mother more than that of the daughter&nbsp;... Lane possessed style; Wilder had substance.\"<ref name=Miller2008-40/>\n\nThe controversy over authorship is often tied to the movement to read the Little House series through an ideological lens. Lane emerged in the 1930s as an avowed conservative polemicist and critic of the [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] administration and his [[New Deal]] programs. According to a 2012 article in the ''New Yorker'', \"When Roosevelt was elected, she noted in her diary, 'America has a dictator.' She prayed for his assassination, and considered doing the job herself.\"<ref name=thurman2012>{{cite web |author=Thurman, Judith |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/a-libertarian-house-on-the-prairie |title=A Libertarian House on the Prairie |date=August 16, 2012 |work=The New Yorker |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref> Whatever Lane's politics, \"attacks on [Wilder's] authorship seem aimed at infusing her books with ideological passions they just don't have.\"<ref name=\"salon.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/10/10/little_house_on_the_prairie_tea_party_manifesto |title='Little House on the Prairie': Tea Party manifesto |author=Fraser, Caroline |work=Los Angeles Review of Books |date=October 10, 2012 |via=''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' (salon.com) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n====Enduring appeal====\nThe original Little House books, written for [[elementary school]]\u2013age children, became an enduring, eight-volume record of pioneering life late in the 19th century based on the Ingalls family's experiences on the American frontier. ''The First Four Years'', about the early days of the Wilder marriage, was discovered by her literary executor [[Roger MacBride]] after Lane's 1968 death and published in 1971, unedited by Lane or MacBride. It is now marketed as the ninth volume.<ref name=thurman2009/>\n\nSince the publication of ''Little House in the Big Woods'' (1932), the books have been continuously in print and have been translated into 40 other languages. Wilder's first\u2014and smallest\u2014royalty check from Harper, in 1932, was for $500, {{Inflation|US|500|1932|r=-1|fmt=eq}}. By the mid-1930s the royalties from the ''Little House'' books brought a steady and increasingly substantial income to the Wilders for the first time in their 50 years of marriage. The collaboration also brought the two writers at Rocky Ridge Farm the money they needed to recoup the loss of their investments in the stock market. Various honors, huge amounts of fan mail, and other accolades were bestowed on Wilder.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n===Autobiography: ''Pioneer Girl''===\nIn 1929\u20131930, already in her early 60s, Wilder began writing her autobiography, titled ''Pioneer Girl.'' It was rejected by publishers. At Lane's urging, she rewrote most of her stories for children. The result was the ''Little House'' series of books. In 2014, the [[South Dakota State Historical Society]] published an annotated version of Wilder's autobiography, titled ''Pioneer Girl: The Annotated Autobiography''.<ref name=SDHS>[http://pioneergirlproject.org/2014/11/21/pioneer-girl-is-out \"Pioneer Girl is out!\"]. November 21, 2014. Pioneer Girl Project (pioneergirlproject.org). South Dakota Historical Society Press. Retrieved October 15, 2015.</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Higgins\n| first = Jim\n| title = Laura Ingalls Wilder's annotated autobiography, 'Pioneer Girl,' shows writer's world, growth\n| newspaper = [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]\n| accessdate = December 23, 2014\n| date = December 5, 2014\n| url = http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/books/laura-ingalls-wilders-annotated-autobiography-pioneer-girl-shows-writers-world-growth-b99399147z1-284813631.html\n}}</ref>\n\n''Pioneer Girl'' includes stories that Wilder felt were inappropriate for children: e.g., a man accidentally immolating himself while drunk, and an incident of extreme violence of a local shopkeeper against his wife, which ended with his setting their house on fire. She also describes previously unknown facets of her father's character. According to its publisher, \"Wilder's fiction, her autobiography, and her real childhood are all distinct things, but they are closely intertwined.\" The book's aim was to explore the differences, including incidents with conflicting or non-existing accounts in one or another of the sources.<ref>{{cite news |last=Flood |first=Alison |date=August 25, 2014 |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder memoir reveals truth behind Little House on the Prairie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/aug/25/laura-ingalls-wilder-memoir-little-house-prairie |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=August 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nWilder has been referred to as one of America's first libertarians.<ref>{{cite news |last=Boaz |first=David |date=May 9, 2015 |title=The Legacy of Laura Ingalls Wilder, One of America's First Libertarians |url=https://time.com/3848967/laura-ingalls-wilder-is-back/ |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref> She was originally a life-long [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], but became dismayed with Roosevelt's New Deal and what she and her daughter, [[Rose Wilder Lane]], saw as Americans' increasing dependence on the federal government. Wilder grew disenchanted with her party and resented government agents who came to farms like hers and grilled farmers about the number of acres they were planting.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news  |last=Klein |first=Christopher |date=February 7, 2014 |title=Little Libertarians on the Prairie: The Hidden Politics Behind a Children's Classic |url=https://www.history.com/news/little-libertarians-on-the-prairie-the-hidden-politics-behind-a-childrens-classic |work=History.com |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref> Her daughter was similarly strongly libertarian.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blakemore |first=Erin |date=April 8, 2016 |title=Politics on the Prairie: Laura Ingalls Wilder and Rose Wilder Lane |url=https://daily.jstor.org/laura-ingalls-wilder-rose-wilder-lane/ |work=Daily Jstor |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=McElroy |first=Wendy |date=April 2, 2019 |title=The Little House on the Prairie of Laura Ingalls Wilder |url=https://www.lewrockwell.com/2019/04/no_author/the-little-house-on-the-prairie-of-laura-ingalls-wilder/ |work=LewRockwell.com |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Later life and death==\nUpon Lane's departure from Rocky Ridge Farm, Laura and Almanzo moved back into the farmhouse they had built, which had most recently been occupied by friends.<ref name=Miller1998-177/>  From 1935 on, they were alone at Rocky Ridge Farm. Most of the surrounding area (including the property with the stone cottage Lane had built for them) was sold, but they still kept some farm animals, and tended their flower beds and vegetable gardens. Almost daily, carloads of fans stopped by, eager to meet the \"Laura\" of the ''Little House'' books.\n\nThe Wilders lived independently and without financial worries until Almanzo's death at the farm in 1949 at age 92. Wilder remained on the farm. For the next eight years, she lived alone, looked after by a circle of neighbors and friends. She continued an active correspondence with her editors, fans, and friends during these years.\n\n[[File:Almanzo and Laura Wilder gravesite Mansfield MO.jpg|thumb|right|Gravesite of Laura Ingalls Wilder and husband Almanzo Wilder at Mansfield Cemetery, Mansfield, Missouri.  Buried next to them is daughter Rose Wilder Lane.]]\nIn autumn 1956, 89-year-old Wilder became severely ill from undiagnosed diabetes and cardiac issues. She was hospitalized by Lane, who had arrived for Thanksgiving. She was able to return home on the day after Christmas.  However, her health declined after her release from the hospital, and she died at home in her sleep on February 10, 1957, three days after her 90th birthday.<ref>{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Laura I. Wilder, Author, Dies at 90. Writer of the 'Little House' Series for Children Was an Ex-Newspaper Editor. Wrote First Book at 65 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/02/12/archives/laura-i-wilder-author-dies-at-90-writer-of-the-little-house-series.html |quote=Mrs. Laura Ingalls Wilder, author of the 'Little House' series of children's books, died yesterday at her farm near here after a long illness. Her age was 90. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=February 12, 1957 |accessdate=October 24, 2012 }} <br>Article preview. Article available only by subscription or purchase. {{subscription required}}</ref> She was buried beside Almanzo at Mansfield Cemetery in Mansfield. Lane was buried next to them upon her death in 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=7-DgDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA809&dq=almanzo+wilder+cemetery&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwil4Y2l64vmAhXEs54KHTB9A24Q6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=almanzo+wilder+cemetery&f=false|title=Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons, 3d ed.|first=Scott|last=Wilson|date=August 17, 2016|publisher=McFarland|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n===Estate===\nFollowing Wilder's death, possession of Rocky Ridge Farm passed to the farmer who had earlier bought the property under a life lease arrangement.<ref>Holtz 1995, pp. 334, 338.</ref> The local population put together a non-profit corporation to purchase the house and its grounds for use as a museum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mansfield Plans Wilder Museum|last=|first=|date=24 February 1957|work=Springfield News & Leader|access-date=}}</ref> After some wariness at the notion of seeing the house rather than the books be a shrine to Wilder, Lane came to believe that making a museum of it would draw long-lasting attention to the books. She donated the money needed to purchase the house and make it a museum, agreed to make significant contributions each year for its upkeep, and donated many of her parents' belongings.<ref>Holtz 1995, p. 340.</ref>\n\nIn compliance with Wilder's will, Lane inherited ownership of the Little House [[literary estate]], with the stipulation that it be for only her lifetime, with all rights reverting to the Mansfield library after her death. Following her demise in 1968, her heir, [[Roger MacBride]], gained control of the books' copyrights. He was like an informally adopted son or grandson to her (one of several younger men with whom she had such a relationship),<ref>See Carolyn Fraser, ''Prairie Fires: The American Dreams of Laura Ingalls Wilder.'' Henry Holt and Co., 2017. Also see William Holtz, ''The Ghost in the Little House: A Life of Rose Wilder Lane''. University of Missouri Press, 1995.</ref> as well as her business agent and lawyer. All of his actions before Lane's death carried her apparent approval; at her request, the copyrights to each of Wilder's \"Little House\" books, as well as those of Lane's own literary works, had been renewed in his name when the original copyrights expired, during the decade between Wilder's and Lane's deaths.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/23/arts/little-library-on-the-offensive.html|title=Little Library On the Offensive|last=Richardson|first=Lynda|date=1999-11-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Nonetheless, many scholars and other readers consider his means of gaining control of the literary estate to have been shady at best, as well as going against Wilder's wishes. His commercialization of the books is also widely considered to have cheapened their literary merit.<ref>See Carolyn Fraser, ''Prairie Fires: The American Dreams of Laura Ingalls Wilder.'' Henry Holt and Co., 2017.</ref>\n\nControversy arose following MacBride's death in 1995, when the Laura Ingalls Wilder Branch of the [[Wright County, Missouri|Wright County]] Library in Mansfield\u2014the library founded in part by Wilder\u2014decided it was worth trying to recover the rights. The ensuing court case was settled in an undisclosed manner, but MacBride's heirs retained the rights to Wilder's books. From the settlement, the library received enough to start work on a new building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Wilder library on verge of settlement|last=Strait|first=Jefferson|date=28 April 2001|work=Springfield News-Leader|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/1999/11/03/lawsuit-on-the-prairiebattle-pits-small-library-against-huge-estate/|title=LAWSUIT ON THE PRAIRIE:BATTLE PITS SMALL LIBRARY AGAINST HUGE ESTATE|last=Levine|first=Hallie|date=1999-11-03|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nThe popularity of the Little House books has grown over the years following Wilder's death, spawning a multimillion-dollar franchise of [[mass merchandising]] under MacBride's impetus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tharp|first=Julie|last2=Kleiman|first2=Jeff|date=2000|title=\"Little House on the Prairie\" and the Myth of Self-Reliance|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/43587224|journal=Transformations: The Journal of Inclusive Scholarship and Pedagogy|volume=11|issue=1|pages=55\u201364|issn=1052-5017}}</ref> Results of the franchise have included additional spinoff book series{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\u2014some written by MacBride and his daughter, [[Abigail MacBride Allen|Abigail]]\u2014and the long-running [[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|television series]], starring [[Melissa Gilbert]] as Wilder and [[Michael Landon]] as her father.\n\n== Works ==\n{{Main|List of Little House on the Prairie books}}\nBecause she died in 1957, Wilder's works are now [[public domain]] in countries where the [[List of countries' copyright lengths|term of copyright]] lasts 50 years after the author's death, or less; generally this does not include works first published posthumously. Works first published before 1924 or where copyright was not renewed, primarily her newspaper columns, are also public domain [[Copyright law of the United States|in the United States]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n===Little House books===\nThe eight \"original\" Little House books were published by Harper & Brothers with illustrations by [[Helen Sewell]] (the first three) or by Sewell and Mildred Boyle.<!--source is our 8 book articles-->\n\n* ''[[Little House in the Big Woods]]'' (1932)\u2014named to the inaugural [[Lewis Carroll Shelf Award]] list in 1958\n* ''[[Farmer Boy]]'' (1933)\u2014about Almanzo Wilder growing up in New York\n* ''[[Little House on the Prairie (novel)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' (1935)\n* ''[[On the Banks of Plum Creek]]'' (1937){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[By the Shores of Silver Lake]]'' (1939){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[The Long Winter (novel)|The Long Winter]]'' (1940){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[Little Town on the Prairie]]'' (1941){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[These Happy Golden Years]]'' (1943){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[The First Four Years (novel)|The First Four Years]]'' (1971)\n\n===Other works===\n* ''[[On the Way Home]]'' (1962, published posthumously)\u2014diary of the Wilders' move from [[De Smet, South Dakota]], to [[Mansfield, Missouri]], edited and supplemented by [[Rose Wilder Lane]]<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/laura-ingalls-wilder/on-the-way-home-3 \"On the Way Home: The Diary Of A Trip From South Dakota To Mansfield, Missouri, In 1894\"]. ''Kirkus Reviews''. November 1, 1962. Retrieved October 2, 2015.</ref>\n* ''The First Four Years'' (1971, published posthumously by Harper & Row), illustrated by [[Garth Williams]]<!--source is our book article-->\u2014commonly considered the ninth Little House book\n* ''[[West from Home]]'' (1974, published posthumously), ed. [[Roger Lea MacBride]]\u2014Wilder's letters to Almanzo while visiting Lane in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]]<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/laura-ingalls-wilder/west-from-home \"West From Home: Letters Of Laura Ingalls Wilder, San Francisco, 1915\"]. ''Kirkus Reviews''. March 1, 1974. Retrieved October 2, 2015.</ref>\n* ''Little House in the Ozarks: The Rediscovered Writings'' (1991)<ref>{{cite book|author=Wilder, Laura |editor=Hines, Stephen W.| location=Nashville | publisher= T. Nelson | title=Little House in the Ozarks: The Rediscovered Writings | date= 1991|isbn= 0883659689}}</ref> {{LCCN|91010820}}\u2014collection of pre-1932 articles<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/laura-ingalls-wilder/little-house-in-the-ozarks \"Little House in the Ozarks\"]. ''Kirkus Reviews''. July 15, 1991. Retrieved October 2, 2015. \"Wilder was an experienced journalist; many of her articles, often written for a publication called Farmer's Week, described her life on the farm where she and Almanzo had finally settled\".</ref>\n* ''The Road Back Home'', part three (the only part previously unpublished) of ''[[A Little House Traveler (novel)|A Little House Traveler: Writings from Laura Ingalls Wilder's Journeys Across America]]'' (2006, Harper) {{LCCN|2005014975}})\u2014Wilder's record of a 1931 trip with Almanzo to De Smet, South Dakota, and the Black Hills\n<!-- NEED dates and perhaps chron order -->\n* ''A Little House Sampler'' (1988 or 1989, U. of Nebraska), with Rose Wilder Lane, ed. [[William Anderson (American writer)|William Anderson]], {{OCLC|16578355}}<ref name=kirkus-reader/>\n* ''Writings to Young Women''\u2014Volume One: ''On Wisdom and Virtues'', Volume Two: ''On Life as a Pioneer Woman'', Volume Three: ''As Told by Her Family, Friends, and Neighbors''<ref>{{Cite book |title=Writings to young women from Laura Ingalls Wilder|last=Wilder |first=Laura Ingalls |date=2006 |publisher=Tommy Nelson |editor-last=Hines |editor-first=Stephen W. |isbn=1400307848 |location=Nashville, Tenn.|oclc=62341531}}</ref>\n* ''A Little House Reader: A Collection of Writings'' (1998, Harper), ed. William Anderson<ref name=kirkus-reader>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/william-anderson/a-little-house-reader \"A Little House Reader: A Collection of Writings by Laura Ingalls Wilder\"]. ''Kirkus Reviews''. December 15, 1997. Retrieved October 2, 2015.</ref>\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder & Rose Wilder Lane, 1937\u20131939'' (1992, Herbert Hoover Presidential Library), ed. Timothy Walch\u2014selections from letters exchanged by Wilder and Lane, with family photographs, {{OCLC|31440538}}\n* ''Laura's Album: A Remembrance Scrapbook of Laura Ingalls Wilder'' (1998, Harper), ed. William Anderson, {{OCLC|865396917}}\n* ''Pioneer Girl: The Annotated Autobiography'' (South Dakota Historical Society Press, 2014)<ref name=SDHS/>\n* ''Before the Prairie Books: The Writings of Laura Ingalls Wilder 1911\u20131916: The Small Farm''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Before the Prairie Books: The Writings of Laura Ingalls Wilder 1917\u20131918: The War Years''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Before the Prairie Books: The Writings of Laura Ingalls Wilder 1919\u20131920: The Farm Home''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Before the Prairie Books: The Writings of Laura Ingalls Wilder 1921\u20131924: A Farm Woman''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder's Most Inspiring Writings''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder: A Pioneer Girl's World View: Selected Newspaper Columns (Little House Prairie Series)''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''The Selected Letters of Laura Ingalls Wilder'', edited by William Anderson<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingallshomestead.com/shop/the-selected-letters-of-laura-ingalls-wilder|title=The Selected Letters Of Laura Ingalls Wilder|work=ingallshomestead.com|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder Farm Journalist: Writings from the Ozarks'', edited by Stephen W. Hines<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingallshomestead.com/shop/laura-ingalls-wilder-farm-journalist|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Farm Journalist|work=ingallshomestead.com|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder's Fairy Poems'', Introduced and compiled by Stephen W. Hines<ref name=\"Laura Ingalls Wilder's fairy poems\">{{cite book |last=Wilder |first=Laura |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder's fairy poems |publisher=Bantam Doubleday Dell Pub. Group |editor-first=Stephen W |editor-last=Hines |location=New York |year=1998 |isbn=9780385325332 |oclc=37361669}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Documentary===\n{{Main|Little House on the Prairie: The Legacy of Laura Ingalls Wilder}}\n''[[Little House on the Prairie: The Legacy of Laura Ingalls Wilder]]'' (February 2015) is a one-hour [[documentary film]] that looks at the life of Wilder. Wilder's story as a writer, wife, and mother is explored through interviews with scholars and historians, archival photography, paintings by frontier artists, and dramatic reenactments.\n\n===Historic sites and museums===\n{{further|Little House on the Prairie#Little House locations and historical sites}}\n[[File:Laura ingalls wilder memorial society museum grounds.jpg|right|thumb|Laura Ingalls Wilder Memorial Society - De Smet, SD]]\n\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Home and Museum, [[Mansfield, Missouri]]\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Museum, [[Pepin (town), Wisconsin|Pepin, Wisconsin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lauraingallspepin.com/|title=Home |publisher=Laura Ingalls Wilder Museum (lauraingallspepin.com) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Museum, [[Walnut Grove, Minnesota]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walnutgrove.org/museum.htm |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Museum |publisher=Walnut Grove, MN (walnutgrove.org) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Memorial Society museum and historic homes, [[De Smet, South Dakota]];  annual pageant performed here<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ingallshomestead.com/|title=Ingalls Homestead|website=Ingalls Homestead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discoverlaura.org/|title=Tour the original homes of the Ingalls family|first=Discover Laura|last=Ingalls|website=Laura Ingalls Wilder Historic Homes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.desmetpageant.org/|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Pageant|website=Laura Ingalls Wilder Pageant}}</ref>\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Park and Museum, [[Burr Oak, Iowa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lauraingallswilder.us|title=Home |accessdate=February 24, 2008 |publisher=Laura Ingalls Wilder Park and Museum (lauraingallswilder.us) }}</ref>\n* Little House on the Prairie Museum, [[Independence, Kansas]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.littlehouseontheprairiemuseum.com |title=Home |publisher=Little House on the Prairie Museum (littlehouseontheprairiemuseum.com) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n* Wilder Homestead, [[Malone, New York|Malone, NY]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.almanzowilderfarm.com|title=Wilder Homestead, Boyhood Home of Almanzo|work=almanzowilderfarm.com|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Portrayals on screen and stage===\n[[Little House on the Prairie#Television adaptations|Multiple adaptations]] of Wilder's ''Little House on the Prairie'' book series have been produced for [[film adaptation|screen]] and [[theatrical adaptation|stage]]. In them, the following actresses have portrayed Wilder:\n\n* [[Melissa Gilbert]] in the television series ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' and its movie sequels (1974\u20131984)\n* [[Kazuko Sugiyama]] (voice) in the Japanese anime series ''[[Laura, The Prairie Girl]]'' (1975\u20131976)\n* [[Meredith Monroe]], [[Tess Harper]] (elder version), Alandra Bingham (younger version, part 1), Michelle Bevan (younger version, part 2) in part 1 and part 2 of the ''[[Beyond the Prairie: The True Story of Laura Ingalls Wilder]]'' television films (2000 and 2002)\n* [[Kyle Chavarria]] in the TV miniseries ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV miniseries)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' (2005)\n* [[Kara Lindsay]] in the ''[[Little House on the Prairie (musical)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' [[musical theatre#Book musicals|book musical]] (2008\u20132010)\n\n===Wilder Medal===\n{{main|Laura Ingalls Wilder Medal}}\nWilder was five times a runner-up for the annual [[Newbery Medal]], the premier [[American Library Association]] (ALA) book award for children's literature.{{efn|name=newbery |1=Five times from 1938 to 1944 Wilder was one of the runners-up for the American Library Association [[Newbery Medal]], recognizing the previous year's \"most distinguished contribution to American literature for children\". The honored works were the last five of eight books in the Little House series that were published in her lifetime.<ref name=newbery/>}} In 1954, the ALA inaugurated a lifetime achievement award for children's writers and illustrators, named for Wilder, of which she was the first recipient. The Laura Ingalls Wilder Medal recognizes a living author or illustrator whose books, published in the United States, have made \"a substantial and lasting contribution to literature for children\". As of 2013, it has been conferred nineteen times, biennially starting in 2001.<ref name=wilder/> In 2018, the award was renamed the Children's Literature Legacy Award in light of language in Wilder's works which the Association perceived as biased against [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] and [[African American]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Association removes Laura Ingalls Wilder's name from award |url=https://apnews.com/19112531f7a24c9c8ab43b7968c96a1d |website=AP News |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=June 25, 2018|date=June 24, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Other===\n* [[Google Doodle]] commemorated her 148th birthday in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/laura-ingalls-wilders-148th-birthday?hl=en-GB |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder's 148th Birthday |accessdate=June 10, 2015 }}</ref>\n* [[Hall of Famous Missourians]] at the [[Missouri State Capitol]]\u2014a bronze bust depicting Wilder is on permanent display in the rotunda. She was inducted in 1993.\n* Missouri Walk of Fame\u2014Wilder was honored on the Walk in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cherryblossomfest.com/pages/2006.html|title=2006|publisher=www.cherryblossomfest.com|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n* [[List of craters on Venus|Wilder crater]] on [[planet]] [[Venus]] was named after Wilder.\n* In her 1916 essay \"Look for Fairies Now\", Wilder asked, \"Of what use are eyes to a tree, I wonder?\". The following century has seen continued research on the detection of [[far-red]] receptors by plants, including as a possible factor in [[crown shyness]].\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Children's literature}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Biography}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|refs=<ref name=wilder>\n[http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/wildermedal/wilderpast \"Laura Ingalls Wilder Award, Past winners\"]. [[Association for Library Service to Children]] ('''ALSC'''). [[American Library Association]] ('''ALA''').<br />\n&nbsp; [http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/wildermedal/wilderabout \"About the Laura Ingalls Wilder Award\"]. ALSC. ALA. Retrieved 2013-03-08.</ref>\n<ref name=newbery>\n[http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/newberymedal/newberyhonors/newberymedal \"Newbery Medal and Honor Books, 1922\u2013Present\"]. ALSC. ALA.<br />\n&nbsp; [http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/newberymedal/aboutnewbery/aboutnewbery \"The John Newbery Medal\"]. ALSC. ALA. Retrieved 2013-03-08.</ref>\n}}\n\n===Works cited===\n* {{Cite book |author= Holtz, William |title= The Ghost in the Little House: A Life of Rose Wilder Lane |publisher= University of Missouri Press |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-8262-0887-8 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/ghostinlittlehou00holt_0 }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Holtz, William |title=The Ghost in the Little House: A Life of Rose Wilder Lane|publisher= University of Missouri Press |year= 1995 |isbn = 0-8262-1015-5 }} \u2013 Edition: illustrated, reprint, revised; 427 pp.; [https://books.google.com/books?id=inodj1jyRtkC&source=gbs_navlinks_s selections and bibliographic data] retrieved from Google Books 2015-10-15.\n* {{Cite book |author= Miller, John E. |title= Becoming Laura Ingalls Wilder: The Woman Behind the Legend |publisher= University of Missouri Press |year= 1998 |isbn= 0-8262-1167-4 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/becominglauraing0000mill }}\n* {{Cite book |author= Miller, John E. |title= Laura Ingalls Wilder and Rose Wilder Lane: Authorship, Place, Time, and Culture |publisher= University of Missouri Press |year= 2008 |isbn= 978-0-8262-1823-0 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/lauraingallswild00mill }}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |hdl=2376/5707 |last1=Campbell |first1=Donna |year=2003 |chapter='Written with a Hard and Ruthless Purpose': Rose Wilder Lane, Edna Ferber, and Middlebrow Regional Fiction |pages=25\u2013 |editor1-last=Botshon |editor1-first=Lisa |editor2-last=Goldsmith |editor2-first=Meredith |title=Middlebrow Moderns: Popular American Women Writers of the 1920s |isbn=978-1-55553-556-8 }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.3102/00028312032003493 |title=Color Blindness and Basket Making Are Not the Answers: Confronting the Dilemmas of Race, Culture, and Language Diversity in Teacher Education |journal=American Educational Research Journal |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=493\u2013522 |year=2016 |last1=Cochran-Smith |first1=Marilyn }}\n*{{cite book |hdl=10150/195771 |type=PhD Thesis |last1=Fatzinger |first1=Amy S. |year=2008 |title=\"Indians in the House\": Revisiting American Indians in Laura Ingalls Wilder's Little House Books |publisher=University of Arizona }}\n*{{cite book |last=Fraser |first=Caroline |author-link=Caroline Fraser |title=[[Prairie Fires: The American Dreams of Laura Ingalls Wilder]] |location=New York |publisher=Metropolitan Books |date=2017}}\n*{{cite journal |jstor=23532729 |first=Philip |last1=Heldrich |year=2000 |title='Going to Indian Territory': Attitudes Toward Native Americans in ''Little House on the Prairie'' |journal=Great Plains Quarterly |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=99\u2013109 }}\n* {{cite newspaper |first=Patricia Nelson |last=Limerick |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/20/books/review/prairie-fires-laura-ingalls-wilder-biography-caroline-fraser.html |title='Little House on the Prairie' and the Truth About the American West |newspaper=The New York Times |date=November 20, 2017}}\n*{{cite book |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder |author=Sickels, Amy |year=2007 |publisher=Facts On File |isbn=9781438123783 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lauraingallswild0000sick }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1353/chq.0.1688 |title='The Only Good Indian': History, Race, and Representation in Laura Ingalls Wilder's ''Little House on the Prairie'' |journal=Children's Literature Association Quarterly |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=191\u2013201 |year=2002 |last1=Smulders |first1=Sharon }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.3167/ghs.2015.080202 |title=Little Girls on the Prairie and the Possibility of Subversive Reading |journal=Girlhood Studies |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=4\u201320 |year=2015 |last1=Singer |first1=Amy }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1353/chq.2013.0019 |title='Counting Coup' on Children's Literature about American Indians: Louise Erdrich's Historical Fiction |journal=Children's Literature Association Quarterly |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=215\u201335 |year=2013 |last1=Stewart |first1=Michelle Pagni }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q237514|s=Author:Laura_Ingalls_Wilder|c=Category:The Ingalls|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|wikt=no}}\n* [http://www.mnopedia.org/person/wilder-laura-ingalls-1867-1957 Laura Ingalls Wilder in MNopedia, the Minnesota Encyclopedia]\n* {{LCAuth|n79095251|Laura Ingalls Wilder|144|}}\n* [http://beyondlittlehouse.com Beyond Little House] - Laura Ingalls Wilder Legacy and Research Association\n* [http://www.liwfrontiergirl.com Laura Ingalls Wilder, Frontier Girl]\n*[https://drive.google.com/open?id=1NuIpb5j22Ec4WXRoyPp7MK4nxiiyZ-pT&u Travel map of Laura Ingalls Wilder] - A map showing Laura Ingalls Wilder's travels from her birth in 1867 to 1894.\n*[http://littlehouseontheprairie.com/about-the-ingalls-family/ About the Ingalls Family (Sarah S. Uthoff)]\n*[https://westernamericanliterature.com/laura-ingalls-wilder-and-rose-wilder-lane/ Western American Literature Research: Laura Ingalls Wilder]\n*[http://littlehouseontheprairie.com/laura-ingalls-wilder-an-american-fixture/ Laura Ingalls Wilder: An American Fixture (Pamela Smith Hill)]\n\n===Museums===\n* [http://www.lauraingallswilderhome.com Laura Ingalls Wilder Historic Home & Museum], Mansfield, Missouri\n* [http://walnutgrove.org/ Laura Ingalls Wilder Museum], Walnut Grove, Minnesota:\n* [http://www.lauraingallswilder.us/ Laura Ingalls Wilder Park & Museum], Burr Oak, Iowa\n\n===Electronic editions===\n{{Bibliowiki}}\n* {{FadedPage|id=Wilder, Laura Ingalls|name=Laura Ingalls Wilder|author=yes}}\n\n{{Little House}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wilder, Laura Ingalls}}\n[[Category:Laura Ingalls Wilder| ]]\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1957 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:American Congregationalists]]\n[[Category:American libertarians]]\n[[Category:American pioneers]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:American women novelists]]\n[[Category:Christian libertarians]]\n[[Category:Cowgirl Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Deaths from diabetes]]\n[[Category:Delano family]]\n[[Category:Educators from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Ingalls family]]\n[[Category:Laura Ingalls Wilder Medal winners]]\n[[Category:Newbery Honor winners]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:People from De Smet, South Dakota]]\n[[Category:People from Pepin, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:People from Wright County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Wilder family]]\n[[Category:Women children's writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from South Dakota]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer, teacher, and journalist}}\n{{Redirect2|Laura Ingalls|Laura Wilder|other persons|Laura Ingalls (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name        = Laura Ingalls Wilder\n| image       = Laura Ingalls Wilder cropped sepia2.jpg\n| caption     = Laura Ingalls Wilder, circa 1885\n| birth_name  = Laura Elizabeth Ingalls\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1867|02|07}}\n| birth_place = [[Pepin County, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1957|02|10|1867|02|07}}\n| death_place = [[Mansfield, Missouri]], U.S.\n| occupation  = Writer, teacher, journalist, family farmer\n| nationality = American\n| period      = 1911\u20131957 (as a writer)\n| genre       = Diaries, essays, [[family saga]] ([[Children's literature|children's]] [[historical novels]])\n| subject<!-- designed for nonfiction -->     = [[Midwestern United States|Midwestern]] and [[Western United States|Western]]\n| movement    =\n| notableworks = {{plainlist|\n* ''[[Little House on the Prairie (novel)|Little House on the Prairie]]''\n* [[List of Little House on the Prairie books|Little House series]]\n}}\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Almanzo Wilder]] |1885|1949|end=d.}}\n| children    = {{Plainlist|\n* 2, [[Rose Wilder Lane]] and Unnamed Male Infant}}\n| relatives   = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Charles Ingalls|Charles Phillip Ingalls]] <small>(father)</small>\n* [[Caroline Ingalls|Caroline Lake Quiner]] <small>(mother)</small>\n* [[Mary Ingalls|Mary Amelia Ingalls]] <small>(sister)</small>\n* [[Carrie Ingalls|Caroline Celestia \"Carrie\" Ingalls Swansey]] <small>(sister)</small>\n* [[Caroline Ingalls#Freddie Ingalls|Charles Frederick \"Freddie\" Ingalls]] <small>(brother)</small>\n* [[Grace Ingalls|Grace Pearl Ingalls Dow]] <small>(sister)</small>}}\n| awards      = {{Awards | [[Laura Ingalls Wilder Medal]] |est. 1954}}\n| signature   = Laura Ingalls Wilder signature.svg\n}}\n\n'''Laura Elizabeth Ingalls Wilder''' (February 7, 1867 \u2013 February 10, 1957) was an American writer known for the ''[[Little House on the Prairie]]'' series of children's books, published between 1932 and 1943, which were based on her childhood in a [[settler]] and [[American pioneer|pioneer]] family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Laura-Ingalls-Wilder|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder {{!}} Biography, Books, & Facts|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 1970s and early 1980s, the television series ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' was loosely based on the Little House books, and starred [[Melissa Gilbert]] as Laura and [[Michael Landon]] as her father, [[Charles Ingalls]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Little House on the Prairie|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0071007/|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n\n==Birth and ancestry==\n[[File:Caroline and Charles Ingalls sepia cropped.jpg|thumb|Caroline and Charles Ingalls]]\nLaura Elizabeth Ingalls was born to [[Charles Ingalls|Charles Phillip]] and [[Caroline Ingalls|Caroline Lake (n\u00e9e Quiner) Ingalls]] on February 7, 1867.  At the time of Ingalls' birth, the family lived seven miles north of the village of [[Pepin, Wisconsin]] in the [[Big Woods]] region of [[Wisconsin]]. Ingalls' home in Pepin became the setting for her first book, ''[[Little House in the Big Woods]]''.<ref name=\"pepin\">{{cite web |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder |url=http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/topics/wilder/index.asp |publisher=Wisconsin Historical Society |website=wisconsinhistory.org |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210135806/http://www.wisconsinhistory.org/topics/wilder/index.asp|archive-date=February 10, 2007}}</ref>  She was the second of five children, following older sister, [[Mary Ingalls|Mary Amelia]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Benge |first=Janet and Geoff |url=https://books.google.com/?id=hbdPbFVxE7oC |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder: A Storybook Life |page=180 |publisher=YWAM Publishing |year=2005 |isbn=1-932096-32-9}}</ref><ref>[http://www.aap.org/en-us/about-the-aap/aap-press-room/Pages/What-Really-Caused-Mary-Ingalls-to-Go-Blind.aspx \"What Really Caused Mary Ingalls to Go Blind?\"]. February 4, 2013. [[American Academy of Pediatrics]]. Press release announcing Allexan, et al.:<br /> \u2022 {{cite journal|author1=Allexan, Sarah S. |author2=Byington, Carrie L. |author3=Finkelstein, Jerome I. |author4=Tarini, Beth A. | title = Blindness in Walnut Grove: How Did Mary Ingalls Lose Her Sight? | journal = Pediatrics | volume = 131 |issue=3 |date=March 1, 2013 |pages=404\u201306 |doi=10.1542/peds.2012-1438|pmid=23382439 |pmc=4074664 }}</ref><ref name=NYT>{{cite news |first= KJ |last= Dell'Antonia |title= Scarlet Fever Probably Didn't Blind Mary Ingalls |url= http://parenting.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/04/scarlet-fever-probably-didnt-blind-mary-ingalls/ |newspaper=The New York Times |date= February 4, 2013 |accessdate= February 4, 2013 }}</ref><ref name=USNews>{{cite news |first= Gordon |last= Serena |title= Mistaken Infection 'On The Prairie'? |url= http://health.usnews.com/health-news/news/articles/2013/02/04/mistaken-infection-on-the-prairie |publisher=HealthDay; [[U.S. News & World Report]] (usnews.com/health-news) |date= February 4, 2013 |accessdate= February 4, 2013 }}</ref> Three more children would follow, [[Carrie Ingalls|Caroline Celestia (Carrie)]], [[Caroline Ingalls#Freddie Ingalls|Charles Frederick]], who died in infancy, and [[Grace Ingalls|Grace Pearl]]. Ingalls Wilder's birth site is commemorated by a replica [[log cabin]] at the [[Little House Wayside]] in Pepin.<ref name=\"VisitPepinCounty\">{{cite web |url=http://visitpepincounty.com/Laura.pdf |title=Laura.pdf |publisher=Little House Wayside; Pepin, Wisconsin (visitpepincounty.com) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref> Her life in Pepin formed the basis for her first book, ''Little House in the Big Woods'' (1932).<ref name=pepin/>\n\nIngalls was a descendant of the [[Delano family]], the ancestral family of [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Franklin D. Roosevelt|Franklin Delano Roosevelt]].<ref name=\"genealogymagazine\">{{cite web |author1=Gormley, Myra Vanderpool |author2=Rhonda R. McClure |url=http://www.genealogymagazine.com/ingalls.html|title=A Genealogical Look at Laura Ingalls Wilder |publisher=GenealogyMagazine.com |accessdate=October 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edmund-rice.org/era5gens/p34.htm#i1065|title=Eunice Sleeman |publisher= Edmund Rice (1638) Association (edmund-rice.org) |date=2002 |quote=Eunice Sleeman was the mother of Eunice Blood (1782\u20131862), the wife of Nathan Colby (born 1778), who were the parents of [[Charles Phillip Ingalls|Laura Louise Colby Ingalls (1810\u20131883)]], Ingalls' paternal grandmother |accessdate=April 20, 2010}}</ref> One paternal ancestor, Edmund Ingalls, from [[Skirbeck]], [[Lincolnshire]], [[England]],  emigrated to [[Thirteen Colonies|America]], settling in [[Lynn, Massachusetts]].<ref name=\"genealogymagazine\" />\n\nShe was a third cousin, once removed, of President [[Ulysses S. Grant]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mayflowerhistory.com/famous-descendants/|title=Famous Descendants|website=MayflowerHistory.com}}</ref>\n\n===Early life===\nWhen she was two years old, Ingalls Wilder moved with her family from Wisconsin in 1869. After stopping in [[Rothville, Missouri]], they settled in the [[Indian country]] of [[Kansas]], near modern day [[Independence, Kansas#History|Independence, Kansas]]. Her younger sister, [[Carrie Ingalls|Carrie]], was born in Independence in August 1870, not long before they moved again. According to Ingalls Wilder, her father Charles Ingalls had been told that the location would be open to white settlers, but when they arrived this was not the case. The Ingalls family had no legal right to occupy their homestead because it was on the [[Osage Nation|Osage Indian]] reservation. They had just begun to farm when they heard rumors that settlers would be evicted, so they left in the spring of 1871. Although in her novel, ''[[Little House on the Prairie (novel)|Little House on the Prairie]],'' and ''Pioneer Girl'' memoir, Ingalls Wilder portrayed their departure as being prompted by rumors of eviction, she also noted that her parents needed to recover their Wisconsin land because the buyer had not paid the mortgage.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Kaye |first=Frances W. |title=Little Squatter on the Osage Diminished Reserve: Reading Laura Ingalls Wilder's Kansas Indians |journal=Great Plains Quarterly |volume=20 |issue=2 |year=2000 |pages=123\u2013140 |doi= |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1022&context=greatplainsquarterly }}</ref>\n\nThe Ingalls family went back to Wisconsin where they lived for the next three years. Those experiences formed the basis for Wilder's novels ''Little House in the Big Woods'' (1932) and ''[[Little House on the Prairie (novel)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' (1935).\n\n''[[On the Banks of Plum Creek]]'' (1937), the third volume of her fictionalized history which takes place around 1874, the Ingalls family moves from Kansas to an area near [[Walnut Grove, Minnesota]], settling in a [[Dugout (shelter)|dugout]] on the banks of [[Plum Creek (Cottonwood River)|Plum Creek]].<ref name=\"archives\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Timeline |work=Laura Ingalls Wilder |publisher=The Herbert Hoover Presidential Library and Museum; National Archives and Records Administration (hoover.archives.gov) |accessdate=October 25, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141025222424/http://www.hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html |archive-date=October 25, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> They moved there from Wisconsin when Ingalls was about seven years old, after briefly living with the family of her uncle, Peter Ingalls, first in Wisconsin and then on rented land near [[Lake City, Minnesota]]. In Walnut Grove, the family first lived in a dugout sod house on a [[Preemption (land)|preemption]] claim; after wintering in it, they moved into a new house built on the same land. Two summers of ruined crops led them to move to [[Iowa]]. On the way, they stayed again with Charles Ingalls' brother, Peter Ingalls, this time on his farm near [[South Troy, Minnesota]]. Her brother, Charles Frederick Ingalls (\"Freddie\"), was born there on November 1, 1875, dying nine months later in August 1876. In [[Burr Oak, Iowa]], the family helped run a hotel. The youngest of the Ingalls children, [[Grace Ingalls|Grace]], was born there on May 23, 1877.\n\nThe family moved from Burr Oak back to Walnut Grove where Charles Ingalls served as the town butcher and [[justice of the peace]]. He accepted a railroad job in the spring of 1879, which took him to eastern [[Dakota Territory]], where they joined him that fall. Ingalls Wilder omitted the period in 1876\u20131877 when they lived near Burr Oak, skipping to Dakota Territory, portrayed in ''[[By the Shores of Silver Lake]]'' (1939).\n\n===De Smet===\n[[File:Laura ingalls wilder museum surveyor's house desmet sd.jpg|thumb|right|Surveyor's House, the first home in Dakota Territory of the Charles Ingalls family - De Smet, South Dakota]]\nWilder's father filed for a [[Homestead Act|formal homestead]] over the winter of 1879\u20131880.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.archives.gov/research/land/ingalls|title=Land Records: Ingalls Homestead File|date=August 15, 2016|website=National Archives|access-date=13 June 2019}}</ref> [[De Smet, South Dakota]], became her parents' and sister Mary's home for the remainder of their lives. After spending the mild winter of 1879\u20131880 in the surveyor's house, they watched the town of De Smet rise up from the prairie in 1880. The following winter, 1880\u20131881, one of the most severe on record in the Dakotas, was later described by Ingalls Wilder in her novel, ''[[The Long Winter (novel)|The Long Winter]]'' (1940). Once the family was settled in De Smet, Ingalls attended school, worked several part-time jobs, and made friends. Among them was bachelor homesteader [[Almanzo Wilder]]. This time in her life is documented in the books ''[[Little Town on the Prairie]]'' (1941) and ''[[These Happy Golden Years]]'' (1943).\n\n===Young teacher===\nOn December 10, 1882, two months before her 16th birthday, Ingalls accepted her first teaching position.<ref>{{cite web|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Timeline|url=https://hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html|website=Herbert Hoover Presidential Library & Museum|publisher=Herbert Hoover Presidential Library & Museum|accessdate=January 27, 2017}}</ref> She taught three terms in [[one-room school]]s when she was not attending school in De Smet. (In ''Little Town on the Prairie'' she receives her first teaching certificate on December 24, 1882, but that was an enhancement for dramatic effect.{{Citation needed|date=November 2011|reason=How was it an enhancement?}}) Her original \"Third Grade\" teaching certificate can be seen on page 25 of William Anderson's book ''Laura's Album'' (1998).<ref>{{cite book|author=Anderson, William|title=Laura's Album|date=1998|publisher=Harper Collins}}</ref> She later admitted she did not particularly enjoy it, but felt a responsibility from a young age to help her family financially, and wage-earning opportunities for women were limited. Between 1883 and 1885, she taught three terms of school, worked for the local dressmaker, and attended high school, although she did not graduate.\n\n===Early marriage years===\n[[File:Rose wilder lane birthplace roadside marker.jpg|thumb|right|Rose Wilder Lane birthplace roadside marker - DeSmet]]\n[[File:Laura and Almanzo Wilder 1885 retouched sepia.jpg|thumb|left|upright=.6|Laura and Almanzo Wilder, circa 1885]]\n[[File:Rose wilder lane birthplace desmet sd 2b.jpg|thumb|right|Location of Wilder homestead where both of Wilder's children were born - DeSmet]]\nIngalls' teaching career and studies ended when the 18-year-old Laura married 28-year-old Almanzo Wilder on August 25, 1885.<ref name=\"WfH\" /> From the beginning of their relationship, the pair had nicknames for each other: she called him \"Manly\" and he, because he had a sister named Laura, called her \"Bessie\", from her middle name, Elizabeth.<ref name=\"WfH\">{{cite book | first1=Laura Ingalls | last1=Wilder | title=West from Home: Letters of Laura Ingalls Wilder, San Francisco, 1915 | publisher=HarperCollins | date=1974 | last2=Wilder | first2=Almanzo | page=xvii}}</ref> Almanzo had achieved a degree of prosperity on his homestead claim;<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=-mteBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT99&dq=Almanzo+Wilder+prosperous#v=onepage&q=Almanzo%20Wilder%20prosperous&f=false|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder: American Writer on the Prairie|last=Ketcham|first=Sallie|date=September 16, 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136725739|language=en}}</ref> the newly married couple started their life together in a new home, north of De Smet.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2009/08/10/wilder-women|title=Wilder Women|last=Thurman|first=Judith|website=The New Yorker|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 1886, Wilder gave birth to her daughter, [[Rose Wilder Lane|Rose]].  In 1889, she gave birth to a son who died at 12 days of age before being named. He was buried at De Smet, Kingsbury County, South Dakota.<ref name=\"Laura Ingalls Wilder Timeline\">{{cite web |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Timeline |website=hoover.archives.gov |url=https://www.hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html |publisher=The Herbert Hoover Presidential Library and Museum |location=West Branch, IA, US |accessdate=June 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525034756/http://www.hoover.archives.gov/LIW/timeline/timeline.html |archive-date=May 25, 2016 |url-status=dead  }}</ref><ref name=\"De Smet Info\">{{cite web |title=De Smet Info |website=ingallshomestead.com |url=http://www.ingallshomestead.com/de-smet-info/ |accessdate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> On the grave marker, he is remembered as \"Baby Son of A. J. Wilder\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=JGjYAAAAMAAJ&q=%22Baby+Son+of+A.+J.+Wilder%22&dq=%22Baby+Son+of+A.+J.+Wilder%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJpuyO64vmAhWwna0KHf4jCRcQ6AEIMDAB|title=Christian Living: A Magazine for Home and Community|date=March 3, 1963|publisher=Mennonite Publishing House|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nTheir first few years of marriage were difficult. Complications from a life-threatening bout of [[diphtheria]] left Almanzo partially [[paralysis|paralyzed]]. Although he eventually regained nearly full use of his legs, he needed a cane to walk for the remainder of his life. This setback, among many others, began a series of unfortunate events that included the death of their newborn son, the destruction of their barn along with its hay and grain by a mysterious fire,<ref>Miller 1998, p. 80.</ref> the total loss of their home from a fire accidentally set by Rose,<ref>Miller 1998, p. 84.</ref> and several years of severe [[drought]] that left them in debt, physically ill, and unable to earn a living from their 320 acres (129.5 hectares) of prairie land. These trials were documented in Wilder's book ''[[The First Four Years (novel)|The First Four Years]]'' (published in 1971). Around 1890, they left De Smet and spent about a year resting at the home of Almanzo's parents on their [[Spring Valley, Minnesota]], farm before moving briefly to [[Westville, Florida]], in search of a climate to improve Almanzo's health. They found, however, that the dry plains they were used to were very different from the humidity they encountered in Westville. The weather, along with feeling out of place among the locals, encouraged their return to De Smet in 1892, where they purchased a small home.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.minnpost.com/mnopedia/2014/08/story-behind-stories-laura-ingalls-wilders-life-minnesota-and-beyond/|title=The story behind the stories: Laura Ingalls Wilder\u2019s life in Minnesota and beyond|date=2014-08-19|website=MinnPost|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nybooks.com/articles/2018/04/19/laura-ingalls-wilder-and-wilder/|title=Wilder and Wilder|last=Messud|first=Claire|date=2018-04-19|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en|issn=0028-7504}}</ref>\n\n==Move to Mansfield, Missouri==\n[[File:LauraIngallsWilder-RockyRidgeFarm-MansfieldMO adjusted.jpg|thumb|right|Rocky Ridge Farm, Mansfield, Missouri]]\n\nIn 1894, the Wilders moved to [[Mansfield, Missouri]], and used their savings to make the [[down payment]] on an undeveloped property just outside town. They named the place [[Laura Ingalls Wilder House|Rocky Ridge Farm]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Laura's Life on Rocky Ridge Farm | website=Laura Ingalls Wilder Historic Home & Museum | date=November 5, 2012 | url=http://www.lauraingallswilderhome.com/?page_id=452 | ref={{sfnref | Laura Ingalls Wilder Historic Home & Museum | 2012}} | accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref> and moved into a ramshackle log cabin. At first, they earned income only from wagon loads of fire wood they would sell in town for 50 cents.  Financial security came slowly. Apple trees they planted did not bear fruit for seven years. Almanzo's parents visited around that time and gave them the deed to the house they had been renting in Mansfield, which was the economic boost Wilder's family needed. They then added to the property outside town, and eventually accrued nearly 200 acres (80.9 hectares). Around 1910, they sold the house in town, moved back to the farm, and completed the farmhouse with the proceeds. What began as about 40 acres (16.2 hectares) of thickly wooded, stone-covered hillside with a windowless log cabin became in 20 years a relatively prosperous poultry, dairy, and fruit farm, and a 10-room farmhouse.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=kWsrAQAAQBAJ&lpg=PA69&ots=VWlFJOd3i1&dq=laura%20ingalls%20wilder%20missouri%2010%20room%20farmhouse&pg=PA69#v=onepage&q=laura%20ingalls%20wilder%20missouri%2010%20room%20farmhouse&f=false|title=Famous Americans: A Directory of Museums, Historic Sites, and Memorials|last=Danilov|first=Victor J.|date=2013-09-26|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-9186-9|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe Wilders had learned from cultivating wheat as their sole crop in De Smet. They diversified Rocky Ridge Farm with poultry, a dairy farm, and a large apple orchard. Wilder became active in various clubs and was an advocate for several regional farm associations. She was recognized as an authority in poultry farming and rural living, which led to invitations to speak to groups around the region.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder, farm journalist : writings from the Ozarks|last=Wilder |first=Laura Ingalls |date=2007 |publisher=University of Missouri Press |editor-last=Hines |editor-first=Stephen W. |isbn=978-0826266156 |location=Columbia |oclc=427509646}}</ref>\n\n==Writing career==\nAn invitation to submit an article to the ''Missouri Ruralist'' in 1911 led to Wilder's permanent position as a columnist and editor with that publication, which she held until the mid-1920s. She also took a paid position with the local [[Federal Farm Loan Act|Farm Loan Association]], dispensing small loans to local farmers.\n\nWilder's column in the ''Ruralist'', \"As a Farm Woman Thinks\", introduced her to a loyal audience of rural [[Ozarks|Ozarkians]], who enjoyed her regular columns. Her topics ranged from home and family, including her 1915 trip to [[San Francisco, California]], to visit Rose Lane and the Pan-Pacific exhibition, to [[World War I]] and other world events, and to the fascinating world travels of Lane as well as her own thoughts on the increasing options offered to women during this era. While the couple were never wealthy until the \"Little House\" books began to achieve popularity, the farming operation and Wilder's income from writing and the Farm Loan Association provided them with a stable living.\n\n\"[By] 1924\", according to the Professor John E. Miller, \"[a]fter more than a decade of writing for farm papers, Wilder had become a disciplined writer, able to produce thoughtful, readable prose for a general audience.\" At this time, her now-married daughter, Rose Wilder Lane, helped her publish two articles describing the interior of the farmhouse, in ''Country Gentleman'' magazine.<ref>Miller 1998, p. 161.</ref>\n\nIt was also around this time that Lane began intensively encouraging Wilder to improve her writing skills with a view toward greater success as a writer than Lane had already achieved.<ref>Miller 1998, p. 162.</ref>  The Wilders, according to Miller, had come to \"[depend] on annual income subsidies from their increasingly famous and successful daughter.\" They both had concluded that the solution for improving their retirement income was for Wilder to become a successful writer herself. However, the \"project never proceeded very far.\"<ref>Miller 2008, p. 24.</ref>\n\nIn 1928, Lane hired out the construction of an English-style stone cottage for her parents on property adjacent to the farmhouse they had personally built and still inhabited. She remodeled and took it over.<ref name=Miller1998-177>Miller 1998, p. 177.</ref>\n\n===''Little House'' books===\n{{main|List of Little House on the Prairie books}}\n\nThe [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|Stock Market Crash of 1929]] wiped the Wilders out; Lane's investments were devastated as well. They still owned the 200-acre (81-hectare) farm, but they had invested most of their savings with Lane's broker. In 1930, Wilder requested Lane's opinion about an autobiographical manuscript she had written about her pioneering childhood. The [[Great Depression]], coupled with the deaths of Wilder's mother in 1924 and her older sister in 1928, seem to have prompted her to preserve her memories in a life story called ''Pioneer Girl''. She also hoped that her writing would generate some additional income. The original title of the first of the books was ''When Grandma Was a Little Girl''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Students visiting Wilder's prairie|last=Hines-Dochterman|first=Meredith|date=30 September 2005|work=St. Joseph News-Press|access-date=}}</ref> On the advice of Lane's publisher, she greatly expanded the story. As a result of Lane's publishing connections as a successful writer and after editing by her, [[Harper (publisher)#Harper & Brothers (1833\u20131962)|Harper & Brothers]] published Wilder's book in 1932 as ''Little House in the Big Woods''. After its success, she continued writing. The close and often rocky collaboration between her and Lane continued, in person until 1935, when Lane permanently left Rocky Ridge Farm, and afterward by correspondence.\n\nThe collaboration worked both ways: two of Lane's most successful novels, ''Let the Hurricane Roar'' (1932) and ''Free Land'' (1938), were written at the same time as the \"Little House\" series and basically retold Ingalls and Wilder family tales in an adult format.<ref name=Miller2008-40>Miller 2008, p. 40.</ref>\n\n====Authorship controversy====\nSome, including Lane's biographer, William Holtz, have alleged that Wilder's daughter was her ghostwriter.<ref>Holtz 1993.{{full citation needed|date=October 2015}}<!-- page needed --></ref>  Existing evidence includes ongoing correspondence between the women about the books' development, Lane's extensive diaries, and Wilder's handwritten manuscripts with edit notations shows an ongoing collaboration between the two women.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nMiller, using this record, describes varying levels of involvement by Lane. ''[[Little House in the Big Woods]]'' (1932) and ''[[These Happy Golden Years]]'' (1943), he notes, received the least editing. \"The first pages&nbsp;... and other large sections of [''Big Woods'']\", he observes, \"stand largely intact, indicating&nbsp;... from the start&nbsp;...[Laura's] talent for narrative description.\"<ref>Miller 1998, pp. 6, 190.</ref>  Some volumes saw heavier participation by Lane,<ref>Miller 2008, pp. 37 et seq.</ref> while [[The First Four Years (novel)|''The First Four Years'']] (1971) appears to be exclusively a Wilder work.<ref name=thurman2009>{{cite web |author=Thurman, Judith |url=http://www.newyorker.com/arts/critics/atlarge/2009/08/10/090810crat_atlarge_thurman?currentPage=paragraph-29 |title=Wilder Women: The mother and daughter behind the Little House stories |date=August 10, 2009 |work=The New Yorker |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\nConcludes Miller, \"In the end, the lasting literary legacy remains that of the mother more than that of the daughter&nbsp;... Lane possessed style; Wilder had substance.\"<ref name=Miller2008-40/>\n\nThe controversy over authorship is often tied to the movement to read the Little House series through an ideological lens. Lane emerged in the 1930s as an avowed conservative polemicist and critic of the [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]] administration and his [[New Deal]] programs. According to a 2012 article in the ''New Yorker'', \"When Roosevelt was elected, she noted in her diary, 'America has a dictator.' She prayed for his assassination, and considered doing the job herself.\"<ref name=thurman2012>{{cite web |author=Thurman, Judith |url=http://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/a-libertarian-house-on-the-prairie |title=A Libertarian House on the Prairie |date=August 16, 2012 |work=The New Yorker |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref> Whatever Lane's politics, \"attacks on [Wilder's] authorship seem aimed at infusing her books with ideological passions they just don't have.\"<ref name=\"salon.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2012/10/10/little_house_on_the_prairie_tea_party_manifesto |title='Little House on the Prairie': Tea Party manifesto |author=Fraser, Caroline |work=Los Angeles Review of Books |date=October 10, 2012 |via=''[[Salon (website)|Salon]]'' (salon.com) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n====Enduring appeal====\nThe original Little House books, written for [[elementary school]]\u2013age children, became an enduring, eight-volume record of pioneering life late in the 19th century based on the Ingalls family's experiences on the American frontier. ''The First Four Years'', about the early days of the Wilder marriage, was discovered by her literary executor [[Roger MacBride]] after Lane's 1968 death and published in 1971, unedited by Lane or MacBride. It is now marketed as the ninth volume.<ref name=thurman2009/>\n\nSince the publication of ''Little House in the Big Woods'' (1932), the books have been continuously in print and have been translated into 40 other languages. Wilder's first\u2014and smallest\u2014royalty check from Harper, in 1932, was for $500, {{Inflation|US|500|1932|r=-1|fmt=eq}}. By the mid-1930s the royalties from the ''Little House'' books brought a steady and increasingly substantial income to the Wilders for the first time in their 50 years of marriage. The collaboration also brought the two writers at Rocky Ridge Farm the money they needed to recoup the loss of their investments in the stock market. Various honors, huge amounts of fan mail, and other accolades were bestowed on Wilder.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\n===Autobiography: ''Pioneer Girl''===\nIn 1929\u20131930, already in her early 60s, Wilder began writing her autobiography, titled ''Pioneer Girl.'' It was rejected by publishers. At Lane's urging, she rewrote most of her stories for children. The result was the ''Little House'' series of books. In 2014, the [[South Dakota State Historical Society]] published an annotated version of Wilder's autobiography, titled ''Pioneer Girl: The Annotated Autobiography''.<ref name=SDHS>[http://pioneergirlproject.org/2014/11/21/pioneer-girl-is-out \"Pioneer Girl is out!\"]. November 21, 2014. Pioneer Girl Project (pioneergirlproject.org). South Dakota Historical Society Press. Retrieved October 15, 2015.</ref><ref>{{Cite news\n| last = Higgins\n| first = Jim\n| title = Laura Ingalls Wilder's annotated autobiography, 'Pioneer Girl,' shows writer's world, growth\n| newspaper = [[Milwaukee Journal Sentinel]]\n| accessdate = December 23, 2014\n| date = December 5, 2014\n| url = http://www.jsonline.com/entertainment/books/laura-ingalls-wilders-annotated-autobiography-pioneer-girl-shows-writers-world-growth-b99399147z1-284813631.html\n}}</ref>\n\n''Pioneer Girl'' includes stories that Wilder felt were inappropriate for children: e.g., a man accidentally immolating himself while drunk, and an incident of extreme violence of a local shopkeeper against his wife, which ended with his setting their house on fire. She also describes previously unknown facets of her father's character. According to its publisher, \"Wilder's fiction, her autobiography, and her real childhood are all distinct things, but they are closely intertwined.\" The book's aim was to explore the differences, including incidents with conflicting or non-existing accounts in one or another of the sources.<ref>{{cite news |last=Flood |first=Alison |date=August 25, 2014 |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder memoir reveals truth behind Little House on the Prairie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2014/aug/25/laura-ingalls-wilder-memoir-little-house-prairie |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=August 26, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nWilder has been referred to as one of America's first libertarians.<ref>{{cite news |last=Boaz |first=David |date=May 9, 2015 |title=The Legacy of Laura Ingalls Wilder, One of America's First Libertarians |url=https://time.com/3848967/laura-ingalls-wilder-is-back/ |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref> She was originally a life-long [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], but became dismayed with Roosevelt's New Deal and what she and her daughter, [[Rose Wilder Lane]], saw as Americans' increasing dependence on the federal government. Wilder grew disenchanted with her party and resented government agents who came to farms like hers and grilled farmers about the number of acres they were planting.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news  |last=Klein |first=Christopher |date=February 7, 2014 |title=Little Libertarians on the Prairie: The Hidden Politics Behind a Children's Classic |url=https://www.history.com/news/little-libertarians-on-the-prairie-the-hidden-politics-behind-a-childrens-classic |work=History.com |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref> Her daughter was similarly strongly libertarian.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blakemore |first=Erin |date=April 8, 2016 |title=Politics on the Prairie: Laura Ingalls Wilder and Rose Wilder Lane |url=https://daily.jstor.org/laura-ingalls-wilder-rose-wilder-lane/ |work=Daily Jstor |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite news |last=McElroy |first=Wendy |date=April 2, 2019 |title=The Little House on the Prairie of Laura Ingalls Wilder |url=https://www.lewrockwell.com/2019/04/no_author/the-little-house-on-the-prairie-of-laura-ingalls-wilder/ |work=LewRockwell.com |accessdate=June 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Later life and death==\nUpon Lane's departure from Rocky Ridge Farm, Laura and Almanzo moved back into the farmhouse they had built, which had most recently been occupied by friends.<ref name=Miller1998-177/>  From 1935 on, they were alone at Rocky Ridge Farm. Most of the surrounding area (including the property with the stone cottage Lane had built for them) was sold, but they still kept some farm animals, and tended their flower beds and vegetable gardens. Almost daily, carloads of fans stopped by, eager to meet the \"Laura\" of the ''Little House'' books.\n\nThe Wilders lived independently and without financial worries until Almanzo's death at the farm in 1949 at age 92. Wilder remained on the farm. For the next eight years, she lived alone, looked after by a circle of neighbors and friends. She continued an active correspondence with her editors, fans, and friends during these years.\n\n[[File:Almanzo and Laura Wilder gravesite Mansfield MO.jpg|thumb|right|Gravesite of Laura Ingalls Wilder and husband Almanzo Wilder at Mansfield Cemetery, Mansfield, Missouri.  Buried next to them is daughter Rose Wilder Lane.]]\nIn autumn 1956, 89-year-old Wilder became severely ill from undiagnosed diabetes and cardiac issues. She was hospitalized by Lane, who had arrived for Thanksgiving. She was able to return home on the day after Christmas.  However, her health declined after her release from the hospital, and she died at home in her sleep on February 10, 1957, three days after her 90th birthday.<ref>{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |title=Laura I. Wilder, Author, Dies at 90. Writer of the 'Little House' Series for Children Was an Ex-Newspaper Editor. Wrote First Book at 65 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1957/02/12/archives/laura-i-wilder-author-dies-at-90-writer-of-the-little-house-series.html |quote=Mrs. Laura Ingalls Wilder, author of the 'Little House' series of children's books, died yesterday at her farm near here after a long illness. Her age was 90. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=February 12, 1957 |accessdate=October 24, 2012 }} <br>Article preview. Article available only by subscription or purchase. {{subscription required}}</ref> She was buried beside Almanzo at Mansfield Cemetery in Mansfield. Lane was buried next to them upon her death in 1968.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=7-DgDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA809&dq=almanzo+wilder+cemetery&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwil4Y2l64vmAhXEs54KHTB9A24Q6AEIMTAB#v=onepage&q=almanzo+wilder+cemetery&f=false|title=Resting Places: The Burial Sites of More Than 14,000 Famous Persons, 3d ed.|first=Scott|last=Wilson|date=August 17, 2016|publisher=McFarland|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n===Estate===\nFollowing Wilder's death, possession of Rocky Ridge Farm passed to the farmer who had earlier bought the property under a life lease arrangement.<ref>Holtz 1995, pp. 334, 338.</ref> The local population put together a non-profit corporation to purchase the house and its grounds for use as a museum.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Mansfield Plans Wilder Museum|last=|first=|date=24 February 1957|work=Springfield News & Leader|access-date=}}</ref> After some wariness at the notion of seeing the house rather than the books be a shrine to Wilder, Lane came to believe that making a museum of it would draw long-lasting attention to the books. She donated the money needed to purchase the house and make it a museum, agreed to make significant contributions each year for its upkeep, and donated many of her parents' belongings.<ref>Holtz 1995, p. 340.</ref>\n\nIn compliance with Wilder's will, Lane inherited ownership of the Little House [[literary estate]], with the stipulation that it be for only her lifetime, with all rights reverting to the Mansfield library after her death. Following her demise in 1968, her heir, [[Roger MacBride]], gained control of the books' copyrights. He was like an informally adopted son or grandson to her (one of several younger men with whom she had such a relationship),<ref>See Carolyn Fraser, ''Prairie Fires: The American Dreams of Laura Ingalls Wilder.'' Henry Holt and Co., 2017. Also see William Holtz, ''The Ghost in the Little House: A Life of Rose Wilder Lane''. University of Missouri Press, 1995.</ref> as well as her business agent and lawyer. All of his actions before Lane's death carried her apparent approval; at her request, the copyrights to each of Wilder's \"Little House\" books, as well as those of Lane's own literary works, had been renewed in his name when the original copyrights expired, during the decade between Wilder's and Lane's deaths.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/11/23/arts/little-library-on-the-offensive.html|title=Little Library On the Offensive|last=Richardson|first=Lynda|date=1999-11-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Nonetheless, many scholars and other readers consider his means of gaining control of the literary estate to have been shady at best, as well as going against Wilder's wishes. His commercialization of the books is also widely considered to have cheapened their literary merit.<ref>See Carolyn Fraser, ''Prairie Fires: The American Dreams of Laura Ingalls Wilder.'' Henry Holt and Co., 2017.</ref>\n\nControversy arose following MacBride's death in 1995, when the Laura Ingalls Wilder Branch of the [[Wright County, Missouri|Wright County]] Library in Mansfield\u2014the library founded in part by Wilder\u2014decided it was worth trying to recover the rights. The ensuing court case was settled in an undisclosed manner, but MacBride's heirs retained the rights to Wilder's books. From the settlement, the library received enough to start work on a new building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Wilder library on verge of settlement|last=Strait|first=Jefferson|date=28 April 2001|work=Springfield News-Leader|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/1999/11/03/lawsuit-on-the-prairiebattle-pits-small-library-against-huge-estate/|title=LAWSUIT ON THE PRAIRIE:BATTLE PITS SMALL LIBRARY AGAINST HUGE ESTATE|last=Levine|first=Hallie|date=1999-11-03|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref>\n\nThe popularity of the Little House books has grown over the years following Wilder's death, spawning a multimillion-dollar franchise of [[mass merchandising]] under MacBride's impetus.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Tharp|first=Julie|last2=Kleiman|first2=Jeff|date=2000|title=\"Little House on the Prairie\" and the Myth of Self-Reliance|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/43587224|journal=Transformations: The Journal of Inclusive Scholarship and Pedagogy|volume=11|issue=1|pages=55\u201364|issn=1052-5017}}</ref> Results of the franchise have included additional spinoff book series{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\u2014some written by MacBride and his daughter, [[Abigail MacBride Allen|Abigail]]\u2014and the long-running [[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|television series]], starring [[Melissa Gilbert]] as Wilder and [[Michael Landon]] as her father.\n\n== Works ==\n{{Main|List of Little House on the Prairie books}}\nBecause she died in 1957, Wilder's works are now [[public domain]] in countries where the [[List of countries' copyright lengths|term of copyright]] lasts 50 years after the author's death, or less; generally this does not include works first published posthumously. Works first published before 1924 or where copyright was not renewed, primarily her newspaper columns, are also public domain [[Copyright law of the United States|in the United States]].{{citation needed|date=May 2017}}\n\n===Little House books===\nThe eight \"original\" Little House books were published by Harper & Brothers with illustrations by [[Helen Sewell]] (the first three) or by Sewell and Mildred Boyle.<!--source is our 8 book articles-->\n\n* ''[[Little House in the Big Woods]]'' (1932)\u2014named to the inaugural [[Lewis Carroll Shelf Award]] list in 1958\n* ''[[Farmer Boy]]'' (1933)\u2014about Almanzo Wilder growing up in New York\n* ''[[Little House on the Prairie (novel)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' (1935)\n* ''[[On the Banks of Plum Creek]]'' (1937){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[By the Shores of Silver Lake]]'' (1939){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[The Long Winter (novel)|The Long Winter]]'' (1940){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[Little Town on the Prairie]]'' (1941){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[These Happy Golden Years]]'' (1943){{efn|name=newbery}}\n* ''[[The First Four Years (novel)|The First Four Years]]'' (1971)\n\n===Other works===\n* ''[[On the Way Home]]'' (1962, published posthumously)\u2014diary of the Wilders' move from [[De Smet, South Dakota]], to [[Mansfield, Missouri]], edited and supplemented by [[Rose Wilder Lane]]<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/laura-ingalls-wilder/on-the-way-home-3 \"On the Way Home: The Diary Of A Trip From South Dakota To Mansfield, Missouri, In 1894\"]. ''Kirkus Reviews''. November 1, 1962. Retrieved October 2, 2015.</ref>\n* ''The First Four Years'' (1971, published posthumously by Harper & Row), illustrated by [[Garth Williams]]<!--source is our book article-->\u2014commonly considered the ninth Little House book\n* ''[[West from Home]]'' (1974, published posthumously), ed. [[Roger Lea MacBride]]\u2014Wilder's letters to Almanzo while visiting Lane in [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]]<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/laura-ingalls-wilder/west-from-home \"West From Home: Letters Of Laura Ingalls Wilder, San Francisco, 1915\"]. ''Kirkus Reviews''. March 1, 1974. Retrieved October 2, 2015.</ref>\n* ''Little House in the Ozarks: The Rediscovered Writings'' (1991)<ref>{{cite book|author=Wilder, Laura |editor=Hines, Stephen W.| location=Nashville | publisher= T. Nelson | title=Little House in the Ozarks: The Rediscovered Writings | date= 1991|isbn= 0883659689}}</ref> {{LCCN|91010820}}\u2014collection of pre-1932 articles<ref>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/laura-ingalls-wilder/little-house-in-the-ozarks \"Little House in the Ozarks\"]. ''Kirkus Reviews''. July 15, 1991. Retrieved October 2, 2015. \"Wilder was an experienced journalist; many of her articles, often written for a publication called Farmer's Week, described her life on the farm where she and Almanzo had finally settled\".</ref>\n* ''The Road Back Home'', part three (the only part previously unpublished) of ''[[A Little House Traveler (novel)|A Little House Traveler: Writings from Laura Ingalls Wilder's Journeys Across America]]'' (2006, Harper) {{LCCN|2005014975}})\u2014Wilder's record of a 1931 trip with Almanzo to De Smet, South Dakota, and the Black Hills\n<!-- NEED dates and perhaps chron order -->\n* ''A Little House Sampler'' (1988 or 1989, U. of Nebraska), with Rose Wilder Lane, ed. [[William Anderson (American writer)|William Anderson]], {{OCLC|16578355}}<ref name=kirkus-reader/>\n* ''Writings to Young Women''\u2014Volume One: ''On Wisdom and Virtues'', Volume Two: ''On Life as a Pioneer Woman'', Volume Three: ''As Told by Her Family, Friends, and Neighbors''<ref>{{Cite book |title=Writings to young women from Laura Ingalls Wilder|last=Wilder |first=Laura Ingalls |date=2006 |publisher=Tommy Nelson |editor-last=Hines |editor-first=Stephen W. |isbn=1400307848 |location=Nashville, Tenn.|oclc=62341531}}</ref>\n* ''A Little House Reader: A Collection of Writings'' (1998, Harper), ed. William Anderson<ref name=kirkus-reader>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/william-anderson/a-little-house-reader \"A Little House Reader: A Collection of Writings by Laura Ingalls Wilder\"]. ''Kirkus Reviews''. December 15, 1997. Retrieved October 2, 2015.</ref>\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder & Rose Wilder Lane, 1937\u20131939'' (1992, Herbert Hoover Presidential Library), ed. Timothy Walch\u2014selections from letters exchanged by Wilder and Lane, with family photographs, {{OCLC|31440538}}\n* ''Laura's Album: A Remembrance Scrapbook of Laura Ingalls Wilder'' (1998, Harper), ed. William Anderson, {{OCLC|865396917}}\n* ''Pioneer Girl: The Annotated Autobiography'' (South Dakota Historical Society Press, 2014)<ref name=SDHS/>\n* ''Before the Prairie Books: The Writings of Laura Ingalls Wilder 1911\u20131916: The Small Farm''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Before the Prairie Books: The Writings of Laura Ingalls Wilder 1917\u20131918: The War Years''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Before the Prairie Books: The Writings of Laura Ingalls Wilder 1919\u20131920: The Farm Home''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Before the Prairie Books: The Writings of Laura Ingalls Wilder 1921\u20131924: A Farm Woman''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder's Most Inspiring Writings''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder: A Pioneer Girl's World View: Selected Newspaper Columns (Little House Prairie Series)''{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n* ''The Selected Letters of Laura Ingalls Wilder'', edited by William Anderson<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingallshomestead.com/shop/the-selected-letters-of-laura-ingalls-wilder|title=The Selected Letters Of Laura Ingalls Wilder|work=ingallshomestead.com|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder Farm Journalist: Writings from the Ozarks'', edited by Stephen W. Hines<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ingallshomestead.com/shop/laura-ingalls-wilder-farm-journalist|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Farm Journalist|work=ingallshomestead.com|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Laura Ingalls Wilder's Fairy Poems'', Introduced and compiled by Stephen W. Hines<ref name=\"Laura Ingalls Wilder's fairy poems\">{{cite book |last=Wilder |first=Laura |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder's fairy poems |publisher=Bantam Doubleday Dell Pub. Group |editor-first=Stephen W |editor-last=Hines |location=New York |year=1998 |isbn=9780385325332 |oclc=37361669}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Documentary===\n{{Main|Little House on the Prairie: The Legacy of Laura Ingalls Wilder}}\n''[[Little House on the Prairie: The Legacy of Laura Ingalls Wilder]]'' (February 2015) is a one-hour [[documentary film]] that looks at the life of Wilder. Wilder's story as a writer, wife, and mother is explored through interviews with scholars and historians, archival photography, paintings by frontier artists, and dramatic reenactments.\n\n===Historic sites and museums===\n{{further|Little House on the Prairie#Little House locations and historical sites}}\n[[File:Laura ingalls wilder memorial society museum grounds.jpg|right|thumb|Laura Ingalls Wilder Memorial Society - De Smet, SD]]\n\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Home and Museum, [[Mansfield, Missouri]]\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Museum, [[Pepin (town), Wisconsin|Pepin, Wisconsin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lauraingallspepin.com/|title=Home |publisher=Laura Ingalls Wilder Museum (lauraingallspepin.com) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Museum, [[Walnut Grove, Minnesota]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walnutgrove.org/museum.htm |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Museum |publisher=Walnut Grove, MN (walnutgrove.org) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Memorial Society museum and historic homes, [[De Smet, South Dakota]];  annual pageant performed here<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ingallshomestead.com/|title=Ingalls Homestead|website=Ingalls Homestead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://discoverlaura.org/|title=Tour the original homes of the Ingalls family|first=Discover Laura|last=Ingalls|website=Laura Ingalls Wilder Historic Homes}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.desmetpageant.org/|title=Laura Ingalls Wilder Pageant|website=Laura Ingalls Wilder Pageant}}</ref>\n* Laura Ingalls Wilder Park and Museum, [[Burr Oak, Iowa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lauraingallswilder.us|title=Home |accessdate=February 24, 2008 |publisher=Laura Ingalls Wilder Park and Museum (lauraingallswilder.us) }}</ref>\n* Little House on the Prairie Museum, [[Independence, Kansas]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.littlehouseontheprairiemuseum.com |title=Home |publisher=Little House on the Prairie Museum (littlehouseontheprairiemuseum.com) |accessdate=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n* Wilder Homestead, [[Malone, New York|Malone, NY]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.almanzowilderfarm.com|title=Wilder Homestead, Boyhood Home of Almanzo|work=almanzowilderfarm.com|accessdate=December 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Portrayals on screen and stage===\n[[Little House on the Prairie#Television adaptations|Multiple adaptations]] of Wilder's ''Little House on the Prairie'' book series have been produced for [[film adaptation|screen]] and [[theatrical adaptation|stage]]. In them, the following actresses have portrayed Wilder:\n\n* [[Melissa Gilbert]] in the television series ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV series)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' and its movie sequels (1974\u20131984)\n* [[Kazuko Sugiyama]] (voice) in the Japanese anime series ''[[Laura, The Prairie Girl]]'' (1975\u20131976)\n* [[Meredith Monroe]], [[Tess Harper]] (elder version), Alandra Bingham (younger version, part 1), Michelle Bevan (younger version, part 2) in part 1 and part 2 of the ''[[Beyond the Prairie: The True Story of Laura Ingalls Wilder]]'' television films (2000 and 2002)\n* [[Kyle Chavarria]] in the TV miniseries ''[[Little House on the Prairie (TV miniseries)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' (2005)\n* [[Kara Lindsay]] in the ''[[Little House on the Prairie (musical)|Little House on the Prairie]]'' [[musical theatre#Book musicals|book musical]] (2008\u20132010)\n\n===Wilder Medal===\n{{main|Laura Ingalls Wilder Medal}}\nWilder was five times a runner-up for the annual [[Newbery Medal]], the premier [[American Library Association]] (ALA) book award for children's literature.{{efn|name=newbery |1=Five times from 1938 to 1944 Wilder was one of the runners-up for the American Library Association [[Newbery Medal]], recognizing the previous year's \"most distinguished contribution to American literature for children\". The honored works were the last five of eight books in the Little House series that were published in her lifetime.<ref name=newbery/>}} In 1954, the ALA inaugurated a lifetime achievement award for children's writers and illustrators, named for Wilder, of which she was the first recipient. The Laura Ingalls Wilder Medal recognizes a living author or illustrator whose books, published in the United States, have made \"a substantial and lasting contribution to literature for children\". As of 2013, it has been conferred nineteen times, biennially starting in 2001.<ref name=wilder/> In 2018, the award was renamed the Children's Literature Legacy Award in light of language in Wilder's works which the Association perceived as biased against [[Native Americans in the United States|Native Americans]] and [[African American]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Association removes Laura Ingalls Wilder's name from award |url=https://apnews.com/19112531f7a24c9c8ab43b7968c96a1d |website=AP News |publisher=Associated Press |accessdate=June 25, 2018|date=June 24, 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Other===\n* [[Google Doodle]] commemorated her 148th birthday in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/laura-ingalls-wilders-148th-birthday?hl=en-GB |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder's 148th Birthday |accessdate=June 10, 2015 }}</ref>\n* [[Hall of Famous Missourians]] at the [[Missouri State Capitol]]\u2014a bronze bust depicting Wilder is on permanent display in the rotunda. She was inducted in 1993.\n* Missouri Walk of Fame\u2014Wilder was honored on the Walk in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cherryblossomfest.com/pages/2006.html|title=2006|publisher=www.cherryblossomfest.com|access-date=2019-05-14}}</ref>\n* [[List of craters on Venus|Wilder crater]] on [[planet]] [[Venus]] was named after Wilder.\n* In her 1916 essay \"Look for Fairies Now\", Wilder asked, \"Of what use are eyes to a tree, I wonder?\". The following century has seen continued research on the detection of [[far-red]] receptors by plants, including as a possible factor in [[crown shyness]].\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Children's literature}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Biography}}\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{notelist}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|refs=<ref name=wilder>\n[http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/wildermedal/wilderpast \"Laura Ingalls Wilder Award, Past winners\"]. [[Association for Library Service to Children]] ('''ALSC'''). [[American Library Association]] ('''ALA''').<br />\n&nbsp; [http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/wildermedal/wilderabout \"About the Laura Ingalls Wilder Award\"]. ALSC. ALA. Retrieved 2013-03-08.</ref>\n<ref name=newbery>\n[http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/newberymedal/newberyhonors/newberymedal \"Newbery Medal and Honor Books, 1922\u2013Present\"]. ALSC. ALA.<br />\n&nbsp; [http://www.ala.org/alsc/awardsgrants/bookmedia/newberymedal/aboutnewbery/aboutnewbery \"The John Newbery Medal\"]. ALSC. ALA. Retrieved 2013-03-08.</ref>\n}}\n\n===Works cited===\n* {{Cite book |author= Holtz, William |title= The Ghost in the Little House: A Life of Rose Wilder Lane |publisher= University of Missouri Press |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-8262-0887-8 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/ghostinlittlehou00holt_0 }}\n* {{Cite book |author=Holtz, William |title=The Ghost in the Little House: A Life of Rose Wilder Lane|publisher= University of Missouri Press |year= 1995 |isbn = 0-8262-1015-5 }} \u2013 Edition: illustrated, reprint, revised; 427 pp.; [https://books.google.com/books?id=inodj1jyRtkC&source=gbs_navlinks_s selections and bibliographic data] retrieved from Google Books 2015-10-15.\n* {{Cite book |author= Miller, John E. |title= Becoming Laura Ingalls Wilder: The Woman Behind the Legend |publisher= University of Missouri Press |year= 1998 |isbn= 0-8262-1167-4 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/becominglauraing0000mill }}\n* {{Cite book |author= Miller, John E. |title= Laura Ingalls Wilder and Rose Wilder Lane: Authorship, Place, Time, and Culture |publisher= University of Missouri Press |year= 2008 |isbn= 978-0-8262-1823-0 |url-access= registration |url= https://archive.org/details/lauraingallswild00mill }}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |hdl=2376/5707 |last1=Campbell |first1=Donna |year=2003 |chapter='Written with a Hard and Ruthless Purpose': Rose Wilder Lane, Edna Ferber, and Middlebrow Regional Fiction |pages=25\u2013 |editor1-last=Botshon |editor1-first=Lisa |editor2-last=Goldsmith |editor2-first=Meredith |title=Middlebrow Moderns: Popular American Women Writers of the 1920s |isbn=978-1-55553-556-8 }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.3102/00028312032003493 |title=Color Blindness and Basket Making Are Not the Answers: Confronting the Dilemmas of Race, Culture, and Language Diversity in Teacher Education |journal=American Educational Research Journal |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=493\u2013522 |year=2016 |last1=Cochran-Smith |first1=Marilyn }}\n*{{cite book |hdl=10150/195771 |type=PhD Thesis |last1=Fatzinger |first1=Amy S. |year=2008 |title=\"Indians in the House\": Revisiting American Indians in Laura Ingalls Wilder's Little House Books |publisher=University of Arizona }}\n*{{cite book |last=Fraser |first=Caroline |author-link=Caroline Fraser |title=[[Prairie Fires: The American Dreams of Laura Ingalls Wilder]] |location=New York |publisher=Metropolitan Books |date=2017}}\n*{{cite journal |jstor=23532729 |first=Philip |last1=Heldrich |year=2000 |title='Going to Indian Territory': Attitudes Toward Native Americans in ''Little House on the Prairie'' |journal=Great Plains Quarterly |volume=20 |issue=2 |pages=99\u2013109 }}\n* {{cite newspaper |first=Patricia Nelson |last=Limerick |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/20/books/review/prairie-fires-laura-ingalls-wilder-biography-caroline-fraser.html |title='Little House on the Prairie' and the Truth About the American West |newspaper=The New York Times |date=November 20, 2017}}\n*{{cite book |title=Laura Ingalls Wilder |author=Sickels, Amy |year=2007 |publisher=Facts On File |isbn=9781438123783 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lauraingallswild0000sick }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1353/chq.0.1688 |title='The Only Good Indian': History, Race, and Representation in Laura Ingalls Wilder's ''Little House on the Prairie'' |journal=Children's Literature Association Quarterly |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=191\u2013201 |year=2002 |last1=Smulders |first1=Sharon }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.3167/ghs.2015.080202 |title=Little Girls on the Prairie and the Possibility of Subversive Reading |journal=Girlhood Studies |volume=8 |issue=2 |pages=4\u201320 |year=2015 |last1=Singer |first1=Amy }}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1353/chq.2013.0019 |title='Counting Coup' on Children's Literature about American Indians: Louise Erdrich's Historical Fiction |journal=Children's Literature Association Quarterly |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=215\u201335 |year=2013 |last1=Stewart |first1=Michelle Pagni }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q237514|s=Author:Laura_Ingalls_Wilder|c=Category:The Ingalls|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|wikt=no}}\n* [http://www.mnopedia.org/person/wilder-laura-ingalls-1867-1957 Laura Ingalls Wilder in MNopedia, the Minnesota Encyclopedia]\n* {{LCAuth|n79095251|Laura Ingalls Wilder|144|}}\n* [http://beyondlittlehouse.com Beyond Little House] - Laura Ingalls Wilder Legacy and Research Association\n* [http://www.liwfrontiergirl.com Laura Ingalls Wilder, Frontier Girl]\n*[https://drive.google.com/open?id=1NuIpb5j