epin, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:People from Wright County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Wilder family]]\n[[Category:Women children's writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from South Dakota]]\n", "name_user": "5.80.249.0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly marriage years)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laura_Ingalls_Wilder"}
{"title_page": "Patriots Day (film)", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Patriots Day\n| image          = Patriots Day (film).png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Berg]]\n| producers      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Scott Stuber]]\n* Dylan Clark\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]]\n* Stephen Levinson\n* Hutch Parker\n* Dorothy Aufiero\n* Michael Radutzky\n}}\n| screenplay = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* Matt Cook\n* Joshua Zetumer\n}}\n| story         = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* Matt Cook\n* Paul Tamasy\n* Eric Johnson\n}}\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]''|[[Casey Sherman]]<br />[[Dave Wedge]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Wahlberg\n* [[Kevin Bacon]]\n* [[John Goodman]]\n* [[J. K. Simmons]]\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trent Reznor]]\n* [[Atticus Ross]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Tobias A. Schliessler]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Colby Parker Jr.\n* Gabriel Fleming\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Closest to the Hole Productions\n* [[Bluegrass Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[CBS Films]] (via [[Lionsgate]])<ref>{{cite news|title=Lionsgate Takes Over CBS Films\u2019 Distribution & Global Sales|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/cbs-films-lionsgate-distribution-sales-partnership-1201283340/|accessdate=November 13, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Business Media|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|11|17|[[AFI Fest]]|2016|12|21|United States}}\n| runtime        = 133 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 132:59 --><ref name=\"BBFC\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/patriots-day-film | title=''Patriots Day'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=December 14, 2016 | accessdate=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $45 million<ref name=\"BOM\" /> \n| gross          = $50.5 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=patriotsday.htm |title=Patriots Day (2016) |website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Patriots Day''''' is a 2016 American crime [[drama]] film about the [[Boston Marathon bombings]] and the subsequent terrorist manhunt. Directed by [[Peter Berg]] and written by Berg, Matt Cook, and Joshua Zetumer, the film is based on the book ''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]'' by [[Casey Sherman]] and [[Dave Wedge]]. It stars [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Kevin Bacon]], [[John Goodman]], [[J.K. Simmons]], [[Michelle Monaghan]], and [[Alex Wolff]]. It marks the third collaboration between Berg and Wahlberg, following ''[[Lone Survivor]]'' and ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]''.\n\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 29, 2016, in [[New York City]], and also filmed in [[Boston]], [[Los Angeles]], [[New Orleans]] and [[Philadelphia]]. The film premiered on November 17, 2016, at the [[AFI Fest]]. Distributed by [[CBS Films]] via [[Lionsgate]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Lionsgate Takes Over CBS Films\u2019 Distribution & Global Sales|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/cbs-films-lionsgate-distribution-sales-partnership-1201283340/|accessdate=November 13, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Business Media|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>, ''Patriots Day'' was released in Boston, New York and Los Angeles on December 21, 2016, followed by a [[Wide release|nationwide expansion]] on January 13, 2017. The film was a box office disappointment, grossing just $50 million worldwide against a production budget of $45 million, but it also received many positive reviews for Berg's direction and the performances of its cast,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-patriots-day-review-20161216-story.html|title='Patriots Day' finds Mark Wahlberg and Peter Berg at their best in a fine tribute to the people of Boston|author=Kenneth Turan|date=20 December 2016|work=latimes.com|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> and was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]] as one of the top ten films of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/2016/ |title=National Board of Review Announces 2016 Award Winners |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe title refers to [[Patriots' Day]], the Massachusetts state holiday on which the Boston Marathon is held.\n\n==Plot==\nOn April 14, 2013, Sergeant Tommy Saunders is capturing a suspect and failing to convince Commissioner Davis to let him off working the marathon as punishment duty the next day. During the [[Boston Marathon]], brothers [[Dzhokhar Tsarnaev|Dzhokhar]] and [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]] detonate two bombs, causing widespread panic. A young couple, Patrick Downes and Jessica Kensky, are injured and taken to separate hospitals, where they are both required to have their legs amputated. Steve Woolfenden, a family man, is also injured and separated from his toddler son, Leo, who is taken by the police to a safe location.\n\nFBI agent Richard DesLauriers is assigned to investigate the bombings in collaboration with  Boston police commissioner [[Edward F. Davis|Ed Davis]], while Police Sergeant Tommy Saunders searches for evidence and helps people that have been injured or separated from their loved ones in the chaos, including Patrick, Jessica, Steven and Leo. FBI analysts review footage of the bombing and identify Dzhokhar and Tamerlan as suspects, but DesLauriers is reluctant to release their pictures to the public without further evidence. His hand is forced when the pictures are leaked to the press, while Pugliese's men begin conducting door-to-door searches for the pair.\n\nDzhokhar and Tamerlan kill officer [[Sean Collier]] in a failed attempt to [[steal]] his pistol, and then carjack student Dun Meng, telling him of their plans to conduct another bombing in [[New York City]]. Just as Dzhokhar enters the [[Shell Gas]] station [[convenience store]], Meng leaves from the vehicle, and runs away fearfully to the [[Mobil]] Gas Station so that he can call the police; the brothers flee in the stolen car. Saunders arrives at the scene, learns of the brothers' plan and is given the stolen car's GPS tracking number, leading police to the pair, which leads to an armed confrontation. The ensuing shootout where the brothers use both firearms and bombs, sees several officers injured. While Tamerlan is shooting, Watertown Police Sergeant Jeffrey Pugliese fires at his ankle, wounding him and hindering his ability to gather more explosives. Tamerlan orders Dzhokhar to run to New York City to continue the rampage while he makes a last stand. As Tamerlan is subdued by the police, Dzhokhar runs over his brother in his flight, killing him as he escapes in the chaos.\n\nMeanwhile, Tamerlan's wife Katherine Russell and Dzhokhar's college friends are detained by the [[Hostage Rescue Team|FBI Hostage Rescue Team]] and questioned by the [[High-Value Interrogation Group]]. Katherine refuses to disclose any knowledge of her husband's illegal activities, paraphrasing the Quran in defiance, while Dzhokhar's friends appear oblivious to his plans, despite having earlier found bomb components in his possessions. A local man named David Henneberry later finds Dzhokhar hiding under the sheets of his boat and calls the police. Dzhokhar is quickly surrounded and arrested after a brief standoff, as Saunders and his colleagues celebrate. The Boston police are invited to attend a [[Boston Red Sox]] game, where [[David Ortiz]] thanks them for their heroism and tells them to \"stay strong\".\n\nDzhokhar was convicted on thirty counts and sentenced to death by [[lethal injection]] and is currently waiting for his appeal in [[ADX Florence|federal prison]]; his three college friends were arrested for obstructing the bombing investigation and authorities are continuing to seek information regarding Russell's possible involvement in the bombings.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]] as [[Boston Police Department]] Sergeant Tommy Saunders \n* [[Kevin Bacon]] as Richard DesLauriers, Special Agent in Charge of the FBI Boston field office\n* [[John Goodman]] as Boston Police Commissioner [[Ed Davis (police commissioner)|Ed Davis]]<ref name=\"GoodmanCast\" />\n* [[J. K. Simmons]] as [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] Police Sergeant Jeffrey Pugliese<ref name=\"Feb2016D\"/>\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]] as Carol Saunders, Tommy's wife and [[registered nurse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patriotsdayfilm.com/synopsis|title=Official movie synopsis|publisher=|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MonaghanCast\"/>\n* [[Alex Wolff]] as [[Dzhokhar Tsarnaev]]<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\"/>\n* Themo Melikidze as [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]]<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\"/>\n* [[Michael Beach]] as [[Governor of Massachusetts]] [[Deval Patrick]]<ref name=\"BeachCast\"/>\n* [[Vincent Curatola]] as [[Boston Mayor]] [[Thomas Menino]]<ref name=\"CuratolaCast\"/>\n* [[James Colby]] as Boston Police Superintendent [[William B. Evans|William Evans]]<ref name=\"ColbyCast\"/>\n* [[Jake Picking]] as [[MIT]] Officer Sean Collier, who was killed by the Tsarnaev brothers 79 hours after the bombings<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n* [[Melissa Benoist]] as Katherine Russell, Tamerlan Tsarnaev's widow<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n*[[Lana Condor]] as Li, Sean Collier's girlfriend and an MIT student\n* [[Jimmy O. Yang]] as Dun Meng ({{zh|c=\u5b5f\u76fe}}),<ref>Chinese name from: {{cite news|url=http://ny.uschinapress.com/weekends/2017/01-13/111620.html|title=\u300a\u7231\u56fd\u8005\u65e5\u300b\u4e0a\u6620 \u518d\u73b0\u6ce2\u9a6c\u7206\u70b8\u6848 \u7559\u5b66\u751f\u5b5f\u76fe\u4e8b\u8ff9\u642c...|newspaper=[[The China Press]]|date=2017-01-13|accessdate=2018-09-22}}</ref> the driver the Tsarnaevs [[carjacked]] 80 hours after the bombing, who escaped at a gas station<ref name=\"YangCast\"/>\n* [[Christopher O'Shea]] as Patrick Downes, who lost his leg in the bombings<ref name=\"Apr2016D\"/> \n* [[Rachel Brosnahan]] as Jessica Kensky, who lost her leg in the bombings<ref name=\"Apr2016D\"/> \n* [[Khandi Alexander]] as Veronica the Interrogator<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n* [[Sean Avery]] as Watertown Officer on Franklin Street\n* [[David Ortiz]] as Himself\n* Cliff Moylan as Sergeant John MacLellan\n* Curtis J. Bellafiore as Officier Joey Reynolds\n* Token as Roommate \nThis film also includes a cameo appearance of the real Dun Meng inside the pizza restaurant in [[Malden, Massachusetts]], as well as the real David Henneberry, who was outside for a short time during the search for the bomber. [[Ken Casey]], singer and bassist for Boston punk band [[Dropkick Murphys]], also has a cameo as a man on a porch.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nThe film was one of what had originally been three proposed about the bombings, the other two being ''Boston Strong'' (based on [[Boston Strong (book)|the book of the same title]]), set to be directed by [[Daniel Espinosa]] and star [[Casey Affleck]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/boston-marathon-bombing-movie-boston-strong-rescued-by-fox/|title=Boston Marathon Bombing Movie 'Boston Strong' Rescued by Fox|first=Jeff|last=Sneider|date=November 18, 2014|website=TheWrap|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Stronger (film)|Stronger]]'', about bombing victim Jeff Bauman, starring [[Jake Gyllenhaal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/jake-gyllenhaal-boston-marathon-bombing-stronger-exclusive-1201552624/|title=Jake Gyllenhaal Circles Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Stronger'|first=Justin|last=Kroll|website=Variety|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> It was to depict [[Edward F. Davis|Boston Police Commissioner Ed Davis]]' experiences during the manhunt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/01/media/60-minutes-movie-patriots-day/index.html|title=CBS to turn '60 Minutes' Segment into 'Patriots Day' Movie|first=Brian|last=Stelter|date=April 1, 2015|website=CNN Money|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> CBS Films purchased the rights to ''Boston Strong'' and merged it into the existing script.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2015/11/15/marathon-movies-patriots-day-and-boston-strong-join-forces/4l8jjHgzi3gnskkeBP1e1N/story.html|title=Movies on Marathon bombings are combined|first=Mark|last=Shanahan|website=Boston Globe|date=November 15, 2015}}</ref> ''Stronger'' was made as a separate film, and released on September 22, 2017.\n\nOn March 31, 2015, [[CBS Films]] announced that it was producing the film as ''Patriots' Day'', depicting the 2013 [[Boston Marathon bombing]] and manhunt.<ref name=March2015Deadline>{{cite web|last=Fleming Jr|first=Mike|title=CBS Films Sets Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Patriots' Day'; Mark Wahlberg Eyes Police Commish Ed Davis Role|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/boston-marathon-bombing-mark-wahlberg-patriots-day-police-commissioner-ed-davis-cbs-films-1201402219/|accessdate=April 4, 2015|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 31, 2015}}</ref> The film's script was written by [[Matt Charman]], and focused on [[Boston Police Department|Boston Police Commissioner]] [[Edward F. Davis]].<ref name=\"March2015Deadline\" /> The film is also based on the book ''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]'' and material from ''[[60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Busch|first=Anita|title=John Goodman Joins Boston Bombing Movie 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/john-goodman-cast-bombing-movie-patriots-day-1201718895/|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> Its final version, not focused specifically on Davis, was written by Peter Berg, Matt Cook, and Joshua Zetumer; [[Mark Wahlberg]] plays police officer Sgt. Tommy Saunders and [[Michelle Monaghan]] plays his wife, Carol.<ref name=\"MonaghanCast\" /> Wahlberg produced the film along with [[Scott Stuber]], Dylan Clark, Stephen Levinson, Michael Radutzky, Hutch Parker, and Dorothy Aufiero.<ref name=\"BaconCast\" /> By February 2016, the title had dropped the apostrophe to become ''Patriots Day''.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\" /> Also by then, [[J. K. Simmons]] had joined the cast as [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] PD Sgt. Jeffrey Pugliese.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\">{{cite web|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=J.K. Simmons Joins Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/jk-simmons-patriots-day-movie-boston-marathon-bombing-1201709405/|accessdate=February 26, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCBS Films and [[Lionsgate]] co-financed the film, with Lionsgate also handling distribution.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\" /> On March 8, 2016, [[Jimmy O. Yang]] joined the film's cast to play Dun Meng, who was carjacked by the Tsarnaev brothers.<ref name=\"YangCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Jimmy O. Yang Joins 'Patriots Day'; Sally Kirkland Cast In 'Most Hated Woman In America'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/jimmy-o-yang-patriots-day-sally-kirkland-most-hated-woman-in-america-1201716650/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cullen|first=Kevin|title=Responsibility worked against carjacking victim Dun Meng|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2015/03/12/the-argument-for-texting-and-driving/d88qK5BV2loEUQ4L7WlCOP/story.html|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Boston Globe|date=March 12, 2015}}</ref> On the same day, [[Vincent Curatola]] was cast to play the [[mayor of Boston]], [[Thomas Menino]], who was in office for his fifth term when the bombings took place.<ref name=\"CuratolaCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Vince Curatola Sworn In As Boston Mayor For 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/vince-curatola-patriots-day-boston-marathon-bombinb-mayor-thomas-menino-1201726400/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> On March 11, 2016, John Goodman signed on to play former Boston Police Commissioner [[Edward F. Davis|Ed Davis]].<ref name=\"GoodmanCast\">{{cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=John Goodman Joins Mark Wahlberg in Boston Marathon Bombing Movie 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-goodman-joins-mark-wahlberg-874651|accessdate=March 12, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> On March 25, 2016, James Colby joined the film to play [[William B. Evans]], a Boston PD superintendent,<ref name=\"ColbyCast\">{{cite web|title=James Colby Joins Mark Wahlberg's Boston Marathon Bombing Drama, 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/james-colby-joins-mark-wahlbergs-878410|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> and following him, [[Michelle Monaghan]] also joined the film, to play Carol Saunders, Tommy's wife.<ref name=\"MonaghanCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Michelle Monaghan Joins 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/michelle-monaghan-patriots-day-boston-marathon-bombing-mark-wahlberg-1201727946/|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 29, 2016}}</ref> On March 31, [[Kevin Bacon]] joined the cast as FBI agent Rick Deslauriers,<ref name=\"BaconCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Kevin Bacon Joins 'Patriots Day' As Key FBI Agent|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/kevin-bacon-patriots-day-fbi-richard-deslauriers-special-agent-in-charge-1201729416/|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 31, 2016}}</ref> and on April 4, 2016, [[Alex Wolff]] and [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm6183987/bio  Themo Melikidze] were cast in the film as Dzhokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev, responsible for the bombing and later manhunt.<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\">{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Alex Wolff, Themo Melikidze to Play Boston Marathon Bombers in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/alex-wolff-themo-melikidze-to-play-boston-marathon-bombers-in-patriots-day-exclusive/|accessdate=April 5, 2016|website=TheWrap|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> [[Michael Beach]] later joined the film to play the [[Governor of Massachusetts]] [[Deval Patrick]].<ref name=\"BeachCast\">{{cite web|last=McNary|first=Dave|title=Michael Beach to Play Gov. Deval Patrick in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/michael-beach-patriots-day-deval-patrick-1201745483/|accessdate=April 5, 2016|website=Variety|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2016, [[Rachel Brosnahan]] and Christopher O'Shea joined the film to play newlyweds Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who were at the finish line, and were both seriously injured but survived.<ref name=\"Apr2016D\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Rachel Brosnahan & Christopher O'Shea Join 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/patriots-day-rachel-brosnahan-christopher-oshea-cast-1201732976/|accessdate=May 6, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 6, 2016}}</ref> The following day, [[Lana Condor]] was cast in the role of Sean Collier's prospective girlfriend.<ref name=\"CondorCast\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/x-men-actress-lana-condor-joins-patriots-day-1201748628/|title='X-Men' Actress Lana Condor Joins 'Patriots Day' (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=April 7, 2016}}</ref> On May 5, 2016, [[Melissa Benoist]] was cast in the film to play Katherine Russell, the widow of Tamerlan Tsarnaev, with [[Khandi Alexander]] set to play a law enforcement interrogator Veronica, [[Jake Picking]] as MIT Police Officer Sean Collier, who was killed 79 hours after the bombing.<ref name=\"May2016TW\">{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Melissa Benoist to Play Boston Marathon Bomber's Widow in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/supergirl-star-melissa-benoist-to-play-boston-marathon-bombers-widow-in-patriots-day/|accessdate=May 6, 2016|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=May 5, 2016}}</ref> [[David Ortiz]], who retired from the [[Boston Red Sox]] after the [[2016 Major League Baseball season|2016 season]], appears as himself.<ref name=\"OrtizCast\">{{cite web|last=Siegel|first=Tatiana|title=Red Sox Slugger David Ortiz to Re-enact Emotional Speech in Boston Bombing Movie (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/red-sox-slugger-david-ortiz-889462|accessdate=May 6, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 29, 2016, in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Find out where Mark Wahlberg will be filming 'Patriots Day' in Massachusetts next week|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2016/03/24/64908/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=On Location Vacations|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Casting Company Seeks Extras For Boston Marathon Bombing Movie|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2016/03/02/patriots-day-mark-wahlberg-boston-marathon-bombings-casting-call/|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=CBSLocal|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Patriots' Day', starring Mark Wahlberg, Open Casting Call will be held in Boston next weekend|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2016/03/05/patriotsdaycastingcall/|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=On Location Vacations|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Tovia|title=Filming For Marathon Bombing Movie Stirs Emotions In Boston|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/03/25/471755112/-its-going-to-trigger-lot-of-ptsd-boston-prepares-for-marathon-bombing-film|accessdate=March 26, 2016|website=NPR|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> with production offices and a soundstage set up in one of the Centennial Park warehouses in [[Peabody, Massachusetts]].  All interior scenes at the FBI warehouse headquarters, as well as exterior 'command tent' scenes, were shot there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salemnews.com/news/local_news/patriots-day-film-company-takes-over-peabody-warehouse/article_0fac0837-787c-50df-a839-41a6f71154ab.html|title='Patriots' Day' film company takes over Peabody warehouse|first=Alan|last=Burke|website=Salem News|date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> Filming was previously scheduled to take place on Laurel Street in [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] to recreate the shootout that took place between police and the Tsarnaev brothers on the actual location, but after objections by residents, town officials denied permission for the film to be shot there.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Palma|first1=Kristi|last2=Hoover|first2=Amanda|title=Some Watertown residents object to film studio's plan to reenact Tsarnaev firefight|url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/2016/02/23/movie-makers-want-recreate-the-watertown-shootout/eJkBEJldbiz6xsw0rFJNzK/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=February 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dwyer|first=Dialynn|title='Patriot's Day' will not film Tsarnaev shootout scenes in Watertown|url=https://www.boston.com/news/2016/02/26/patriot-day-will-not-film-tsarnaev-shootout-scenes-watertown/mb7DDQku94i2xdyiotvdxI/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref> The City of [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] was approached to stand in for Laurel Street, and ended up with eight locations in the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://malden.wickedlocal.com/news/20161102/movie-shoots-are-mini-stimulus-packages-for-malden|title=Movie shoots are mini-stimulus packages for Malden|last=Leibowitz|first=Aaron|newspaper=Malden Observer|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref> The film crew then approached [[University of Massachusetts Dartmouth]] officials for permission to shoot some scenes at the campus, a request that was denied by its chancellor, Gerry Kavanaugh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Marathon filmmakers want to shoot at UMass Dartmouth|url=http://www.southcoasttoday.com/news/20160225/boston-marathon-filmmakers-want-to-shoot-at-umass-dartmouth|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=SouthCoastToday.com|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dwyer|first=Dialynn|title=UMass Dartmouth won't allow 'Patriots' Day' to film on campus|url=https://www.boston.com/news/2016/03/05/umass-dartmouth-won-allow-patriots-day-film-campus/L2fPl6oPMn4jmYf4FBCCHM/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref> [[Simmons College]] stood in the place for exterior shots of UMass Dartmouth.\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where the Tsarnaev brothers killed MIT Police Officer Sean Collier, had allowed the film production to shoot \"entirely peaceful scenes\" on the campus for three days in June.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shanahan|first=Mark|title=Marathon bombing movie to film scenes at MIT|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/03/24/mit-says-patriots-day-director/jcdwKenTHRnCpyzQPMwJiO/story.html|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=Boston Globe|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Letter to the MIT community regarding \"Patriots' Day\" filming|url=https://news.mit.edu/2016/letter-mit-community-regarding-patriots-day-filming-0324|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=MIT|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref> Filming also took place at Collier's actual house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/04/05/patriots-day-scheduled-film-officer-sean-collier-former-residence/hxRsLUpvBuNxE0aSWotusK/story.html|title='Patriots Day' to film at Officer Sean Collier's former residence|first=Steve|last=Annear|website=Boston Globe|date=April 5, 2016}}</ref> The marathon finish line on [[Boylston Street]] was duplicated at the [[Naval Air Station South Weymouth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weymouth.wickedlocal.com/article/20160317/NEWS/160315938|title=PHOTOS: Movie set for \"Patriots' Day\" taking shape at SouthField in Weymouth|website=Wicked Local Weymouth|date=March 17, 2016}}</ref> in addition to scenes filmed at the actual finish line on the day of the 2016 marathon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2016/04/18/mark-wahlberg-patriots-day-scene-filming-boston-marathon-bombing-finish-line/|title=Mark Wahlberg Shoots 'Patriots Day' Scene At Boston Marathon Finish Line|website=CBSLocal|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> Dzhokhar's capture was filmed in [[Framingham, Massachusetts]] on its third anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/04/19/patriots-day-films-capture-scene-framingham/GUzKSWujVyW8sCSH9W9t5N/story.html|title='Patriots Day' films Tsarnaev capture scene in Framingham|first=Mark|last=Shanahan|website=Boston Globe|date=April 19, 2016}}</ref> Additional filming was conducted at [[Doyle's Cafe]] in [[Jamaica Plain]] on April 14, 2016, [[Watertown, Massachusetts]] for shots of the police station and the sequence depicting Dun Meng escaping to the Mobil Gas station unlike the surveillance footage which was shot in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], and at [[Lasell College]] in [[Newton, Massachusetts]] on May 18, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaplainnews.com/2016/04/14/patriots-day-movie-filming-at-doyles-in-jp-today/18490|title='Patriots Day' Movie Filmed at Doyle's in JP Thursday|website=Jamaica Plain News|date=April 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newton.wickedlocal.com/photogallery/WL/20160519/NEWS/519009986/PH/1?refresh=true|title='Patriots Day' films in Newton|website=Wicked Local Newton|date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n{{Main|Patriots Day (soundtrack)}}\n\n[[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-winning composers and [[Nine Inch Nails]] members [[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]] were hired to write the musical score for the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots Day Score Coming from Trent Reznor & Atticus Ross|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/772391-trent-reznor-and-atticus-ross-composing-the-patriots-day-score#/slide/1|accessdate=October 2, 2016|website=ComingSoon.net|date=October 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"Forever (2007 version)\" by [[Dropkick Murphys]] plays during the closing credits of the film; however, it is not included on the film's soundtrack.\n\n== Release ==\n''Patriots Day'' premiered on the closing night of the [[AFI Fest]] on November 17, 2016. It had a red carpet premiere at the [[Wang Theatre|Boch Centre Wang Theatre]] on December 14, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Globe article on Patriots Day premiere|url=https://www.boston.com/culture/entertainment/2016/12/15/the-patriots-day-red-carpet-was-filled-with-celebrities-survivors-and-heroes|accessdate=December 15, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=December 14, 2016}}</ref> The film was released in New York, Boston, Los Angeles, New Orleans, Philadelphia, Sofia, Bulgaria and Paris, France on December 21, 2016, followed by a wide release on January 13, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Wahlberg's 'Patriots Day' Nabs Prime Awards Season Release|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wahlbergs-boston-bombing-movie-patriots-872420|accessdate=March 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Patriots Day'' grossed $31.9 million in the United States and Canada and $18.5 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $50.5 million, against a production budget of $45 million.<ref name=BOM />\n\nIn North America, the film had its expansion alongside the openings of ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'', ''[[The Bye Bye Man]]'', and ''[[Sleepless (2017 film)|Sleepless]]'', as well as the wide expansions of ''[[Silence (2016 film)|Silence]]'' and ''[[Live by Night (film)|Live by Night]]'', and was expected to gross $18\u201320 million from 3,120 theaters in its four-day [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day|MLK]] opening weekend.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-movie-projector-20170109-story.html |title=Mark Wahlberg's 'Patriots Day' and 'La La Land' to battle 'Hidden Figures' for box office win |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> It made $560,000 from Thursday night previews, less than the $860,000 made by Berg and Wahlberg's ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'' in September. The film ended up opening to $12.9 million (a four-day total of $14.2 million), finishing below expectations and 6th at the box office.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/01/patriots-day-sleepless-bye-bye-man-live-by-night-rogue-one-mlk-box-office-1201885490/|title=\u2018Hidden Figures\u2019 Stays Smart, But Why Are So Many Movies Bombing Over MLK Weekend? |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 80% based on 215 reviews, with an average rating of 6.8/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Patriots Day'' offers a stirring, solidly crafted tribute to the heroes of a real-life American tragedy without straying into exploitative action thriller territory.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/patriots_day_2016 |title=Patriots Day (2016) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 13, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 69 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/patriots-day |title=Patriots Day Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A+\" on an A+ to F scale,<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite tweet|user=CinemaScore|number=820147992464424960 |title=@realmonaghan @mark_wahlberg CONGRATULATIONS on your A+ #CinemaScore grade for @patriotsdayfilm http://www.cinemascore.com  |author=[[CinemaScore]] |date=January 13, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref> one of fewer than 90 films in the history of the service to receive such a score.\n\n{{expand section|date=August 2019}}\nKyle Smith of the ''[[New York Post]]'' called it: \"A great American movie about the greatness of ordinary Americans, Patriots Day combines an electrifying manhunt with the intimacy and feel for character writer-director Peter Berg showed in his brilliant TV series [[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|''Friday Night Lights]]''.\"<ref name=\"nypost\">{{cite web |date= 20 December 2016 |last1= Smith |first1= Kyle |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 brilliantly honors American heroes |url= https://nypost.com/2016/12/20/patriots-day-brilliantly-honors-american-heroes/ |website= [[New York Post]] }}</ref>\n\nPeter Debruge of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote: \"It\u2019s genuinely exciting megaplex entertainment, informed by extensive research, featuring bona fide movie stars, and staged with equal degrees of professionalism and respect.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=18 November 2016 |author= Peter Debruge |title= Film Review: \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 |url= https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/patriots-day-review-mark-wahlberg-1201921189/ |website= Variety }}</ref>\n\n===Reception from the Boston area===\nThough the film has mostly garnered approval among critics, many Boston-based publications criticized it for glamorizing the events it was based upon, and for the film's focus on Wahlberg's fictional character. In his review for ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', [[Ty Burr]] wrote: \"It\u2019s professionally made, slickly heartfelt, and is offered up as an act of civic healing. At best, it\u2019s unnecessary. At worst, it\u2019s vaguely insulting\", and when further referencing local moviegoer's reaction to Wahlberg's heroic but fictional Tommy Saunders character, he simply stated, \"We don\u2019t really want to see people who weren\u2019t there. Especially when they\u2019re everywhere\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2016/12/20/patriot-act-marathon-bombing-gets-hollywood-treatment/hy98c7gZs58MLoXmZtgbcJ/story.html|last=Burr|first=Ty |title=\u2018Patriots Day,\u2019 the Marathon bombing movie, is heartfelt and unnecessary |work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners |accessdate=December 20, 2016|date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', Boston-based critic Luke O'Neil also criticized Wahlberg's character, stating: \"For all his talk of honoring his people, Wahlberg seems content to rely on the most hackneyed of Masshole signifiers in their portrayal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a51733/patriots-day-review/ |title=\u2018Patriots Day,\u2019 Review |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=December 21, 2016 |last=O'Neil |first=Luke |accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[The Boston Herald]]'' gave the film a positive review.<ref>{{cite web |date= 20 December 2016 |author= James Verniere |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 captures the drama, horror of marathon attack |url= https://www.bostonherald.com/2016/12/20/patriots-day-captures-the-drama-horror-of-marathon-attack/ |website= [[Boston Herald]] |accessdate= 2019-08-27 }}</ref>\n\nIn response Peter Berg stated that some people automatically disliked the film as they may have been in close proximity to the Boston bombings or they believed the film was made too quickly after the events had occurred.<ref name=\"Selyee\" /> Katharine Q. Seelye, who was not from Boston, wrote in ''[[The New York Times]]'' that the Saunders character was \"[t]he biggest point of divergence\", as Boston-area residents disliked the [[composite character]]'s involvement in all the major events when he was not a single actual person, while people not from the Boston area \"may even appreciate [Saunders] as a narrative device\" and \"have not really questioned\" Saunders's role.<ref name=\"Selyee\" /> She concluded \"that moviegoers outside New England pretty much accept the film on its own terms, as entertainment, and Bostonians do not.\"<ref name=\"Selyee\">{{cite news |date= 2017-01-13 |last= Selyee |first= Katharine Q. |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/13/movies/patriots-day-disconnect-between-bostonians-and-the-rest-of-us.html |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 Disconnect Between Bostonians and the Rest of Us |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |accessdate= 2018-09-27}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe [[National Board of Review Awards 2016|National Board of Review]] honored [[Mark Wahlberg]] and [[Peter Berg]] with their ''Spotlight Award'' for this film (and also for ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/2016/ |title= National Board of Review Announces 2016 Award Winners |work=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n*''[[Dark Night (2016 film)|Dark Night]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.patriotsdayfilm.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|4572514}}\n* {{AllMovie title|654626}}\n* [http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/patriots-day/ ''Patriots Day''] at ''[[History vs. Hollywood]]''\n\n{{Peter Berg}}\n{{Scott Stuber}}\n{{Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross}}\n{{Boston Athletic Association}}\n\n<--!http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/patriots-day-film-->\n<--!http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/patriots-day-film-->\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:CBS Films films]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Thriller films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Crime films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Action films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Boston Police Department]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Berg]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Mark Wahlberg]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2013]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films set in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Steve Jablonsky]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Atticus Ross]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Patriots Day\n| image          = Patriots Day (film).png\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Berg]]\n| producers      = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Scott Stuber]]\n* Dylan Clark\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]]\n* Stephen Levinson\n* Hutch Parker\n* Dorothy Aufiero\n* Michael Radutzky\n}}\n| screenplay = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* Matt Cook\n* Joshua Zetumer\n}}\n| story         = {{Plainlist|\n* Peter Berg\n* Matt Cook\n* Paul Tamasy\n* Eric Johnson\n}}\n| based on = {{Based on|''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]''|[[Casey Sherman]]<br />[[Dave Wedge]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Wahlberg\n* [[Kevin Bacon]]\n* [[John Goodman]]\n* [[J. K. Simmons]]\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Trent Reznor]]\n* [[Atticus Ross]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Tobias A. Schliessler]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* Colby Parker Jr.\n* Gabriel Fleming\n}}\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* Closest to the Hole Productions\n* [[Bluegrass Films]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[CBS Films]] (via [[Lionsgate]])<ref>{{cite news|title=Lionsgate Takes Over CBS Films\u2019 Distribution & Global Sales|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/cbs-films-lionsgate-distribution-sales-partnership-1201283340/|accessdate=November 13, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Business Media|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|11|17|[[AFI Fest]]|2016|12|21|United States}}\n| runtime        = 133 minutes<!-- Theatrical runtime: 132:59 --><ref name=\"BBFC\">{{cite web | url=https://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/patriots-day-film | title=''Patriots Day'' (15) | work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] | date=December 14, 2016 | accessdate=December 14, 2016}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $45 million<ref name=\"BOM\" /> \n| gross          = $50.5 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=patriotsday.htm |title=Patriots Day (2016) |website= [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=August 2, 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Patriots Day''''' is a 2016 American crime [[drama]] film about the [[Boston Marathon bombings]] and the subsequent terrorist manhunt. Directed by [[Peter Berg]] and written by Berg, Matt Cook, and Joshua Zetumer, the film is based on the book ''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]'' by [[Casey Sherman]] and [[Dave Wedge]]. It stars [[Mark Wahlberg]], [[Kevin Bacon]], [[John Goodman]], [[J.K. Simmons]], [[Michelle Monaghan]], and [[Alex Wolff]]. It marks the third collaboration between Berg and Wahlberg, following ''[[Lone Survivor]]'' and ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]''.\n\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 29, 2016, in [[New York City]], and also filmed in [[Boston]], [[Los Angeles]], [[New Orleans]] and [[Philadelphia]]. The film premiered on November 17, 2016, at the [[AFI Fest]]. Distributed by [[CBS Films]] via [[Lionsgate]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Lionsgate Takes Over CBS Films\u2019 Distribution & Global Sales|url=https://deadline.com/2014/11/cbs-films-lionsgate-distribution-sales-partnership-1201283340/|accessdate=November 13, 2014|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=Penske Business Media|date=November 13, 2014}}</ref>, ''Patriots Day'' was released in Boston, New York and Los Angeles on December 21, 2016, followed by a [[Wide release|nationwide expansion]] on January 13, 2017. The film was a box office disappointment, grossing just $50 million worldwide against a production budget of $45 million, but it also received many positive reviews for Berg's direction and the performances of its cast,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-patriots-day-review-20161216-story.html|title='Patriots Day' finds Mark Wahlberg and Peter Berg at their best in a fine tribute to the people of Boston|author=Kenneth Turan|date=20 December 2016|work=latimes.com|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> and was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]] as one of the top ten films of 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/2016/ |title=National Board of Review Announces 2016 Award Winners |publisher=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe title refers to [[Patriots' Day]], the Massachusetts state holiday on which the Boston Marathon is held.\n\n==Plot==\nOn April 14, 2013, Sergeant Tommy Saunders is capturing a suspect and failing to convince Commissioner Davis to let him off working the marathon as punishment duty the next day. During the [[Boston Marathon]], brothers [[Dzhokhar Tsarnaev|Dzhokhar]] and [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]] detonate two bombs, causing widespread panic. A young couple, Patrick Downes and Jessica Kensky, are injured and taken to separate hospitals, where they are both required to have their legs amputated. Steve Woolfenden, a family man, is also injured and separated from his toddler son, Leo, who is taken by the police to a safe location.\n\nFBI agent Richard DesLauriers is assigned to investigate the bombings in collaboration with  Boston police commissioner [[Edward F. Davis|Ed Davis]], while Police Sergeant Tommy Saunders searches for evidence and helps people that have been injured or separated from their loved ones in the chaos, including Patrick, Jessica, Steven and Leo. FBI analysts review footage of the bombing and identify Dzhokhar and Tamerlan as suspects, but DesLauriers is reluctant to release their pictures to the public without further evidence. His hand is forced when the pictures are leaked to the press, while Pugliese's men begin conducting door-to-door searches for the pair.\n\nDzhokhar and Tamerlan kill officer [[Sean Collier]] in a failed attempt to [[steal]] his pistol, and then carjack student Dun Meng, telling him of their plans to conduct another bombing in [[New York City]]. Just as Dzhokhar enters the [[Shell Gas]] station [[convenience store]], Meng leaves from the vehicle, and runs away fearfully to the [[Mobil]] Gas Station so that he can call the police; the brothers flee in the stolen car. Saunders arrives at the scene, learns of the brothers' plan and is given the stolen car's GPS tracking number, leading police to the pair, which leads to an armed confrontation. The ensuing shootout where the brothers use both firearms and bombs, sees several officers injured. While Tamerlan is shooting, Watertown Police Sergeant Jeffrey Pugliese fires at his ankle, wounding him and hindering his ability to gather more explosives. Tamerlan orders Dzhokhar to run to New York City to continue the rampage while he makes a last stand. As Tamerlan is subdued by the police, Dzhokhar runs over his brother in his flight, killing him as he escapes in the chaos.\n\nMeanwhile, Tamerlan's wife Katherine Russell and Dzhokhar's college friends are detained by the [[Hostage Rescue Team|FBI Hostage Rescue Team]] and questioned by the [[High-Value Interrogation Group]]. Katherine refuses to disclose any knowledge of her husband's illegal activities, paraphrasing the Quran in defiance, while Dzhokhar's friends appear oblivious to his plans, despite having earlier found bomb components in his possessions. A local man named David Henneberry later finds Dzhokhar hiding under the sheets of his boat and calls the police. Dzhokhar is quickly surrounded and arrested after a brief standoff, as Saunders and his colleagues celebrate. The Boston police are invited to attend a [[Boston Red Sox]] game, where [[David Ortiz]] thanks them for their heroism and tells them to \"stay strong\".\n\nDzhokhar was convicted on thirty counts and sentenced to death by [[lethal injection]] and is currently waiting for his appeal in [[ADX Florence|federal prison]]; his three college friends were arrested for obstructing the bombing investigation and authorities are continuing to seek information regarding Russell's possible involvement in the bombings.\n\n== Cast ==\n* [[Mark Wahlberg]] as [[Boston Police Department]] Sergeant Tommy Saunders \n* [[Kevin Bacon]] as Richard DesLauriers, Special Agent in Charge of the FBI Boston field office\n* [[John Goodman]] as Boston Police Commissioner [[Ed Davis (police commissioner)|Ed Davis]]<ref name=\"GoodmanCast\" />\n* [[J. K. Simmons]] as [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] Police Sergeant Jeffrey Pugliese<ref name=\"Feb2016D\"/>\n* [[Michelle Monaghan]] as Carol Saunders, Tommy's wife and [[registered nurse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patriotsdayfilm.com/synopsis|title=Official movie synopsis|publisher=|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MonaghanCast\"/>\n* [[Alex Wolff]] as [[Dzhokhar Tsarnaev]]<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\"/>\n* Themo Melikidze as [[Tamerlan Tsarnaev]]<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\"/>\n* [[Michael Beach]] as [[Governor of Massachusetts]] [[Deval Patrick]]<ref name=\"BeachCast\"/>\n* [[Vincent Curatola]] as [[Boston Mayor]] [[Thomas Menino]]<ref name=\"CuratolaCast\"/>\n* [[James Colby]] as Boston Police Superintendent [[William B. Evans|William Evans]]<ref name=\"ColbyCast\"/>\n* [[Jake Picking]] as [[MIT]] Officer Sean Collier, who was killed by the Tsarnaev brothers 79 hours after the bombings<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n* [[Melissa Benoist]] as Katherine Russell, Tamerlan Tsarnaev's widow<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n* [[Jimmy O. Yang]] as Dun Meng ({{zh|c=\u5b5f\u76fe}}),<ref>Chinese name from: {{cite news|url=http://ny.uschinapress.com/weekends/2017/01-13/111620.html|title=\u300a\u7231\u56fd\u8005\u65e5\u300b\u4e0a\u6620 \u518d\u73b0\u6ce2\u9a6c\u7206\u70b8\u6848 \u7559\u5b66\u751f\u5b5f\u76fe\u4e8b\u8ff9\u642c...|newspaper=[[The China Press]]|date=2017-01-13|accessdate=2018-09-22}}</ref> the driver the Tsarnaevs [[carjacked]] 80 hours after the bombing, who escaped at a gas station<ref name=\"YangCast\"/>\n* [[Christopher O'Shea]] as Patrick Downes, who lost his leg in the bombings<ref name=\"Apr2016D\"/> \n* [[Rachel Brosnahan]] as Jessica Kensky, who lost her leg in the bombings<ref name=\"Apr2016D\"/> \n* [[Khandi Alexander]] as Veronica the Interrogator<ref name=\"May2016TW\"/>\n* [[Sean Avery]] as Watertown Officer on Franklin Street\n* [[David Ortiz]] as Himself\n* Cliff Moylan as Sergeant John MacLellan\n* Curtis J. Bellafiore as Officier Joey Reynolds\n* Token as Roommate \nThis film also includes a cameo appearance of the real Dun Meng inside the pizza restaurant in [[Malden, Massachusetts]], as well as the real David Henneberry, who was outside for a short time during the search for the bomber. [[Ken Casey]], singer and bassist for Boston punk band [[Dropkick Murphys]], also has a cameo as a man on a porch.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n== Production ==\n\n=== Development ===\nThe film was one of what had originally been three proposed about the bombings, the other two being ''Boston Strong'' (based on [[Boston Strong (book)|the book of the same title]]), set to be directed by [[Daniel Espinosa]] and star [[Casey Affleck]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/boston-marathon-bombing-movie-boston-strong-rescued-by-fox/|title=Boston Marathon Bombing Movie 'Boston Strong' Rescued by Fox|first=Jeff|last=Sneider|date=November 18, 2014|website=TheWrap|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> and ''[[Stronger (film)|Stronger]]'', about bombing victim Jeff Bauman, starring [[Jake Gyllenhaal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/jake-gyllenhaal-boston-marathon-bombing-stronger-exclusive-1201552624/|title=Jake Gyllenhaal Circles Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Stronger'|first=Justin|last=Kroll|website=Variety|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> It was to depict [[Edward F. Davis|Boston Police Commissioner Ed Davis]]' experiences during the manhunt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/01/media/60-minutes-movie-patriots-day/index.html|title=CBS to turn '60 Minutes' Segment into 'Patriots Day' Movie|first=Brian|last=Stelter|date=April 1, 2015|website=CNN Money|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> CBS Films purchased the rights to ''Boston Strong'' and merged it into the existing script.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2015/11/15/marathon-movies-patriots-day-and-boston-strong-join-forces/4l8jjHgzi3gnskkeBP1e1N/story.html|title=Movies on Marathon bombings are combined|first=Mark|last=Shanahan|website=Boston Globe|date=November 15, 2015}}</ref> ''Stronger'' was made as a separate film, and released on September 22, 2017.\n\nOn March 31, 2015, [[CBS Films]] announced that it was producing the film as ''Patriots' Day'', depicting the 2013 [[Boston Marathon bombing]] and manhunt.<ref name=March2015Deadline>{{cite web|last=Fleming Jr|first=Mike|title=CBS Films Sets Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Patriots' Day'; Mark Wahlberg Eyes Police Commish Ed Davis Role|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/boston-marathon-bombing-mark-wahlberg-patriots-day-police-commissioner-ed-davis-cbs-films-1201402219/|accessdate=April 4, 2015|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 31, 2015}}</ref> The film's script was written by [[Matt Charman]], and focused on [[Boston Police Department|Boston Police Commissioner]] [[Edward F. Davis]].<ref name=\"March2015Deadline\" /> The film is also based on the book ''[[Boston Strong (book)|Boston Strong]]'' and material from ''[[60 Minutes]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Busch|first=Anita|title=John Goodman Joins Boston Bombing Movie 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/john-goodman-cast-bombing-movie-patriots-day-1201718895/|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> Its final version, not focused specifically on Davis, was written by Peter Berg, Matt Cook, and Joshua Zetumer; [[Mark Wahlberg]] plays police officer Sgt. Tommy Saunders and [[Michelle Monaghan]] plays his wife, Carol.<ref name=\"MonaghanCast\" /> Wahlberg produced the film along with [[Scott Stuber]], Dylan Clark, Stephen Levinson, Michael Radutzky, Hutch Parker, and Dorothy Aufiero.<ref name=\"BaconCast\" /> By February 2016, the title had dropped the apostrophe to become ''Patriots Day''.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\" /> Also by then, [[J. K. Simmons]] had joined the cast as [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] PD Sgt. Jeffrey Pugliese.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\">{{cite web|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|title=J.K. Simmons Joins Boston Marathon Bombing Pic 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/jk-simmons-patriots-day-movie-boston-marathon-bombing-1201709405/|accessdate=February 26, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCBS Films and [[Lionsgate]] co-financed the film, with Lionsgate also handling distribution.<ref name=\"Feb2016D\" /> On March 8, 2016, [[Jimmy O. Yang]] joined the film's cast to play Dun Meng, who was carjacked by the Tsarnaev brothers.<ref name=\"YangCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Jimmy O. Yang Joins 'Patriots Day'; Sally Kirkland Cast In 'Most Hated Woman In America'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/jimmy-o-yang-patriots-day-sally-kirkland-most-hated-woman-in-america-1201716650/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Cullen|first=Kevin|title=Responsibility worked against carjacking victim Dun Meng|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2015/03/12/the-argument-for-texting-and-driving/d88qK5BV2loEUQ4L7WlCOP/story.html|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Boston Globe|date=March 12, 2015}}</ref> On the same day, [[Vincent Curatola]] was cast to play the [[mayor of Boston]], [[Thomas Menino]], who was in office for his fifth term when the bombings took place.<ref name=\"CuratolaCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Vince Curatola Sworn In As Boston Mayor For 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/vince-curatola-patriots-day-boston-marathon-bombinb-mayor-thomas-menino-1201726400/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> On March 11, 2016, John Goodman signed on to play former Boston Police Commissioner [[Edward F. Davis|Ed Davis]].<ref name=\"GoodmanCast\">{{cite web|last=Kit|first=Borys|title=John Goodman Joins Mark Wahlberg in Boston Marathon Bombing Movie 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/john-goodman-joins-mark-wahlberg-874651|accessdate=March 12, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 11, 2016}}</ref> On March 25, 2016, James Colby joined the film to play [[William B. Evans]], a Boston PD superintendent,<ref name=\"ColbyCast\">{{cite web|title=James Colby Joins Mark Wahlberg's Boston Marathon Bombing Drama, 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/james-colby-joins-mark-wahlbergs-878410|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> and following him, [[Michelle Monaghan]] also joined the film, to play Carol Saunders, Tommy's wife.<ref name=\"MonaghanCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Michelle Monaghan Joins 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/michelle-monaghan-patriots-day-boston-marathon-bombing-mark-wahlberg-1201727946/|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 29, 2016}}</ref> On March 31, [[Kevin Bacon]] joined the cast as FBI agent Rick Deslauriers,<ref name=\"BaconCast\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Kevin Bacon Joins 'Patriots Day' As Key FBI Agent|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/kevin-bacon-patriots-day-fbi-richard-deslauriers-special-agent-in-charge-1201729416/|accessdate=April 3, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 31, 2016}}</ref> and on April 4, 2016, [[Alex Wolff]] and [https://www.imdb.com/name/nm6183987/bio  Themo Melikidze] were cast in the film as Dzhokhar and Tamerlan Tsarnaev, responsible for the bombing and later manhunt.<ref name=\"Apr2016TW\">{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Alex Wolff, Themo Melikidze to Play Boston Marathon Bombers in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/alex-wolff-themo-melikidze-to-play-boston-marathon-bombers-in-patriots-day-exclusive/|accessdate=April 5, 2016|website=TheWrap|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref> [[Michael Beach]] later joined the film to play the [[Governor of Massachusetts]] [[Deval Patrick]].<ref name=\"BeachCast\">{{cite web|last=McNary|first=Dave|title=Michael Beach to Play Gov. Deval Patrick in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/michael-beach-patriots-day-deval-patrick-1201745483/|accessdate=April 5, 2016|website=Variety|date=April 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2016, [[Rachel Brosnahan]] and Christopher O'Shea joined the film to play newlyweds Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who were at the finish line, and were both seriously injured but survived.<ref name=\"Apr2016D\">{{cite web|last=Pedersen|first=Erik|title=Rachel Brosnahan & Christopher O'Shea Join 'Patriots Day'|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/patriots-day-rachel-brosnahan-christopher-oshea-cast-1201732976/|accessdate=May 6, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 6, 2016}}</ref> The following day, [[Lana Condor]] was cast in the role of Sean Collier's prospective girlfriend.<ref name=\"CondorCast\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/x-men-actress-lana-condor-joins-patriots-day-1201748628/|title='X-Men' Actress Lana Condor Joins 'Patriots Day' (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=April 7, 2016}}</ref> On May 5, 2016, [[Melissa Benoist]] was cast in the film to play Katherine Russell, the widow of Tamerlan Tsarnaev, with [[Khandi Alexander]] set to play a law enforcement interrogator Veronica, [[Jake Picking]] as MIT Police Officer Sean Collier, who was killed 79 hours after the bombing.<ref name=\"May2016TW\">{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Melissa Benoist to Play Boston Marathon Bomber's Widow in 'Patriots Day'|url=https://www.thewrap.com/supergirl-star-melissa-benoist-to-play-boston-marathon-bombers-widow-in-patriots-day/|accessdate=May 6, 2016|website=[[TheWrap]]|date=May 5, 2016}}</ref> [[David Ortiz]], who retired from the [[Boston Red Sox]] after the [[2016 Major League Baseball season|2016 season]], appears as himself.<ref name=\"OrtizCast\">{{cite web|last=Siegel|first=Tatiana|title=Red Sox Slugger David Ortiz to Re-enact Emotional Speech in Boston Bombing Movie (Exclusive)|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/rambling-reporter/red-sox-slugger-david-ortiz-889462|accessdate=May 6, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Filming ===\n[[Principal photography]] began on March 29, 2016, in [[Quincy, Massachusetts]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Find out where Mark Wahlberg will be filming 'Patriots Day' in Massachusetts next week|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2016/03/24/64908/|accessdate=March 28, 2016|website=On Location Vacations|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Casting Company Seeks Extras For Boston Marathon Bombing Movie|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2016/03/02/patriots-day-mark-wahlberg-boston-marathon-bombings-casting-call/|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=CBSLocal|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='Patriots' Day', starring Mark Wahlberg, Open Casting Call will be held in Boston next weekend|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2016/03/05/patriotsdaycastingcall/|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=On Location Vacations|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Tovia|title=Filming For Marathon Bombing Movie Stirs Emotions In Boston|url=https://www.npr.org/2016/03/25/471755112/-its-going-to-trigger-lot-of-ptsd-boston-prepares-for-marathon-bombing-film|accessdate=March 26, 2016|website=NPR|date=March 25, 2016}}</ref> with production offices and a soundstage set up in one of the Centennial Park warehouses in [[Peabody, Massachusetts]].  All interior scenes at the FBI warehouse headquarters, as well as exterior 'command tent' scenes, were shot there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.salemnews.com/news/local_news/patriots-day-film-company-takes-over-peabody-warehouse/article_0fac0837-787c-50df-a839-41a6f71154ab.html|title='Patriots' Day' film company takes over Peabody warehouse|first=Alan|last=Burke|website=Salem News|date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> Filming was previously scheduled to take place on Laurel Street in [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Watertown]] to recreate the shootout that took place between police and the Tsarnaev brothers on the actual location, but after objections by residents, town officials denied permission for the film to be shot there.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Palma|first1=Kristi|last2=Hoover|first2=Amanda|title=Some Watertown residents object to film studio's plan to reenact Tsarnaev firefight|url=https://www.boston.com/news/local/2016/02/23/movie-makers-want-recreate-the-watertown-shootout/eJkBEJldbiz6xsw0rFJNzK/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=February 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dwyer|first=Dialynn|title='Patriot's Day' will not film Tsarnaev shootout scenes in Watertown|url=https://www.boston.com/news/2016/02/26/patriot-day-will-not-film-tsarnaev-shootout-scenes-watertown/mb7DDQku94i2xdyiotvdxI/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=February 26, 2016}}</ref> The City of [[Malden, Massachusetts|Malden]] was approached to stand in for Laurel Street, and ended up with eight locations in the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://malden.wickedlocal.com/news/20161102/movie-shoots-are-mini-stimulus-packages-for-malden|title=Movie shoots are mini-stimulus packages for Malden|last=Leibowitz|first=Aaron|newspaper=Malden Observer|access-date=2017-01-05}}</ref> The film crew then approached [[University of Massachusetts Dartmouth]] officials for permission to shoot some scenes at the campus, a request that was denied by its chancellor, Gerry Kavanaugh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Marathon filmmakers want to shoot at UMass Dartmouth|url=http://www.southcoasttoday.com/news/20160225/boston-marathon-filmmakers-want-to-shoot-at-umass-dartmouth|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=SouthCoastToday.com|date=February 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dwyer|first=Dialynn|title=UMass Dartmouth won't allow 'Patriots' Day' to film on campus|url=https://www.boston.com/news/2016/03/05/umass-dartmouth-won-allow-patriots-day-film-campus/L2fPl6oPMn4jmYf4FBCCHM/story.html|accessdate=March 8, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=March 5, 2016}}</ref> [[Simmons College]] stood in the place for exterior shots of UMass Dartmouth.\n\nThe [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], where the Tsarnaev brothers killed MIT Police Officer Sean Collier, had allowed the film production to shoot \"entirely peaceful scenes\" on the campus for three days in June.<ref>{{cite web|last=Shanahan|first=Mark|title=Marathon bombing movie to film scenes at MIT|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/03/24/mit-says-patriots-day-director/jcdwKenTHRnCpyzQPMwJiO/story.html|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=Boston Globe|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Letter to the MIT community regarding \"Patriots' Day\" filming|url=https://news.mit.edu/2016/letter-mit-community-regarding-patriots-day-filming-0324|accessdate=March 31, 2016|website=MIT|date=March 24, 2016}}</ref> Filming also took place at Collier's actual house.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/metro/2016/04/05/patriots-day-scheduled-film-officer-sean-collier-former-residence/hxRsLUpvBuNxE0aSWotusK/story.html|title='Patriots Day' to film at Officer Sean Collier's former residence|first=Steve|last=Annear|website=Boston Globe|date=April 5, 2016}}</ref> The marathon finish line on [[Boylston Street]] was duplicated at the [[Naval Air Station South Weymouth]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://weymouth.wickedlocal.com/article/20160317/NEWS/160315938|title=PHOTOS: Movie set for \"Patriots' Day\" taking shape at SouthField in Weymouth|website=Wicked Local Weymouth|date=March 17, 2016}}</ref> in addition to scenes filmed at the actual finish line on the day of the 2016 marathon.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2016/04/18/mark-wahlberg-patriots-day-scene-filming-boston-marathon-bombing-finish-line/|title=Mark Wahlberg Shoots 'Patriots Day' Scene At Boston Marathon Finish Line|website=CBSLocal|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> Dzhokhar's capture was filmed in [[Framingham, Massachusetts]] on its third anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/lifestyle/names/2016/04/19/patriots-day-films-capture-scene-framingham/GUzKSWujVyW8sCSH9W9t5N/story.html|title='Patriots Day' films Tsarnaev capture scene in Framingham|first=Mark|last=Shanahan|website=Boston Globe|date=April 19, 2016}}</ref> Additional filming was conducted at [[Doyle's Cafe]] in [[Jamaica Plain]] on April 14, 2016, [[Watertown, Massachusetts]] for shots of the police station and the sequence depicting Dun Meng escaping to the Mobil Gas station unlike the surveillance footage which was shot in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]], and at [[Lasell College]] in [[Newton, Massachusetts]] on May 18, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jamaicaplainnews.com/2016/04/14/patriots-day-movie-filming-at-doyles-in-jp-today/18490|title='Patriots Day' Movie Filmed at Doyle's in JP Thursday|website=Jamaica Plain News|date=April 14, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newton.wickedlocal.com/photogallery/WL/20160519/NEWS/519009986/PH/1?refresh=true|title='Patriots Day' films in Newton|website=Wicked Local Newton|date=May 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\n{{Main|Patriots Day (soundtrack)}}\n\n[[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-winning composers and [[Nine Inch Nails]] members [[Trent Reznor]] and [[Atticus Ross]] were hired to write the musical score for the film.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patriots Day Score Coming from Trent Reznor & Atticus Ross|url=https://www.comingsoon.net/movies/news/772391-trent-reznor-and-atticus-ross-composing-the-patriots-day-score#/slide/1|accessdate=October 2, 2016|website=ComingSoon.net|date=October 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n\"Forever (2007 version)\" by [[Dropkick Murphys]] plays during the closing credits of the film; however, it is not included on the film's soundtrack.\n\n== Release ==\n''Patriots Day'' premiered on the closing night of the [[AFI Fest]] on November 17, 2016. It had a red carpet premiere at the [[Wang Theatre|Boch Centre Wang Theatre]] on December 14, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boston Globe article on Patriots Day premiere|url=https://www.boston.com/culture/entertainment/2016/12/15/the-patriots-day-red-carpet-was-filled-with-celebrities-survivors-and-heroes|accessdate=December 15, 2016|website=Boston.com|date=December 14, 2016}}</ref> The film was released in New York, Boston, Los Angeles, New Orleans, Philadelphia, Sofia, Bulgaria and Paris, France on December 21, 2016, followed by a wide release on January 13, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mark Wahlberg's 'Patriots Day' Nabs Prime Awards Season Release|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wahlbergs-boston-bombing-movie-patriots-872420|accessdate=March 8, 2016|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=March 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n''Patriots Day'' grossed $31.9 million in the United States and Canada and $18.5 million in other territories for a worldwide total of $50.5 million, against a production budget of $45 million.<ref name=BOM />\n\nIn North America, the film had its expansion alongside the openings of ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'', ''[[The Bye Bye Man]]'', and ''[[Sleepless (2017 film)|Sleepless]]'', as well as the wide expansions of ''[[Silence (2016 film)|Silence]]'' and ''[[Live by Night (film)|Live by Night]]'', and was expected to gross $18\u201320 million from 3,120 theaters in its four-day [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day|MLK]] opening weekend.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/hollywood/la-fi-ct-movie-projector-20170109-story.html |title=Mark Wahlberg's 'Patriots Day' and 'La La Land' to battle 'Hidden Figures' for box office win |work=[[Los Angeles Times]]}}</ref> It made $560,000 from Thursday night previews, less than the $860,000 made by Berg and Wahlberg's ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'' in September. The film ended up opening to $12.9 million (a four-day total of $14.2 million), finishing below expectations and 6th at the box office.<ref name=\"opening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/01/patriots-day-sleepless-bye-bye-man-live-by-night-rogue-one-mlk-box-office-1201885490/|title=\u2018Hidden Figures\u2019 Stays Smart, But Why Are So Many Movies Bombing Over MLK Weekend? |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn review aggregator [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 80% based on 215 reviews, with an average rating of 6.8/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Patriots Day'' offers a stirring, solidly crafted tribute to the heroes of a real-life American tragedy without straying into exploitative action thriller territory.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/patriots_day_2016 |title=Patriots Day (2016) |publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |accessdate=April 13, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[Weighted arithmetic mean|weighted average]] score of 69 out of 100, based on 42 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/patriots-day |title=Patriots Day Reviews|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|work=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"A+\" on an A+ to F scale,<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite tweet|user=CinemaScore|number=820147992464424960 |title=@realmonaghan @mark_wahlberg CONGRATULATIONS on your A+ #CinemaScore grade for @patriotsdayfilm http://www.cinemascore.com  |author=[[CinemaScore]] |date=January 13, 2017 |accessdate=February 26, 2018}}</ref> one of fewer than 90 films in the history of the service to receive such a score.\n\n{{expand section|date=August 2019}}\nKyle Smith of the ''[[New York Post]]'' called it: \"A great American movie about the greatness of ordinary Americans, Patriots Day combines an electrifying manhunt with the intimacy and feel for character writer-director Peter Berg showed in his brilliant TV series [[Friday Night Lights (TV series)|''Friday Night Lights]]''.\"<ref name=\"nypost\">{{cite web |date= 20 December 2016 |last1= Smith |first1= Kyle |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 brilliantly honors American heroes |url= https://nypost.com/2016/12/20/patriots-day-brilliantly-honors-american-heroes/ |website= [[New York Post]] }}</ref>\n\nPeter Debruge of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote: \"It\u2019s genuinely exciting megaplex entertainment, informed by extensive research, featuring bona fide movie stars, and staged with equal degrees of professionalism and respect.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=18 November 2016 |author= Peter Debruge |title= Film Review: \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 |url= https://variety.com/2016/film/reviews/patriots-day-review-mark-wahlberg-1201921189/ |website= Variety }}</ref>\n\n===Reception from the Boston area===\nThough the film has mostly garnered approval among critics, many Boston-based publications criticized it for glamorizing the events it was based upon, and for the film's focus on Wahlberg's fictional character. In his review for ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', [[Ty Burr]] wrote: \"It\u2019s professionally made, slickly heartfelt, and is offered up as an act of civic healing. At best, it\u2019s unnecessary. At worst, it\u2019s vaguely insulting\", and when further referencing local moviegoer's reaction to Wahlberg's heroic but fictional Tommy Saunders character, he simply stated, \"We don\u2019t really want to see people who weren\u2019t there. Especially when they\u2019re everywhere\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/movies/2016/12/20/patriot-act-marathon-bombing-gets-hollywood-treatment/hy98c7gZs58MLoXmZtgbcJ/story.html|last=Burr|first=Ty |title=\u2018Patriots Day,\u2019 the Marathon bombing movie, is heartfelt and unnecessary |work=[[The Boston Globe]]|publisher=Boston Globe Media Partners |accessdate=December 20, 2016|date=December 20, 2016}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', Boston-based critic Luke O'Neil also criticized Wahlberg's character, stating: \"For all his talk of honoring his people, Wahlberg seems content to rely on the most hackneyed of Masshole signifiers in their portrayal.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/movies/a51733/patriots-day-review/ |title=\u2018Patriots Day,\u2019 Review |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=December 21, 2016 |last=O'Neil |first=Luke |accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[The Boston Herald]]'' gave the film a positive review.<ref>{{cite web |date= 20 December 2016 |author= James Verniere |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 captures the drama, horror of marathon attack |url= https://www.bostonherald.com/2016/12/20/patriots-day-captures-the-drama-horror-of-marathon-attack/ |website= [[Boston Herald]] |accessdate= 2019-08-27 }}</ref>\n\nIn response Peter Berg stated that some people automatically disliked the film as they may have been in close proximity to the Boston bombings or they believed the film was made too quickly after the events had occurred.<ref name=\"Selyee\" /> Katharine Q. Seelye, who was not from Boston, wrote in ''[[The New York Times]]'' that the Saunders character was \"[t]he biggest point of divergence\", as Boston-area residents disliked the [[composite character]]'s involvement in all the major events when he was not a single actual person, while people not from the Boston area \"may even appreciate [Saunders] as a narrative device\" and \"have not really questioned\" Saunders's role.<ref name=\"Selyee\" /> She concluded \"that moviegoers outside New England pretty much accept the film on its own terms, as entertainment, and Bostonians do not.\"<ref name=\"Selyee\">{{cite news |date= 2017-01-13 |last= Selyee |first= Katharine Q. |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/13/movies/patriots-day-disconnect-between-bostonians-and-the-rest-of-us.html |title= \u2018Patriots Day\u2019 Disconnect Between Bostonians and the Rest of Us |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |accessdate= 2018-09-27}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\nThe [[National Board of Review Awards 2016|National Board of Review]] honored [[Mark Wahlberg]] and [[Peter Berg]] with their ''Spotlight Award'' for this film (and also for ''[[Deepwater Horizon (film)|Deepwater Horizon]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/award-years/2016/ |title= National Board of Review Announces 2016 Award Winners |work=[[National Board of Review]] |date=November 29, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n*''[[Dark Night (2016 film)|Dark Night]]''\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.patriotsdayfilm.com/}}\n* {{IMDb title|4572514}}\n* {{AllMovie title|654626}}\n* [http://www.historyvshollywood.com/reelfaces/patriots-day/ ''Patriots Day''] at ''[[History vs. Hollywood]]''\n\n{{Peter Berg}}\n{{Scott Stuber}}\n{{Trent Reznor and Atticus Ross}}\n{{Boston Athletic Association}}\n\n<--!http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/patriots-day-film-->\n<--!http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/patriots-day-film-->\n\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American crime drama films]]\n[[Category:American crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:American action thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:CBS Films films]]\n[[Category:Drama films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Thriller films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Crime films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Action films based on actual events]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Boston Police Department]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Peter Berg]]\n[[Category:Films produced by Mark Wahlberg]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films set in 2013]]\n[[Category:Films set in Boston]]\n[[Category:Films set in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Steve Jablonsky]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Atticus Ross]]\n[[Category:Federal Bureau of Investigation in fiction]]\n[[Category:Films about terrorism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Factfanatic1", "label": "safe", "comment": "Lana Condor's credit was missing on this page even though she had a sizable speaking role and several cast members who had smaller roles than her were listed, so I added it.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patriots_Day_(film)"}
{"title_page": "Mutty Lall Seal", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|for=prose and grammar|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mutty Lall Seal\n| image        = Mutty_Lal_Seal.jpg\n| image_size   = 200px\n| caption      = Mutty Lall Seal\n| birth_date   = 1792\n| birth_place  = [[Kolkata]]\n| death_date   = 20 May 1854\n| death_place  = [[Kolkata]]\n| occupation   = Businessman\n| spouse       = \n| nationality  = Indian\n}}\n\n'''Mutty Lall Seal''' (also spelt '''Mutty Loll Seal''' or '''Mati Lall Seal''' or '''Motilal Seal''') (1792 \u2013 20 May 1854) was a businessman and philanthropist from [[India]]. Seal begin his life as a bottle and cork dealer but later became very wealthy. He donated large sums of his wealth to charity and education. Seal and [[Ramdulal Sarkar]], another renowned [[Business magnate|shipping magnate]], became part of the Bengali folklore as great merchant princes.<ref>Bhattacharya, Sabyasachi, ''Traders and Trades in Old Calcutta'', in ''Calcutta, the Living City'', Vol I, p 209.</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMutty Lall Seal was born in a [[Bengali Hindu]] family in [[Kolkata|Calcutta]] (now Kolkata), 1792. His father Chaitanya Charan Seal, a [[cloth merchant]], died when Seal was just five years old. His early education began in a ''[[pathshala]] (Indian rural school);'' later he continued his studies at the Martin Bowl English School and the Baboo Nityananda Sen High School. \n\nIn 1809, at the age of seventeen, he was married to Nagri Dassee, the daughter of Mohan Chand Dey from the Surtir Bagan neighbourhood of Kolkata. Seal accompanied his father-in-law on a pilgrimage to northern and western India and was said to be greatly enlightened by his spiritual experience on the journey. Around 1815, he started working at [[Fort William, India|Fort William]] and then the bastion of British power. While working at Fort William, he was involved in the supply of essential commodities to the British army. Later, he worked as an inspector for [[Indian Customs services|Indian Customs]] at [[Bali Khalk|Balikhal]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Achievements==\n\n===Business activities===\n[[File:Sketch of Mutty Lal Seal's residential house at Colootola.jpg|thumb|right|Sketch of Mutty Lall Seal's residential house at Colootola]]\nSeal started his business career by selling bottles and corks to Mr. Hudson, who was one of the most extensive importers of beer in those days.<ref>Mitra, Kissory Chand, ''Mutty Lall Seal'', Calcutta, 1869, p 5-6</ref> Mr. Hudson traded in [[Cowhide|cowhides]] and was the founder and promoter of the first indigo mart, which was established under the name of M/s. Moore, Hickey & Co. The English merchants used to hire Seal for his sound judgement on indigo, silk, sugar, rice, saltpeter, etc. He was appointed as \"Banian\" to around twenty first class agency houses out of around fifty or sixty such houses in Calcutta. Later he became a landed property speculator and merchant successively in partnership with Fergusson Brothers & Co., Oswald Seal & Co. and Tulloh & Co., and in these three firms he was said to have lost some thirty [[Lakh]] of [[Rupee|rupees]]. He got into exporting indigo, silk, sugar, rice, saltpeter to Europe and importing of iron and cotton-piece goods from England.<ref>Chakrabarty, Dipesh, ''The Colonial context of the Bengal Renaissance: A Note On Early Railway Thinking In Bengal'', in ''Indian Economic and Social History Review'', Vol. XI, No. 1, March 1974</ref> Seal acquired a number of [[Cargo ship|cargo boats]] which were then new to the market, worked the old flour mills, and shipped cargoes of biscuits to [[Australia]] for the first [[Emigration|emigrants]] to its newly discovered gold fields. Later, he put up a mill to refine sugar on the centrifugal principle.\n\nThe first to use steamships for internal trade in [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], he prospered in competition with Europeans. He owned around thirteen trade ships including a steam tug named 'Banian'. He made a fortune in a single generation through money-dealing, a phrase which does not merely refer to money-lending, bill discounting and other banking business. There was scarcely a speculation into which he did not enter, and for which he did not supply a portion of funds. From dealings in internal exchanges to contracts for station-building, for the erection of new bazaars, to the revival of transit companies, rare was an undertaking in which he was not an important, though quiet, shareholder. He funded every promising enterprise he found and made profits in the shape of interest.<ref>''Allen's Indian Mail, And Register Of Intelligence For British And Foreign India, China, And All Parts Of The East'', Vol XII, January\u2013December 1854, p 382</ref> At one point he was in complete control over the market dealing in company papers.<ref>Sastri, Sivanath, ''[[Ramtanu Lahiri O Tatkalin Bangasamaj]]'', p 71</ref> Seal was one of the founders of Assam Company Ltd.\n\nUnder his influence, the European-created Oriental Life Insurance Company (later reconstructed as New Oriental Insurance Company in 1834), the first life insurance company on Indian soil, began to underwrite Indian lives.<ref>Rungta, Radhe Shyam ''Rise of Business Corporations in India 1851\u20131900'', p 12-13</ref> He was among the founders of the Bank of India, and was on the board of the Agricultural And Horticultural Society of India.<ref>''Parbury's Oriental Herald And Colonial Intelligencer'', Vol II, July\u2013December 1838, p 28</ref><ref>''The Calcutta Monthly Journal And General Register of Occurrences Throughout The British Dominions in the East Forming An Epitome of the Indian Press'', For The Year 1836, Calcutta, p 204</ref> In time, he amassed as much wealth as [[Dwarkanath Tagore]] and Rustomjee Cowasjee. In 1878, Kishori Chand Mitra delivered a lecture on the life of Seal calling him the \"[[Rothschild]] of Calcutta\".<ref>Sarkar, Tanika, ''Hindu Wife, Hindu Nation'', p 34</ref> Pandith Sivanath Sastri wrote: \"He never adopted unfair means for earning money. He was well-behaved, polite and helpful to others.\"\n\n===Philanthropy===\nAs a philanthropist, Seal founded an alms house at [[Belgharia]] (in the suburbs of Calcutta) in 1841, where on average 500 people were fed daily,<ref>Banerjee, Prajnananda, ''Calcutta and Its Hinterland: A Study in Economic History of India, 1833\u20131900'', p 144\n</ref> and is still open to the poor. It has a bathing ''[[Ghats|ghat]]'' which exists today on the bank of the [[Hooghly River]] known as Motilal Ghat\n\nHe was well known as the donor of an extensive tract of land, which at the time was valued at Rs. 12,000,<ref>''Third Report of the Committee Appointed by the Right Honourable The Governour of Bengal for the Establishment of a Fever Hospital And For Inquiring into Local Management And Taxation in Calcutta, Calcutta: Bishop's College Press, 1847,'' p 35</ref> to the then British Government on which the [[Calcutta Medical College]] was built. The Government of Bengal recognized his liberality by naming a ward in his honor, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080511234715/http://www.medicalcollegekolkata.org/personalities.html ''The Mutty Lall Seal Ward''], for native male patients. Seal subsequently supplemented this gift by a donation of a lac of rupees for the establishment of a female (lying in) hospital which started functioning in 1838.<ref>''Missionary And Religious Intelligence'', in ''The Calcutta Christian Observer'', Vol. I, New Series, January\u2013December 1840, p 171</ref>\n\n[[Image:Mutty Lall Seal's Shrine - Belgharia - North 24 Parganas 2012-04-11 9732.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Mutty Lall Seal's shrine and almshouse on B T road]]\n\nIn those days the [[Hindus|Hindu]] community was alarmed, owing to several conversions to Christianity taking place among the boys at missionary schools offering free education. (Seal himself did partnership with Fergusson Brothers, they did not ask him to convert to [[Christianity]] to do business. Education was not provided for converting to Christianity, many of the people educated outside India at the time were Christians, including [[Mahatma Gandhi]].) To counter this, there was an anti-missionary movement led by the rich and influential [[Babu (title)|Babu]] of Calcutta for a free national school of their own. \n\nOne afternoon they all assembled in a meeting presided over by [[Radhakanta Deb|Raja Radha Kanta Deb]] at the [[Oriental Seminary]]. Many speeches were made and resolutions adopted, but donations recorded in the subscription book were scant. When the book passed to the hand of Seal, he immediately put down his name for one [[Lakh]] of rupees. Others who had estimated contributing a few hundred or a few thousand rupees panicked and the meeting ended.\n\nPledged to his subscription, Seal carried out the promise of a national institution with his own independent efforts. On Wednesday, 1 March 1842, a gathering of respectable people took place at his house for the formal opening of the Mutty Lall Seal's Free College. Among those present were Sir Lawrence Peel, the Chief Justice; Sir [[John Peter Grant]]; Mr. Lyall, the Advocate-General; Mr. Leith and the other principal members of the Calcutta Bar; Captain Birch, Superintendent of the Police; Mr. George Thompson; Right Reverend Dr. Carew; Baboo [[Dwarkanath Tagore]]; Baboo [[Ramkamal Sen]]; Baboo Russomoy Dutt and Revd. [[Krishna Mohan Banerjee]]. The Catholic Bishop and all the clergy of the Catholic Cathedral, as well as all the Professors of [[St. Xavier's College, Calcutta|St. Xavier's College]], were likewise present. Nearly the whole of the dissenting ministers and missionaries of Calcutta and its neighbourhood also attended.<ref>''The Catholic Cabinet, And Chronicle of Religious Intelligence, Containing Original And Selected Articles, A Monthly Periodical'', Volume I, 1843, p 187</ref> There were eloquent speeches in testimony to his noble generosity and liberal mindset with Mr. George Thompson complimenting him as \"a Hindu gentleman, who had nobly resolved to consecrate a large portion of the substances he had acquired by honorable exertion, to the intellectual improvement of the youth of his own nation to transmute his money into mind\"''.<ref>Mullick, Promatha Nath, ''History of Vaisyas of Bengal'', p 136-139</ref>''\n\nMutty Lall Seal's Free College (later renamed Mutty Lall Seal's Free School and College) was to provide for the education of Hindus to enable them to occupy posts of trust and emolument in their own country. This education included [[English Literature]], History, [[Geography]], [[Elocution]], Writing, [[Arithmetic]], [[Algebra]], Philosophical Sciences, [[Further Mathematics|Higher Mathematics]] and the practical application of Mathematics. The institution was opened free of cost, only one rupee was charged per month to cover expenses such as books and stationery and the surplus being expended towards furnishing the school with mathematical instruments. The number of students receiving education at one time was to be limited to 500. The institute was initially under the management of the Directors of the parent college of [[St. Xavier's College, Calcutta|St. F. Xavier]], Chowringhee, Calcutta, who furnished teachers to further the cause of [[secular education]].<ref>''Goethals News'', Vol. IV, No. 3 Bulletin, July \u2013 September 2001</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] had the responsibility of imparting education, the conductors had pledged themselves to withhold all Christian instruction from the pupils.<ref>''The Calcutta Review'', Vol. II, October\u2013December 1844, p 73</ref> However, later Seal dissolved the connection between his college and the Jesuits over a dispute that in violation of their pledge, viands were distributed among the Hindu boys contrary to their religious sentiments. The institute was then placed under Revd. [[Krishna Mohan Banerjee]].<ref>''The Indian Mail, A Monthly Register For British & Foreign India, China, & Australasia'', Vol. I, May\u2013December 1843, p 614-615</ref> A sum of Rs. 12,000 was spent yearly for the upkeep of the college from his trust. The college stood in high estimation of the public and competed successfully with the Government and Missionary Colleges in the university examinations ([[Suniti Kumar Chatterji]] and [[A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada|Swami Prabhupada]] were some students of the college). The college initially started functioning at Seal's house and was later shifted to the present building on [[Chittaranjan Avenue]] where it still exists.\n\nThe other charities which have made his name known to the public are contained in a deed of trust; by which he donated a considerable portion of his property (amounting to several [[Lakh]] of rupees) for the good of the public. A net yearly income of Rs. 36,000 derived from those properties were spent for various charitable purposes. Apart from running and maintaining the college, about Rs. 4,000 was spent on helping poor widows and orphans every year and for running and maintaining two alms houses for the poor and underprivileged.<ref>''The Calcutta Review'', Vol. CXI, Calcutta, 1900, p 86-88</ref> He extended financial support and co-operation for the establishment of the Hindu Charitable Institution and Hindu Metropolitan College. Seal's Free School, Hindu Metropolitan College and some of the other institutions of the time were calculated to offset the 'ill effects' of the liberal education offered at the [[Presidency College, Kolkata|Hindu College]].<ref>Majumdar, Swapan, ''Literature and Literary Life in Old Calcutta'', in ''Calcutta, the Living City'', Vol I, p 110.</ref>\n<gallery>\nImage:Mutty Lal Seal's devalaya at Belghoria.jpg|Devalaya at Mutty Lall Seal's Belghoria alms house\nImage:Mutty Lal Seal's guest house at Behala.jpg|Mutty Lall Seal's guest house at Behala\nImage:Mutty Lal Seal's bathing ghat.jpg|Mutty Lall Seal's bathing ghat on the bank of river Hooghly\nImage:Mutty Lal Seal's Free School.jpg|Mutty Lall Seal's Free School & College - Estd. 1842\n</gallery>\n\n==Later life==\nWhen he was alive, the native society of Kolkata was divided into two parts. One was the reformist section led by [[Ram Mohan Roy|Raja Rammohun Roy]] and the other was the conservative section led by [[Radhakanta Deb|Radha Kanta Deb]]. Most of the rich people of Kolkata were in the latter group. Deb strongly opposed both the move to ban [[Sati (practice)|sati]] and efforts for remarriage of widows, many of whom were child-widows. Although Seal was a conservative, he was in favor of Roy's efforts of banning sati, supported the cause of women's education as well as remarriage of widows. He made a public offer for a dowry of 1000 rupees to the person who should have the courage to break through the ancient prejudices of caste and marry a widow.<ref>Ripley, George, Dana, Charles A.,''The New American Cyclopaedia: A Popular Dictionary Of General Knowledge'', Vol. II, 1859, p 443</ref> When Seal died on 20 May 1854, his obituary in the ''Hindu Intelligence'' described him as the \"richest and most virtuous [[Babu (title)|Babu]] of Calcutta\".<ref>Sengupta, Nitish, ''History Of The Bengali Speaking People'', p 259-260</ref> One of the busy streets in Kolkata's business district is named after him as 'Moti Sil Street'.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Citation\n | surname1 = Chaudhuri \n | given1 = Sukanta (Ed)\n | year = 1995\n | title = Calcutta: The Living City\n | edition = \n | publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]\n | ISBN = 0-19-563698-8\n}}\n* Sastri, Sivanath, ''Ramtanu Lahiri O Tatkalin Banga Samaj'' in Bengali (1903/2001), p 48, New Age Publishers Pvt. Ltd.\n* Sengupta, Subodh Chandra and Bose, Anjali (Ed), ''Sansad Bangali Charitabhidhan'' (Biographical dictionary) in Bengali (1976/1998), p 391, Sahitya Sansad. {{ISBN|81-85626-65-0}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060528210256/http://www.abasar.net/bk_main.asp?what=B00663 Biography] (in [[Bengali language|Bengali]] information website Abasar)\n\n{{Bengal Renaissance}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seal, Mutty Lall}}\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Bengali people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kolkata]]\n[[Category:1792 births]]\n[[Category:1854 deaths]]\n[[Category:Founders of Indian schools and colleges]]\n[[Category:19th-century philanthropists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|for=prose and grammar|date=April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Mutty Lall Seal\n| image        = Mutty_Lal_Seal.jpg\n| image_size   = 200px\n| caption      = Mutty Lall Seal\n| birth_date   = 1792\n| birth_place  = [[Kolkata]]\n| death_date   = 20 May 1854\n| death_place  = [[Kolkata]]\n| occupation   = Businessman\n| spouse       = \n| nationality  = Indian\n}}\n\n'''Mutty Lall Seal''' (also spelt '''Mutty Loll Seal''' or '''Mati Lall Seal''' or '''Motilal Seal''') (1792 \u2013 20 May 1854) was a businessman and philanthropist from [[India]]. Seal begin his life as a bottle and cork dealer but later became very wealthy. He donated large sums of his wealth to charity and education. Seal and [[Ramdulal Sarkar]], another renowned [[Business magnate|shipping magnate]], became part of the Bengali folklore as great merchant princes.<ref>Bhattacharya, Sabyasachi, ''Traders and Trades in Old Calcutta'', in ''Calcutta, the Living City'', Vol I, p 209.</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nMutty Lall Seal was born in a [[Bengali Hindu]] family in [[Kolkata|Calcutta]] (now Kolkata), 1792. His father Chaitanya Charan Seal, a [[cloth merchant]], died when Seal was just five years old. His early education began in a ''[[pathshala]] (Indian rural school);'' later he continued his studies at the Martin Bowl English School and the Baboo Nityananda Sen High School. \n\nIn 1809, at the age of seventeen, he was married to Nagri Dassee, the daughter of Mohan Chand Dey from the Surtir Bagan neighborhood of Kolkata. Seal accompanied his father-in-law on a pilgrimage to northern and western India and was said to be greatly enlightened by his spiritual experience on the journey. Around 1815, he started working at [[Fort William, India|Fort William]] and then the bastion of British power. While working at Fort William, he was involved in the supply of essential commodities to the British army. Later, he worked as an inspector for [[Indian Customs services|Indian Customs]] at [[Bali Khalk|Balikhal]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n==Achievements==\n\n===Business activities===\n[[File:Sketch of Mutty Lal Seal's residential house at Colootola.jpg|thumb|right|Sketch of Mutty Lall Seal's residential house at Colootola]]\nSeal started his business career by selling bottles and corks to Mr. Hudson, who was one of the most extensive importers of beer in those days.<ref>Mitra, Kissory Chand, ''Mutty Lall Seal'', Calcutta, 1869, p 5-6</ref> Mr. Hudson traded in [[Cowhide|cowhides]] and was the founder and promoter of the first indigo mart, which was established under the name of M/s. Moore, Hickey & Co. The English merchants used to hire Seal for his sound judgement on indigo, silk, sugar, rice, saltpeter, etc. He was appointed as \"Banian\" to around twenty first class agency houses out of around fifty or sixty such houses in Calcutta. Later he became a landed property speculator and merchant successively in partnership with Fergusson Brothers & Co., Oswald Seal & Co. and Tulloh & Co., and in these three firms he was said to have lost some thirty [[Lakh]] of [[Rupee|rupees]]. He got into exporting indigo, silk, sugar, rice, saltpeter to Europe and importing of iron and cotton-piece goods from England.<ref>Chakrabarty, Dipesh, ''The Colonial context of the Bengal Renaissance: A Note On Early Railway Thinking In Bengal'', in ''Indian Economic and Social History Review'', Vol. XI, No. 1, March 1974</ref> Seal acquired a number of [[Cargo ship|cargo boats]] which were then new to the market, worked the old flour mills, and shipped cargoes of biscuits to [[Australia]] for the first [[Emigration|emigrants]] to its newly discovered gold fields. Later, he put up a mill to refine sugar on the centrifugal principle.\n\nThe first to use steamships for internal trade in [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], he prospered in competition with Europeans. He owned around thirteen trade ships including a steam tug named 'Banian'. He made a fortune in a single generation through money-dealing, a phrase which does not merely refer to money-lending, bill discounting and other banking business. There was scarcely a speculation into which he did not enter, and for which he did not supply a portion of funds. From dealings in internal exchanges to contracts for station-building, for the erection of new bazaars, to the revival of transit companies, rare was an undertaking in which he was not an important, though quiet, shareholder. He funded every promising enterprise he found and made profits in the shape of interest.<ref>''Allen's Indian Mail, And Register Of Intelligence For British And Foreign India, China, And All Parts Of The East'', Vol XII, January\u2013December 1854, p 382</ref> At one point he was in complete control over the market dealing in company papers.<ref>Sastri, Sivanath, ''[[Ramtanu Lahiri O Tatkalin Bangasamaj]]'', p 71</ref> Seal was one of the founders of Assam Company Ltd.\n\nUnder his influence, the European-created Oriental Life Insurance Company (later reconstructed as New Oriental Insurance Company in 1834), the first life insurance company on Indian soil, began to underwrite Indian lives.<ref>Rungta, Radhe Shyam ''Rise of Business Corporations in India 1851\u20131900'', p 12-13</ref> He was among the founders of the Bank of India, and was on the board of the Agricultural And Horticultural Society of India.<ref>''Parbury's Oriental Herald And Colonial Intelligencer'', Vol II, July\u2013December 1838, p 28</ref><ref>''The Calcutta Monthly Journal And General Register of Occurrences Throughout The British Dominions in the East Forming An Epitome of the Indian Press'', For The Year 1836, Calcutta, p 204</ref> In time, he amassed as much wealth as [[Dwarkanath Tagore]] and Rustomjee Cowasjee. In 1878, Kishori Chand Mitra delivered a lecture on the life of Seal calling him the \"[[Rothschild]] of Calcutta\".<ref>Sarkar, Tanika, ''Hindu Wife, Hindu Nation'', p 34</ref> Pandith Sivanath Sastri wrote: \"He never adopted unfair means for earning money. He was well-behaved, polite and helpful to others.\"\n\n===Philanthropy===\nAs a philanthropist, Seal founded an alms house at [[Belgharia]] (in the suburbs of Calcutta) in 1841, where on average 500 people were fed daily,<ref>Banerjee, Prajnananda, ''Calcutta and Its Hinterland: A Study in Economic History of India, 1833\u20131900'', p 144\n</ref> and is still open to the poor. It has a bathing ''[[Ghats|ghat]]'' which exists today on the bank of the [[Hooghly River]] known as Motilal Ghat\n\nHe was well known as the donor of an extensive tract of land, which at the time was valued at Rs. 12,000,<ref>''Third Report of the Committee Appointed by the Right Honourable The Governour of Bengal for the Establishment of a Fever Hospital And For Inquiring into Local Management And Taxation in Calcutta, Calcutta: Bishop's College Press, 1847,'' p 35</ref> to the then British Government on which the [[Calcutta Medical College]] was built. The Government of Bengal recognized his liberality by naming a ward in his honor, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080511234715/http://www.medicalcollegekolkata.org/personalities.html ''The Mutty Lall Seal Ward''], for native male patients. Seal subsequently supplemented this gift by a donation of a lac of rupees for the establishment of a female (lying in) hospital which started functioning in 1838.<ref>''Missionary And Religious Intelligence'', in ''The Calcutta Christian Observer'', Vol. I, New Series, January\u2013December 1840, p 171</ref>\n\n[[Image:Mutty Lall Seal's Shrine - Belgharia - North 24 Parganas 2012-04-11 9732.JPG|thumb|right|250px|Mutty Lall Seal's shrine and almshouse on B T road]]\n\nIn those days the [[Hindus|Hindu]] community was alarmed, owing to several conversions to Christianity taking place among the boys at missionary schools offering free education. (Seal himself did partnership with Fergusson Brothers, they did not ask him to convert to [[Christianity]] to do business. Education was not provided for converting to Christianity, many of the people educated outside India at the time were Christians, including [[Mahatma Gandhi]].) To counter this, there was an anti-missionary movement led by the rich and influential [[Babu (title)|Babu]] of Calcutta for a free national school of their own. \n\nOne afternoon they all assembled in a meeting presided over by [[Radhakanta Deb|Raja Radha Kanta Deb]] at the [[Oriental Seminary]]. Many speeches were made and resolutions adopted, but donations recorded in the subscription book were scant. When the book passed to the hand of Seal, he immediately put down his name for one [[Lakh]] of rupees. Others who had estimated contributing a few hundred or a few thousand rupees panicked and the meeting ended.\n\nPledged to his subscription, Seal carried out the promise of a national institution with his own independent efforts. On Wednesday, 1 March 1842, a gathering of respectable people took place at his house for the formal opening of the Mutty Lall Seal's Free College. Among those present were Sir Lawrence Peel, the Chief Justice; Sir [[John Peter Grant]]; Mr. Lyall, the Advocate-General; Mr. Leith and the other principal members of the Calcutta Bar; Captain Birch, Superintendent of the Police; Mr. George Thompson; Right Reverend Dr. Carew; Baboo [[Dwarkanath Tagore]]; Baboo [[Ramkamal Sen]]; Baboo Russomoy Dutt and Revd. [[Krishna Mohan Banerjee]]. The Catholic Bishop and all the clergy of the Catholic Cathedral, as well as all the Professors of [[St. Xavier's College, Calcutta|St. Xavier's College]], were likewise present. Nearly the whole of the dissenting ministers and missionaries of Calcutta and its neighbourhood also attended.<ref>''The Catholic Cabinet, And Chronicle of Religious Intelligence, Containing Original And Selected Articles, A Monthly Periodical'', Volume I, 1843, p 187</ref> There were eloquent speeches in testimony to his noble generosity and liberal mindset with Mr. George Thompson complimenting him as \"a Hindu gentleman, who had nobly resolved to consecrate a large portion of the substances he had acquired by honorable exertion, to the intellectual improvement of the youth of his own nation to transmute his money into mind\"''.<ref>Mullick, Promatha Nath, ''History of Vaisyas of Bengal'', p 136-139</ref>''\n\nMutty Lall Seal's Free College (later renamed Mutty Lall Seal's Free School and College) was to provide for the education of Hindus to enable them to occupy posts of trust and emolument in their own country. This education included [[English Literature]], History, [[Geography]], [[Elocution]], Writing, [[Arithmetic]], [[Algebra]], Philosophical Sciences, [[Further Mathematics|Higher Mathematics]] and the practical application of Mathematics. The institution was opened free of cost, only one rupee was charged per month to cover expenses such as books and stationery and the surplus being expended towards furnishing the school with mathematical instruments. The number of students receiving education at one time was to be limited to 500. The institute was initially under the management of the Directors of the parent college of [[St. Xavier's College, Calcutta|St. F. Xavier]], Chowringhee, Calcutta, who furnished teachers to further the cause of [[secular education]].<ref>''Goethals News'', Vol. IV, No. 3 Bulletin, July \u2013 September 2001</ref>\n\nAlthough [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] had the responsibility of imparting education, the conductors had pledged themselves to withhold all Christian instruction from the pupils.<ref>''The Calcutta Review'', Vol. II, October\u2013December 1844, p 73</ref> However, later Seal dissolved the connection between his college and the Jesuits over a dispute that in violation of their pledge, viands were distributed among the Hindu boys contrary to their religious sentiments. The institute was then placed under Revd. [[Krishna Mohan Banerjee]].<ref>''The Indian Mail, A Monthly Register For British & Foreign India, China, & Australasia'', Vol. I, May\u2013December 1843, p 614-615</ref> A sum of Rs. 12,000 was spent yearly for the upkeep of the college from his trust. The college stood in high estimation of the public and competed successfully with the Government and Missionary Colleges in the university examinations ([[Suniti Kumar Chatterji]] and [[A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada|Swami Prabhupada]] were some students of the college). The college initially started functioning at Seal's house and was later shifted to the present building on [[Chittaranjan Avenue]] where it still exists.\n\nThe other charities which have made his name known to the public are contained in a deed of trust; by which he donated a considerable portion of his property (amounting to several [[Lakh]] of rupees) for the good of the public. A net yearly income of Rs. 36,000 derived from those properties were spent for various charitable purposes. Apart from running and maintaining the college, about Rs. 4,000 was spent on helping poor widows and orphans every year and for running and maintaining two alms houses for the poor and underprivileged.<ref>''The Calcutta Review'', Vol. CXI, Calcutta, 1900, p 86-88</ref> He extended financial support and co-operation for the establishment of the Hindu Charitable Institution and Hindu Metropolitan College. Seal's Free School, Hindu Metropolitan College and some of the other institutions of the time were calculated to offset the 'ill effects' of the liberal education offered at the [[Presidency College, Kolkata|Hindu College]].<ref>Majumdar, Swapan, ''Literature and Literary Life in Old Calcutta'', in ''Calcutta, the Living City'', Vol I, p 110.</ref>\n<gallery>\nImage:Mutty Lal Seal's devalaya at Belghoria.jpg|Devalaya at Mutty Lall Seal's Belghoria alms house\nImage:Mutty Lal Seal's guest house at Behala.jpg|Mutty Lall Seal's guest house at Behala\nImage:Mutty Lal Seal's bathing ghat.jpg|Mutty Lall Seal's bathing ghat on the bank of river Hooghly\nImage:Mutty Lal Seal's Free School.jpg|Mutty Lall Seal's Free School & College - Estd. 1842\n</gallery>\n\n==Later life==\nWhen he was alive, the native society of Kolkata was divided into two parts. One was the reformist section led by [[Ram Mohan Roy|Raja Rammohun Roy]] and the other was the conservative section led by [[Radhakanta Deb|Radha Kanta Deb]]. Most of the rich people of Kolkata were in the latter group. Deb strongly opposed both the move to ban [[Sati (practice)|sati]] and efforts for remarriage of widows, many of whom were child-widows. Although Seal was a conservative, he was in favor of Roy's efforts of banning sati, supported the cause of women's education as well as remarriage of widows. He made a public offer for a dowry of 1000 rupees to the person who should have the courage to break through the ancient prejudices of caste and marry a widow.<ref>Ripley, George, Dana, Charles A.,''The New American Cyclopaedia: A Popular Dictionary Of General Knowledge'', Vol. II, 1859, p 443</ref> When Seal died on 20 May 1854, his obituary in the ''Hindu Intelligence'' described him as the \"richest and most virtuous [[Babu (title)|Babu]] of Calcutta\".<ref>Sengupta, Nitish, ''History Of The Bengali Speaking People'', p 259-260</ref> One of the busy streets in Kolkata's business district is named after him as 'Moti Sil Street'.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Citation\n | surname1 = Chaudhuri \n | given1 = Sukanta (Ed)\n | year = 1995\n | title = Calcutta: The Living City\n | edition = \n | publisher= [[Oxford University Press]]\n | ISBN = 0-19-563698-8\n}}\n* Sastri, Sivanath, ''Ramtanu Lahiri O Tatkalin Banga Samaj'' in Bengali (1903/2001), p 48, New Age Publishers Pvt. Ltd.\n* Sengupta, Subodh Chandra and Bose, Anjali (Ed), ''Sansad Bangali Charitabhidhan'' (Biographical dictionary) in Bengali (1976/1998), p 391, Sahitya Sansad. {{ISBN|81-85626-65-0}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060528210256/http://www.abasar.net/bk_main.asp?what=B00663 Biography] (in [[Bengali language|Bengali]] information website Abasar)\n\n{{Bengal Renaissance}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Seal, Mutty Lall}}\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Bengali people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Kolkata]]\n[[Category:1792 births]]\n[[Category:1854 deaths]]\n[[Category:Founders of Indian schools and colleges]]\n[[Category:19th-century philanthropists]]\n", "name_user": "Katempurdon", "label": "safe", "comment": "Made minor edits to correct spelling and grammar mistakes.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutty_Lall_Seal"}
{"title_page": "Charles Moran (racing driver)", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2014}}\n'''Charles Moran Jr.''' (May 27, 1906 &ndash; June 7, 1978) was an [[United States|American]] [[racecar driver]] and managing partner of Francis I. DuPont, brokerage firm.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born in [[New York City]], son of Charles Moran, a naval historian, and Martha Adams.<ref name=\"Marquis1957\">{{cite book |title=Who's Who in Commerce and Industry |date=1957 |publisher=Marquis Who's Who |page=784 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WuMdAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=12 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe attended [[St. George's School, Newport|St. George's School]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]], and [[Princeton University]] before graduating from [[Columbia University]].<ref name=\"Marquis1957\"/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1928, driving a Rallye, he finished 4th in the 24-hour race at Baldoux, the Bol d'Or, driving the full 24 hours without relief. For the next year and a half he campaigned this car in Spa, San Sebastian, Madrid, Geisberg.<ref>LISCA News October 1960</ref> He was the first American to race at [[24 Hours of Le Mans|Le Mans]] in 1929, in a DuPont, with co-driver Alfredo Luis Miranda; he raced the same car at [[Indianapolis 500|Indianapolis]] in 1930 with George Reed in the mechanics seat.<ref>Hemmings ''Classic Car'', December 2014, p. 45</ref>\n\nIn 1932, he gave up racing, joined DuPont Motors as an engineer, and then moved to a related enterprise, the brokerage firm of Francis I. DuPont, where he became managing partner in the 1950s.   In 1949 he resumed racing, this time in sports cars ([[Bugatti]], [[MG Cars|MGs]], [[Briggs Cunningham|Cunninghams]], [[AC Bristol]], [[Lotus Cars|Lotus]], [[Ferrari]]) in [[Sports Car Club of America|SCCA]] events and again at Le Mans, with his [[Ferrari 212 Inter|Ferrari 212]] (1951, finishing 16th, 1952 DNF)<ref>http://www.experiencelemans.com</ref> and with his Cunningham C4Rx coupe, co-driver John Gordon Bennett (1953, finishing 10th).<ref>http://www.briggscunningham.com</ref>\n\nHe became Secretary of the Sports Car Club of America in 1952-3 and President in 1954-5.<ref>LISCA News October 1960</ref> He was a member of the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale du Sport Automobile|Commission Sportive Internationale]] and the American representative at the [[Federation Internationale d'Automobile]]. \n\nIn 1956 the [[American Automobile Association]] ended its relationship as the sole motorsport organization affiliated with the the F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile which governed international racing. As a result, the U.S. no longer had an association with FIA and hence no international racing licenses could be issued, international landspeed records could be certified, or US events be FIA sanctioned' which would put international drivers competing in them at risk of losing their FIA licenses.  Only Indy and Sebring retained their FIA licenses.\n\nMoran took it upon himself to organize the [[Automobile Competition Committee for the United States]] (ACCUS) to overcome rivalries between SCCA, USAC clubs and have one umbrella entity to work with the FIA.  He became the first president of ACCUS and managed it skillfully in its early years and led the negotiating with the FIA for US affiliation.  FIA recognized ACCUS in 1957.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lynch, Michael T., 1938-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/39281843|title=American sports car racing in the 1950s|date=1998|publisher=MBI Pub. Co|others=Edgar, William, 1933-, Parravano, Ron, 1948-|isbn=0-7603-0367-3|location=Osceola, WI|oclc=39281843}}</ref>\n\nHe chaired the Board of Trustees at St. George's School 1958-62.<ref>unpublished ms. by Charles Moran III, \"Recollections,\" written for family, 2012</ref>\n\n===Indy 500 results===\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Car\n!Start\n!Qual\n!Rank\n!Finish\n!Laps\n!Led\n!Retired\n|-\n![[1930 Indianapolis 500|1930]]\n|32\n|19\n|89.733\n|36\n|27\n|22\n|0\n|Crash T3\n|-\n|colspan=6|'''Totals'''\n|22\n|0\n|\n|}\n{{col-break|gap=1em}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Starts\n|1\n|-\n!Poles\n|0\n|-\n!Front Row\n|0\n|-\n!Wins\n|0\n|-\n!Top 5\n|0\n|-\n!Top 10\n|0\n|-\n!Retired\n|1\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 1936, he married Josephine D. Taylor, daughter of David H. Taylor of 875 [[Park Avenue]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"1936Wedding\">{{cite news |title=CHARLES MORAN JR. WEDS MISS TAYLOR; Ceremony Performed at Home of Bride's Parents, Mr. and Mrs. David H. Taylor. |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1936/02/12/88632454.pdf |accessdate=12 August 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 February 1936}}</ref> Together, they had two children:{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n* Charles Moran III (b. 1936), who served in the O.S.S.in England and France in 1944-5.<ref>Family Correspondence</ref>\n* David Taylor Moran (b. 1940).\n\nHe later married Hesteranne Primrose Butz; they had 3 children:{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n* Martha Adams Moran (b. 1962)\n* Amedee Depau Moran (b. 1963)\n* Helen Moran. Charles Moran Jr. \n\nMoran died on June 7, 1978 in [[Teasdale, Utah]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moran, Charles}}\n[[Category:20th-century American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis 500 drivers]]\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2014}}\n'''Charles Moran Jr.''' (May 27, 1906 &ndash; June 7, 1978) was an [[United States|American]] [[racecar driver]] and managing partner of Francis I. DuPont, brokerage firm.\n\n==Early life==\nHe was born in [[New York City]], son of Charles Moran, a naval historian, and Martha Adams.<ref name=\"Marquis1957\">{{cite book |title=Who's Who in Commerce and Industry |date=1957 |publisher=Marquis Who's Who |page=784 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WuMdAQAAIAAJ |accessdate=12 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe attended [[St. George's School, Newport|St. George's School]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]], and [[Princeton University]] before graduating from [[Columbia University]].<ref name=\"Marquis1957\"/>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1928, driving a Rallye, he finished 4th in the 24-hour race at Baldoux, the Bol d'Or, driving the full 24 hours without relief. For the next year and a half he campaigned this car in Spa, San Sebastian, Madrid, Geisberg.<ref>LISCA News October 1960</ref> He was the first American to race at [[24 Hours of Le Mans|Le Mans]] in 1929, in a DuPont, with co-driver Alfredo Luis Miranda; he raced the same car at [[Indianapolis 500|Indianapolis]] in 1930 with George Reed in the mechanics seat.<ref>Hemmings ''Classic Car'', December 2014, p. 45</ref>\n\nIn 1932, he gave up racing, joined DuPont Motors as an engineer, and then moved to a related enterprise, the brokerage firm of Francis I. DuPont, where he became managing partner in the 1950s.   In 1949 he resumed racing, this time in sports cars ([[Bugatti]], [[MG Cars|MGs]], [[Briggs Cunningham|Cunninghams]], [[AC Bristol]], [[Lotus Cars|Lotus]], [[Ferrari]]) in [[Sports Car Club of America|SCCA]] events and again at Le Mans, with his Ferrari 212 Inter|Ferrari 212]] (1951, finishing 16th, 1952 DNF)<ref>http://www.experiencelemans.com</ref> and with his Cunningham C4Rx coupe, co-driver John Gordon Bennett (1953, finishing 10th).<ref>http://www.briggscunningham.com</ref>\n\nHe became Secretary of the Sports Car Club of America in 1952-3 and President in 1954-5.<ref>LISCA News October 1960</ref> He was a member of the [[Commission Sportive Internationale]] and the American representative at the [[Federation Internationale d'Automobile]]. \n\nIn 1956 the [[American Automobile Association]] ended its relationship as the sole motorsport organization affiliated with the the F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile which governed international racing. As a result, the U.S. no longer had an association with FIA and hence no international racing licenses could be issued, international landspeed records could be certified, or US events be FIA sanctioned' which would put international drivers competing in them at risk of losing their FIA licenses.  Only Indy and Sebring retained their FIA licenses.\n\nMoran took it upon himself to organize the [[American Competition Committee for the United States]] (ACCUS) to overcome rivalries between SCCA, USAC clubs and have one umbrella entity to work with the FIA.  He became the first president of ACCUS and managed it skillfully in its early years and led the negotiating with the FIA for US affiliation.  FIA recognized ACCUS in 1957.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lynch, Michael T., 1938-|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/39281843|title=American sports car racing in the 1950s|date=1998|publisher=MBI Pub. Co|others=Edgar, William, 1933-, Parravano, Ron, 1948-|isbn=0-7603-0367-3|location=Osceola, WI|oclc=39281843}}</ref>\n\nHe chaired the Board of Trustees at St. George's School 1958-62.<ref>unpublished ms. by Charles Moran III, \"Recollections,\" written for family, 2012</ref>\n\n===Indy 500 results===\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-break}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Car\n!Start\n!Qual\n!Rank\n!Finish\n!Laps\n!Led\n!Retired\n|-\n![[1930 Indianapolis 500|1930]]\n|32\n|19\n|89.733\n|36\n|27\n|22\n|0\n|Crash T3\n|-\n|colspan=6|'''Totals'''\n|22\n|0\n|\n|}\n{{col-break|gap=1em}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Starts\n|1\n|-\n!Poles\n|0\n|-\n!Front Row\n|0\n|-\n!Wins\n|0\n|-\n!Top 5\n|0\n|-\n!Top 10\n|0\n|-\n!Retired\n|1\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Personal life==\nIn February 1936, he married Josephine D. Taylor, daughter of David H. Taylor of 875 [[Park Avenue]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=\"1936Wedding\">{{cite news |title=CHARLES MORAN JR. WEDS MISS TAYLOR; Ceremony Performed at Home of Bride's Parents, Mr. and Mrs. David H. Taylor. |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1936/02/12/88632454.pdf |accessdate=12 August 2019 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=12 February 1936}}</ref> Together, they had two children:{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n* Charles Moran III (b. 1936), who served in the O.S.S.in England and France in 1944-5.<ref>Family Correspondence</ref>\n* David Taylor Moran (b. 1940).\n\nHe later married Hesteranne Primrose Butz; they had 3 children:{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n* Martha Adams Moran (b. 1962)\n* Amedee Depau Moran (b. 1963)\n* Helen Moran. Charles Moran Jr. \n\nMoran died on June 7, 1978 in [[Teasdale, Utah]].{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moran, Charles}}\n[[Category:20th-century American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis 500 drivers]]\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "InfoArchivist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Correct Wikipedia articles links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Moran_(racing_driver)"}
{"title_page": "Peyton List (actress, born 1998)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|American actress and model}}\n{{For|the actress from ''[[FlashForward]]'' and ''[[Mad Men]]''|Peyton List (actress, born 1986<!--This refers to another actress - please don't change the year-->)}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Peyton List\n| image              = Peyton Roi List.JPG\n| alt                = Portrait image of Peyton List\n| caption            = List in 2013\n| birth_name         = Peyton Roi List\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1998|4|6}22}\n| birth_place        = [[Florida]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Actress\n* model\n<!-- Please DO NOT list \"singer\" unless/until she meets the notability guidelines for that, per WP:NSINGER -->\n}}\n| years_active       = 2002\u2013present\n| relatives          = [[Spencer List]] (twin brother)\n}}\n\n'''Peyton Roi List'''<ref name=\"Hollywood.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/peyton-roi-list-58405847/ |title=Peyton Roi List |website=Hollywood.com |accessdate=June 15, 2018 |archivedate=August 14, 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814164943/http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/peyton-roi-list-58405847/ |url-status=dead}}</ref> (born April 6, 1998<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900077&type=list|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616173906/http://www.disneychannelmedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=900077&type=list|title=Peyton List|work=[[Disney Channel]]|archivedate=June 16, 2012|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref>) is an American actress and model. List appeared in various films and television episodes as a young child and modeled for [[tween]] magazines and companies. In 2011, she joined the cast of ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' as Emma Ross, the eldest of four siblings that are being cared for by a young nanny. In 2015, she reprised the role in the spinoff series ''[[Bunk'd]]''. She is also recognized for playing [[Greg Heffley#Holly Hills|Holly Hills]] in the [[Diary of a Wimpy Kid (film series)|''Diary of a Wimpy Kid'' film series]], and for the role of [[List of The Karate Kid characters#Tory|Tory]] in the television series ''[[Cobra Kai]]''. She also starred as Ellie O'Brien in the 2016 Disney Channel Original Movie ''[[The Swap (2016 film)|The Swap]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nList was born April 6, 1998.<ref name=\"Hollywood.com\"/> She has two brothers, her twin [[Spencer List|Spencer]],<ref name=TribuneChronicle>{{cite web|first = Andy | last = Gray | newspaper = [[Tribune Chronicle]] |url=http://www.tribtoday.com/page/content.detail/id/554977/Peyton-List-is-no-wimpy-kid.html|title=Peyton List is no wimpy kid | location = Warren, Ohio |date=March 28, 2011 |accessdate=June 15, 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712143223/http://www.tribtoday.com/page/content.detail/id/554977/Peyton-List-is-no-wimpy-kid.html|archivedate=July 12, 2015|url-status=dead|url-access=subscription }}</ref> and a younger brother,<ref name=TeenVogue>Keiser, Amanda. [http://www.teenvogue.com/gallery/peyton-list-room-makeover#7 \"Peyton List Just Got the Ultimate Room Makeover and We Have the Exclusive First Look!\"]. ''[[Teen Vogue]]''. Retrieved May 2, 2017.</ref> Phoenix, both of whom are actors.<ref name=TribuneChronicle/>\n\nShe attended The Carroll School (P.S. 58) for elementary school, and the New Voices School for Academic and Creative Arts (M.S. 443) for middle school, both in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lo|first1=Danica|title=Peyton List's Favorite New York City Hotspots|url=http://www.epicurious.com/archive/blogs/editor/2014/07/peyton-list-new-york-city.html|website=The Epicurious Blog|publisher=Conde Nast|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref> She attended [[Oak Park High School (California)|Oak Park High School]] in [[Oak Park, California]], where she graduated in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kowalski|first1=Kristine Hope|title=Class of 2016: Spencer and Peyton List Graduate High School|url=http://www.twistmagazine.com/posts/spencer-peyton-list-graduate-high-school-103529/photos/peyton-spencer-list-146083|website=Twist Magazine|publisher=Bauer Teen Group|accessdate=June 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\n{{Expand section|date=November 2019}}\nList first began acting with television and film appearances. She first made an uncredited appearance on the [[soap opera]] ''[[As the World Turns]]'' in 2002.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2004, she appeared on the television show ''[[All My Children]]'' as Bess, and in the same year made a cameo appearance in the feature film ''[[Spider-Man 2]]'', which was uncredited.<ref name=\":1\" /> She continued to appear in guest roles and cameos as well as making another uncredited appearance on the live show ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''{{Citation needed|date=November 2019}} until 2008, when she had her first major role in the feature film ''[[27 Dresses]]'', starring as the young version of the character Jane Nichols. The film was a commercial success,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl1229030913/?landingModalImageUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fm.media-amazon.com%2Fimages%2FG%2F01%2FIMDbPro%2Fimages%2Fhome%2FwelcomeToBomojov2._CB1571421611_.png|title=27 Dresses|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> and served as List\u2019s acting debut.\n\nList began to appear in more feature films, and in 2010 was cast in alongside [[Robert Pattinson]] in the film ''[[Remember Me (2010 film)|Remember Me]],'' as a girl who bullies Pattinson's character's little sister. The film was a box-office success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2859304449/?landingModalImageUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fm.media-amazon.com%2Fimages%2FG%2F01%2FIMDbPro%2Fimages%2Fhome%2FwelcomeToBomojov2._CB1571421611_.png|title=Remember Me|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> In the same year, List had begun her work with Disney, and appeared in the Disney film ''[[The Sorcerer's Apprentice (2010 film)|The Sorcerer's Apprentice]]'', which turned to be a [[box-office bomb]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl2540733953/?landingModalImageUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fm.media-amazon.com%2Fimages%2FG%2F01%2FIMDbPro%2Fimages%2Fhome%2FwelcomeToBomojov2._CB1571421611_.png|title=The Sorcerer's Apprentice|website=Box Office Mojo|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> She also was cast in [[Lifetime Movie Network]]'s ''[[Secrets in the Walls]]'', alongside [[Jeri Ryan]] and [[Kay Panabaker]].\n\nList starred in ''[[Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules (film)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules]]'' and ''[[Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days (film)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days]]''. She had a major role as Holly Hills, the crush of Greg. The cast, including List, had won a [[Young Artist Award]]. From 2011 to 2015, she starred as Emma Ross, the eldest of four children, on the Disney Channel series ''[[Jessie (2011 TV series)|Jessie]]'' alongside [[Debby Ryan]] and her ''Diary of a Wimpy Kid'' co-star [[Karan Brar]]. On February 25, 2015, it was announced that ''Jessie'' would end after its fourth season, and that List, along with Brar and [[Skai Jackson]], would reprise their roles in the spinoff series ''[[Bunk'd]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://deadline.com/2015/02/jessie-cancelled-spinoff-peyton-list-karan-brar-skai-jackson-disney-channel-1201380940/ |title=Disney Channel's 'Jessie' Ending Run, But Spinoff Series Set With Stars Peyton List, Karan Brar & Skai Jackson |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=February 25, 2015 |accessdate=February 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nList is an active member of the [[Disney Channel Circle of Stars]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fanlala.com/news/26-disney-channel-stars-sing-do-you-want-build-snowman-frozen|title=26 Disney channel stars sing do you want build snowman frozen|date=July 18, 2014 |accessdate=July 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Other ventures ==\n\n===Modeling===\n[[File:Peyton_R._List_at_27_Dresses_Premiere_1.jpg|right|thumb|Upright|List at the ''[[27 Dresses]]'' premiere in January 2008]]\nList was a 2011 model for [[Tween Brands|''Justice'' magazine]]. She has also appeared on the cover of the ''[[American Girl (magazine)|American Girl]]'''s 2009 Back to School issue.\n\nShe has appeared in over four hundred advertisements in various formats for various companies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kontrolgirl.com/2013/03/14/introducing-the-spring-issue-of-kontrol-girl-magazine-featuring-peyton-list-mindless-behavior/|title=Introducing... The Spring Issue of Kontrol Girl Magazine Featuring Peyton List & Mindless Behavior!|date=March 14, 2013|work=Kontrol Girl magazine|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://rockycoastnews.blogspot.com/2012/01/meet-insider-raising-actress.html|title=Rocky Coast News: MEET INSIDER: Raising Actress & Fashionable Peyton List|last=Mills|first=David|date=January 21, 2012|work=Meet Insider&nbsp;\u2013 Rocky Coast News|location=Maine|accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Singing ===\nShe performed with [[Ingrid Michaelson]] at one of Michaelson's concerts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/hot-pics/those-pants-tho-2015126|title=Hot Pics!-Those Pants Tho!|work=Us Weekly|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref> In 2018, List released her first single \"Liar Liar\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Actress-Peyton-List-Drops-New-Pop-Anthem-LIAR-LIAR-20181102|title=Actress Peyton List Drops New Pop Anthem LIAR LIAR|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|accessdate=January 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Namefellow==\nPeyton List shares the same name with a fellow actress, [[Peyton List (actress, born 1986)|Peyton List (born 1986)]].<ref name=\"saltman\">{{cite news |last1=Laura |first1=Saltman |title=A Tale Of Two Peytons: Jessie's Peyton List On Sharing Her Famous Name With Other Peyton List |url=https://www.yahoo.com/celebrity/news/tale-two-peytons-jessies-peyton-list-sharing-her-215829849.html |accessdate=November 20, 2019 |work=Access Hollywood |publisher=Yahoo News |date=October 14, 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170207024916/https://www.yahoo.com/celebrity/news/tale-two-peytons-jessies-peyton-list-sharing-her-215829849.html |archivedate=February 7, 2017}}</ref><ref name=nguyen>{{citation|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2016/10/peyton-list-frequency-swap-thinning-1201733445/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|work=[[IndieWire]]|title=Peyton List-icle: 6 Ways to Identify Which Peyton List Is Which|first=Hanh|last=Nguyen|date=October 5, 2016|quote='Peyton List is an American actress and model.' This Wikipedia description is accurate and true. The problem? It\u2019s true about two different people. That\u2019s right. Two Peyton Lists are working actresses and models. Two Peyton Lists are, um, listed on IMDb. Two Peyton Lists are currently on our TVs. Two Peyton Lists are confusing our Google searches. Two Peyton Lists are messing with our minds.}}</ref> The younger List was interviewed by ''[[Access Hollywood]]'', saying she uses '''Peyton R. List''' to avoid confusion.<ref name=saltman /> Union [[SAG-AFTRA]]'s policy avoids actors with the same name; this instance went unnoticed.<ref name=saltman/> They appeared in the same scene \u2014 when the older List starred on ''[[As the World Turns]]'' as Lucy Montgomery.<ref name=saltman /><ref name=\":1\">{{citation|url=http://heavy.com/entertainment/2016/10/peyton-list-disney-channel-star-bunkd-who-plays-emma-ross-the-swap-jessie-twin-brother-age-family-movies-photos/|accessdate=November 29, 2016|website=[[Heavy.com]]|title=Peyton List, Disney Channel Star: 5 Fast Facts You Need to Know|date=October 7, 2016|first=Daniel S.|last=Levine}}</ref> Years later, the younger List cited confusion when they stayed at the same hotel \u2014 they received [[daily call sheet]]s and [[voicemail]]s for each other.<ref name=saltman/> ''[[IndieWire]]'' noted the confusion appeared on the website [[Wikipedia]], where both actresses's articles started out with exactly the same introduction text of: \"Peyton List is an American actress and model.\"<ref name=nguyen/>\n\n==Personal life==\nAs of March 2011, List lived with her family in New York.<ref name=TribuneChronicle/> The family had moved to Los Angeles by the time List was 16.<ref name=TeenVogue/>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Film performances\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Spider-Man 2]]''\n| Little girl playing on steps\n| Uncredited<ref>{{cite web|title=The Cast of Disney's Jessie talk about swinging by Marvel's Ultimate Spider-Man|url=http://marvel.com/news/tv/23486/the_cast_of_disneys_jessie_talk_about_swinging_by_marvels_ultimate_spider-man_web-warriors|publisher=Marvel|accessdate=August 9, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[27 Dresses]]''\n| Young Jane Nichols\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[Confessions of a Shopaholic (film)|Confessions of a Shopaholic]]''\n| Shoestore girl #2\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[3 Backyards]]''\n| Emily\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Remember Me (2010 film)|Remember Me]]''\n| Samantha\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''{{sortname|The|Sorcerer's Apprentice|dab=2010 film}}''\n| Young Becky\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Bereavement (film)|Bereavement]]''\n| Wendy Miller\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| style=\"white-space:nowrap;\" | ''[[Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules (film)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Rodrick Rules]]''\n| Holly Hills\n|\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Something Borrowed (film)|Something Borrowed]]''\n| Young Darcy Rhone\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''{{sortname|The|Trouble with Cali}}''\n| Young Cali Bluejones\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days (film)|Diary of a Wimpy Kid: Dog Days]]''\n| Holly Hills\n| [[34th Young Artist Awards|Young Artist Award for Best Performance in a Feature Film&nbsp;\u2013 Young Ensemble Cast]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms34.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130403013454/http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms34.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=April 3, 2013 |title=34th Annual Young Artist Awards \u2013 Nominations |publisher=[[Young Artist Award]]s |accessdate=February 1, 2015 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''{{sortname|The|Seventh Dwarf}}''\n| Princess Rose\n| Voice role\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Thinning]]''\n| Laina Michaels\n| <ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/digital/news/logan-paul-peyton-list-the-thinning-legendary-1201643508/|title=Digital Star Logan Paul, Peyton List Topline \u2018The Thinning\u2019 Thriller from Legendary Digital (EXCLUSIVE)|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=November 18, 2015|accessdate=February 14, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''{{sortname|The|Outcasts|dab=2017 film}}''\n| Mackenzie\n| Originally titled ''The Outskirts''; scheduled for a 2015 release, but held until 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/swen-group-distribution-victoria-justice-outcasts-exclusive-1202004189/|title=Swen Group Moves Into U.S. Distribution With Victoria Justice\u2019s \u2018Outcasts\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=March 8, 2017|accessdate=March 8, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[The Thinning: New World Order]]''\n| Laina Michaels\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''[[Then Came You (2018 film)|Then Came You]]''\n| Ashley\n|\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Batman: Hush (film)|Batman: Hush]]''\n| [[Barbara Gordon|Barbara Gordon / Batgirl]]\n| Voice role<ref>{{cite web |last1=Vejvoda |first1=Jim |title=Batman: Hush Movie - Exclusive First Look Photo and Voice Cast News |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2019/03/27/batman-hush-exclusive-first-look-photo-and-voice-cast-news |website=[[IGN]] |date=March 27, 2019 |accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Valley Girl (2020 film)|Valley Girl]]''\n| Courtney\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/06/valley-girl-